<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SuddenAcceleration     07-26 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudden Acceleration,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercedes Sudden Accleration Probe Expanded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300,000 Mercedes-Benz automobiles
are under investigation to determine if hundreds of reports of
unintended acceleration are true, the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration says.
   The agency said Monday it had broadened its probe into
allegations that the vehicles speed up without the operator's
intervention to encompass 309,000 cars made by Mercedes from 1984
through 1988. The cars are all equipped with gasoline engines and
automatic transmissions.
   NHTSA in October had begun an investigation into 42,353
1986-1987 Mercedes Model 124 300E cars. The new engineering
analysis broadens the regulatory case to include the Mercedes
models 107 SL, 126 SE, SEL and SEC, and 201 190E.
   NHTSA said it has received reports of 301 instances of sudden
acceleration in the Mercedes cars. The agency said 217 of the
instances reportedly resulted in accidents that injured 92 people
and killed one person.
   Mercedes-Benz of North America will cooperate fully with the
NHTSA investigation, said A.B. Schuman, a spokesman for the company
in Montvale, N.J.
   He said in the company's investigation of 283
sudden-acceleration reports, ``our technicians have never found any
electrical, electronic or mechanical defect in our cars that could
cause unintended acceleration.''
   The Mercedes case is among six NHTSA investigations into alleged
sudden acceleration involving at least 4.8 million vehicles. Other
makers and the number of vehicles involved are Ford Motor Co., 3.2
million; General Motors Corp., 800,000; Audi, 255,000; Nissan,
183,000; and Honda, 62,500.
   The Mercedes investigation was opened at the request of the
Center for Auto Safety, a consumer group often at odds with the
auto industry and its regulators.
   ``The steady increase in sudden acceleration incidents in
numerous Mercedes models other than the 1986-87 300E demonstrates
that Mercedes' entire line of recent-year gasoline engine cars with
automatic transmissions is affected by this defect,'' the center
said.
   The center said it had received 164 reports of sudden
acceleration in Mercedes cars, resulting in 125 accidents, 46
injuries and one death.
</TEXT>
