<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     07-26 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Roger Rabbit' on Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business is booming at the nation's movie
theaters this summer with hits like ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit''
producing revenues running well ahead of last year's record $4.2
billion take.
   ``The business is really rolling along. It's got momentum
because there's variety, a selection for every taste,'' John Krier
of Exhibitor Relations Co. said Monday.
   With the completion of eight weeks of the traditionally rich
summer season, more than $934 million worth of tickets have been
sold, 13 percent more than for the period last year.
   The industry trade paper Daily Variety said when all the
receipts are tallied the summer box office may reach $1.7 billion
compared with $1.59 billion a year ago.
   Analysts attributed the revenue gains to the diversity of this
summer's films _ ranging from mindless comedies, animated and
partially-animated films and violent, action-packed fare.
   ``When you have many popular films, you have a great summer,''
said Variety's Art Murphy. ``You notice there are no films that did
$10 million or more. That's because there is competition. It's the
quality of product.''
   Steven Spielberg's collaboration with Disney, ``Who Framed Roger
Rabbit,'' featuring the technological wizardry of live and animated
characters, regained the No. 1 position at the nation's box offices
last weekend with a take of $8.9 million.
   It nudged out last week's top film ``Coming to America.'' The
second-place Eddie Murphy film earned $8.8 million, just $33,000
shy of the leader.
   Bruce Willis' ``Die Hard'' was third, Clint Eastwood's ``Dead
Pool'' was fourth, the Robert DeNiro-Charles Grodin comedy
``Midnight Run'' was fifth and the re-release of the 46-year-old
Disney classic ``Bambi'' was sixth.
   The mindless ``Big Top Pee-wee'' faired poorly in its debut,
bringing in $4.6 million to place seventh, and ``Caddyshack II''
was eighth with $4.4 million.
   The Tom Hanks hit ``Big,'' placing ninth, maintained its stature
after eight weeks of release by adding $3.9 million in receipts for
a total gross of $75.2 million. ``Bull Durham'' rounded out the top
10 with $2.4 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $8.92 million, 1,402
screens, $6,362 per screen, $84.1 million, five weeks, $40 million.
   2. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $8.89 million, 2,064
screens, $4,305 per screen, $81.2 million, four weeks, $20 million.
   3. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $7.1 million, 1,276 screens,
$5,569 per screen, $10.1 million, two weeks, n-a.
   4. ``The Dead Pool,'' Warner Bros., $6.0 million, 1,831 screens,
$3,285 per screen, $23.1 million, two weeks, $18 million.
   5. ``Midnight Run,'' Universal, $5.5 million, 1,158 screens,
$4,775 per screen, $7.1 million, one week, n-a.
   6. ``Bambi,'' Disney, $5.3 million, 1,489 screens, $3,570 per
screen, $18.3 million, two weeks, $2 million (in 1942).
   7. ``Big Top Pee-wee,'' Paramount, $4.6 million, 1,256 screens,
$3,682 per screen, $4.6 million, one week, n-a.
   8. ``Caddyshack II,'' Warner Bros., $4.4 million, 1,556 screens,
$2,851 per screen, $4.4 million, one week, n-a.
   9. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.9 million, 1,276 screens,
$3,060 per screen, $75.3 million, eight weeks, $15 million.
   10. ``Bull Durham,'' Orion, $2.4 million, 1,019 screens, $2,371
per screen, $36.3 million, six weeks, $12 million.
</TEXT>
