<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     07-26 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Sticking To Statehouse Duties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is maintaining his hybrid schedule
of Statehouse duties and presidential campaigning by tending to
gubernatorial tasks today, including a law-and-order event.
   Dukakis was spending most of today at the office, with a visit
to a new police post at a downtown subway stop to swear in six new
members of the state transit authority police force.
   The Massachusetts governor spent all of Monday at the
Statehouse, putting aside state business for an hour-long meeting
with Hungarian Prime Minister Karoly Grosz before the communist
leader headed to Washington to meet President Reagan.
   Wednesday also was to be a Statehouse day for Dukakis, who kicks
off an eight-state campaign swing Thursday.
   Dukakis kept a low profile Monday, refusing to comment as he
walked Grosz out of his office to an elevator surrounded by
reporters.
   Grosz is the first East European communist party leader to come
to the United States in 10 years and the first Hungarian leader to
visit this country in more than 40 years.
   At the top of Dukakis' state agenda is legislative unrest with
some of the $138 million in planned spending Dukakis vetoed from
the state's fiscal 1989 budget. Some lawmakers, irate over the
slashing of $91 million in local aid, have asked the legislative
leadership to halt a summer recess so they can attempt to override
the vetoes.
   ``Not to worry _ all is well,'' Dukakis said when asked Monday
afternoon to discuss a meeting between the administration's top
budget officer and House Speaker George Keverian.
   Dukakis' schedule this week fits with his primary season
practice of spending Monday through Wednesday at the Statehouse
before heading out to campaign. He is expected to continue that
pattern through much of the general election campaign.
   The tentative schedule for this week's trip includes stops in
New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan, Missouri, Illinois,
Wisconsin and North Carolina.
   Dukakis' running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, took a weekend
campaign trip with Dukakis but was not scheduled to campaign with
the governor this week.
</TEXT>
