<2ND_LINE>AM-Counterfeit Indictment,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counterfeit Indictment Names Former Police Chief, Supremacist
Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-time police chief, a former white
supremacist leader and three other men have been charged in what
prosecutors say was a scheme to pass $100,000 in counterfeit money
to raise money for paramilitary organizations.
   The federal indictment revealed Monday accuses James P.
Wickstrom, 45, with attempting to buy conterfeit $20 and $50 bills
through Victor F. Rizzo, a chiropractor in Cambria County, about 70
miles east of Pittsburgh.
   Wickstrom, who was arrested June 24, is a former leader of the
supremacist group, Posse Comitatus.
   At a hearing June 29, Secret Service agent Thomas Reddington
said Wickstrom planned to pass the fake bills for genuine currency
overseas to help support right-wing, paramilitary organizations.
   Also named in the six-count indictment was David F. Gardner, 44,
who was police chief in Youngstown, about 35 miles southeast of
Pittsburgh, from 1980 to 1983; and Thomas M. Ryan, 29, of Dublin,
Ireland, who was staying with Rizzo and was identified as his
driver.
   The indictment charges them with conspiracy, counterfeiting and
firearms violations.
   The fifth man named in the indictment, Harry Luttner of Latrobe,
is in Westmoreland County prison on state burglary charges. He is
accused of providing paper for the production of phony bills.
   Gardner now works as a paramilitary instructor, according to
documents prepared for his appearance before a federal magistrate
after his arrest Monday. He was released on $5,000 bond. He is
accused of agreeing to provide armed protection when the phony
money was purchased.
   Rizzo and Ryan were arrested June 22 when Rizzo took delivery of
counterfeit bills from an undercover Secret Service agent. They are
free on $10,000 bond.
   Wickstrom, who has been in custody since his arrest June 24,
served a 13-month prison sentence in Wisconsin for Posse-related
activities. He lives in Homer City, about 45 miles east of
Pittsburgh. Authorities claim he began a branch of the
white-supremacist Christian Identity Church in that town.
</TEXT>
