<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonDisturbance 4thLd-Writethru a0667 07-26 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Disturbance, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0667,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Injuries Reported in Maryland Penitentiary Disturbance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with number of injured guards
now put at eight, sted seven; governor meeting with prison
officials, picking up 4th graf pvs, `Shipley said...'. SUBS grafs
10 and 11, `Two guards...,' to update with detail on injuries to
guards and psychologist. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `The problem...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disturbances broke out among inmates at a
maximum-security prison, injuring eight guards, a prison
psychologist and three inmates, authorities said.
   ``It appears to be under control,'' Luther Starnes, assistant
press secretary to Gov. William Donald Schaefer, said about an hour
after ambulances were sent to the Maryland Penitentiary in downtown
Baltimore.
   State Police spokesman Cpl. Greg Shipley said no prisoners
escaped.
   Schaefer met Monday night with the prison warden and state
prison officials, and said afterward that he was satisfied with
their handling of the disturbance.
   Shipley said the disturbance began in the recreation yard
shortly before 1 p.m, spread to a crisis clinic where the
psychologist was having a session with inmates, and erupted again
in another section of the yard. He said a minor fire also was set
in the clinic.
   Baltimore police carrying shotguns immediately surrounded the
perimeter of the prison, and a police helicopter flew overhead.
Several downtown streets were blocked off, causing traffic backups.
   Prison officials did not know the reason for the three incidents
and do not think they were organized, Shipley said.
   Two homemade knives were recovered, and several gunshots also
were fired, he said.
   Officials said the prison immediately was ``locked down,'' with
inmates locked in their cells.
   Two inmates, one in critical condition and one in fair, were
being treated for gunshot wounds, said Anita Hisley, spokeswoman
for Johns Hopkins Hospital. The third inmate was being treated at
the prison hospital, which handles less-serious injuries, officials
said.
   One of the eight injured guards suffered a gunshot wound to the
neck, but authorities believe he may have been wounded by another
officer during the melee. He and two other guards were
hospitalized, while the others were treated and released.
   The psychologist was treated for facial injuries and released.
   The problem apparently resulted from an altercation that
possibly followed an aborted escape attempt, said Bill Bowlander,
executive director of Council 92 of the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, which represents
correctional officers.
   The penitentiary, which opened in 1811, ordinarily holds 700 to
800 men, but Monday's inmate count was 1,270. Eighteen of its
inmates are on death row.
</TEXT>
