<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     07-26 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte Lauds Peace Plan; Rebels Attack Bowling Alley In San
Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
called a Central American peace plan a regional ``declaration of
independence'' but accused Nicaragua of not fulfilling obligations
under the year-old effort.
   Also Monday, guerrillas set fire to a bowling alley in the
capital to retaliate after police dispersed an anti-government
march, the manager said.
   No one was reported hurt and no group claimed responsibility for
the attack.
   Duarte, 62, appeared energetic Monday during his first news
conference since he returned to El Salvador July 11 after six weeks
of medical treatment in the United States. He is suffering from
terminal liver cancer and doctors give him six to 18 months more to
live.
   Duarte accused Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government of not
adhering to terms of the peace plan signed Aug. 7 in Guatemala by
the five Central American presidents.
   The plan calls for negotiations between governments and
insurgents to end civil wars in Nicaragua, El Salvador and
Guatemala. It also calls for amnesties for politically motivated
crimes, moves toward democratization and a ban on outside support
for guerrilla movements.
   The plan ``has fulfilled many of its objectives and must be
considered a declaration of principles and, for me, it has been a
second declaration of independence for Central America,'' Duarte
said.
   ``In the short term, some of the plan's objectives have been
fulfilled, and some have not been fulfilled,'' he said, without
elaborating.
   ``Nicaragua, in signing (the accord), made an appearance of
trying to put it into practice, but obviously that put it into
confrontation with democracy,'' he added.
   Duarte accused the Sandinistas of supporting leftist Salvadoran
guerrillas battling his U.S.-backed government.
   Duarte's government declared an amnesty for political crimes and
lifted a state of emergency to comply with the peace initiative.
But there have been no talks between the government and rebels
since October.
   The foreign ministers of Guatemala, El Salvador, Costa Rica and
Honduras meet Aug. 1 in Guatemala City with U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz to discuss the plan's achievements and shortcomings.
   Duarte said there are no plans for a meeting of presidents to
mark the initiative's first anniversary.
   Meanwhile, 10 to 12 masked men with pistols and at least one
submachine gun set fire to a bowling alley after taking money from
about 30 patrons and identifying themselves as ``urban commandos''
of the Faribundo Marti Liberation Front, said Guillermo Castro,
manager of the Bolerama Jardin.
   The front, a coalition of five guerrilla groups, has waged an
8-year-old war against the government.
   Castro said the guerrillas took ``money they said was a
`contribution' to the cause. They said the attack was in reprisal
for the government's repression of Thursday's march.''
   The guerrillas then doused several pool tables in a room
adjoining the main bowling area with gasoline and set them afire,
Castro said.
   Firefighters arrived within 15 minutes and extinguished the
blaze.
   Castro said none of the bowling alley's owners has any
connection with the government and that he did not understand why
the business was targeted.
   On Thursday last week, police used tear gas and fired shots in
the air to break up an anti-government demonstration in San
Salvador. Protesters then burned at least nine vehicles.
   Human rights groups estimate more than 65,000 people have been
killed in El Salvador since the civil war began in October 1979.
</TEXT>
