<HEAD>Judge Scheduled Impeachment Trial For `Voodoo Mayor'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has scheduled an impeachment
trial for an 85-year-old mayor who last week donned a turban and
rubber snakes while declaring ``National Voodoo Week.''
   But an attorney for Florala Mayor H.T. Mathis said the trial is
moot because the mayor's four-year term ends Oct. 3.
   ``Really I think he is more interested in clearing his name than
anything else,'' said attorney James Prestwood.
   Covington County Circuit Judge William Baldwin on Monday refused
to dismiss charges of neglect of duty, corruption and incompetency,
and set an Aug. 29 trial date.
   Last week, while clad in a turban and rubber snakes, Mathis
proclaimed ``National Voodoo Week'' at a midnight news conference
on the steps of the county courthouse.
   The mayor said ``National Voodoo Week'' was aimed at promoting
publicity for the town and peace among the residents.
   Attorney General Don Siegelman has accused Mathis of
mismanagement and improperly pardoning about two dozen drunken
drivers in Florala, a town of about 2,200 residents on the
Alabama-Florida border.
   Mathis has said he has pardoned numerous DUI convictions because
of what he calls overzealous police officers.
   Siegelman said Mathis' ``voodoo antics'' may be an issue at the
trial.
   Mathis said Siegelman had no right to ask a judge to empanel the
county grand jury that returned the impeachment recommendation.
   Prestwood said he was ``absolutely optimistic'' that Mathis
would be found innocent at the impeachment trial, but may seek a
delay to prepare for the trial.
