<1ST_LINE>u a AM-InsulationDanger     07-26 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insulation Danger,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Investigating Wiring Insulation at Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is
re-evaluating the use of a wiring insulation found in most U.S.
nuclear power plants after discovering damaged electrical circuits
at several facilities, according to a published report.
   Uldis Potapovs, chief of the commission's unit that inspects
vendor-supplied plant equipment, said the insulating material known
as Kapton appears to damage easily under mechanical stress and even
in routine handling by plant maintenance crews, the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram reported in Tuesday's editions.
   Worn or damaged Kapton has been discovered on electrical wires
that connect reactor containment buildings with main-plant control
circuits located outside the reactor, Potapovs told the newspaper.
   He said such damage is a ``significant concern'' because it
could cause erroneous equipment readings or failure of equipment,
but there has never been a failure serious enough to produce a fire.
   Kapton can be found on wiring in most of the nation's 104
operating nuclear power plants, Potapovs said.
   Kapton, made by E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co., is a thin,
lightweight insulation often used to wrap wiring in
high-performance aircraft. It has been cited as a factor in dozens
of aircraft fires and is suspected of contributing to dozens more,
the Star-Telegram has reported in a series of stories this week.
   Du Pont has long maintained that its insulation does not crack
or break any sooner than other insulation.
   The U.S. Navy, which has banned Kapton in its aircraft, says the
material deteriorates prematurely, cracks easily and even explodes
under certain conditions.
   But other Kapton users, including the Air Force and most
commercial aircraft builders, say the insulation is the best on the
market for the job.
   Asked if the NRC might call for a ban on Kapton in nuclear
plants, Potapovs said, ``That certainly would be a possibility.''
   But Potapovs added that it seems more likely that the agency
will issue a non-binding notice to plant operators recommending
that Kapton wires be reinforced with a sleeve or coating and that
maintenance crews be instructed in how to best handle the material.
   The NRC has already issued one notice dealing with Kapton
problems at nuclear power plants, agency records show. The agency
reported Feb. 4, 1987, that wires wrapped with Kapton had shorted
out because of ``insulation degradation'' on two occasions at
separate plants.
   The wires were in small electric motors that regulated the
opening and closing of steam supply valves at the plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
