<DOCNO> AP880726-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerLinks Bjt   07-26 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Links, Bjt,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Gene Linked To Breast And Lung Cancers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gene found to be defective in a rare
eye cancer has been linked to breast cancer and a common form of
lung cancer, researchers say.
   The gene was the first of a new group of anti-cancer genes that
normally protect against cancer but allow cancer to appear when
defective, said Ray White of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute at
the University of Utah in Salt Lake City.
   Similar anti-cancer genes now have also been linked to colon
cancer, another common and lethal form of cancer.
   The findings that the gene is linked to breast cancer and
so-called small-cell lung cancer suggest that it and other
anti-cancer genes could play a major role in many types of human
cancer, White told genetics students at the Jackson Laboratory in
Bar Harbor on Monday.
   Identifying those genes and determining how they go wrong does
not mean cancer will then be eliminated, White said. But the
understanding of these genetic abnormalities is crucial to
ultimately being able to wipe out cancer, he said.
   Over the shorter term, he said, understanding the genetics of
cancer might allow doctors to diagnose subtypes of common cancers
and learn to treat them better.
   The gene was identified in children with a rare eye cancer known
as retinoblastoma. White and Webster Cavenee at the Ludwig
Institute for Cancer Research in Montreal were among the scientists
who made that initial discovery and learned how the gene worked.
   Later, those retinoblastoma children were found to develop
osteosarcoma, a bone cancer, also as a result of defects in the
retinoblastoma gene.
   More recently, researchers at the University of California, San
Francisco, led by Wen-Hwa Lee and Eva Lee, have found that the gene
is defective in certain breast cancer cells grown in the laboratory.
   About the same time, Frederic Kaye and colleagues at the
National Cancer Institute-Navy Medical Oncology Branch reported
seeing retinoblastoma gene defects in small-cell lung cancer cells
in the laboratory.
   ``It may well be that the majority of small-cell lung cancers
involve a lesion in the retinoblastoma gene as well as several
others,'' said White.
   Retinoblastoma affects perhaps 1,000 Americans annually, but
small-cell lung cancer strikes 30,000 people in the United States
every year, and breast cancer strikes 130,000.
   Suddenly, a gene that was important only in a rare disease is
now seen to be significant in two of the most important and most
devastating human cancers.
   Meanwhile, White had identified a similar anti-cancer gene in a
rare form of inherited colon cancer.
   He said Monday he has now shown that this anti-cancer gene plays
a role in the much more common non-inherited form of colon cancer
that is another one of the country's leading cancer killers.
   Bert Vogelstein of the Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine in Baltimore also has identified several other genetic
defects associated with colon cancer.
   He estimated that perhaps as many as seven genetic defects must
occur for colon cancer to develop. He said he and White have now
identified five of those defects.
   ``You can look at these genetic alterations as the causes of
cancer _ just as you can look at bacteria as the causes of
infection,'' Vogelstein said in a telephone interview. ``Except
it's more complicated in cancer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-26 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG EATON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Rose thought a clump of grass
got caught in his car's suspension during a camping trip. But he
was in for a surprise when he tried to remove the object.
   ``I touched it and it moved _ and then I moved, too!'' Rose, 33,
said Monday. ``I thought it was a snake or something.''
   The ``grass'' turned out to be a hedgehog, a small, spiny,
porcupine-like mammal. The hedgehog hitched 350 miles underneath
the car last weekend before Rose found the prickly little beast
curled up in the suspension.
   ``I thought it was grass,'' Rose said.
   Rose said he found the hedgehog while cleaning the car and his
camping trailer after a seven-hour drive from Cornwall, in
southwestern England, to Long Eaton, near Nottingham in the north.
   ``I dropped a screwdriver under the car,'' he said. ``The
hedgehog really surprised me.''
   Rose, a sheet-metal worker, dismantled the suspension and
removed the frightened animal, taking care not to touch it. He fed
the ``ravenous'' little creature cat food and milk.
   The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty of Animals later
picked up the hedgehog and planned to release it in the
countryside, Rose said.
   Hedgehogs, which grow to a foot in length including the tail,
are covered with sharp spines and often roll into a ball when
alarmed. They inhabit the undergrowth in woodlands and along the
edges of fields and rarely venture out in daylight.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They pay no dues, have no scheduled meetings and
wear no skull rings.
   They have a policy of ``kindly waves of the left hand to
indicate fellowship'' with other riders.
   They are the Chickens From Heck Motorcycle and Bridge Club, an
organization not known for striking fear into the hearts of
motorists, small communities or other riders.
   ``The Chickens From Heck Motorcycle and Bridge Club do not
consider themselves superior or patronizing in any respect,'' said
Blair Chotzinoff, the five-member club's ``Grand Capon.''
   The club, whose motto is ``ride slow and snack often,''
undertakes no ``runs,'' or major trips. Its haphazard ride schedule
consists of last-minute phone calls when one of the Chickens feels
like a leisurely jaunt at ``highway speeds close enough to legal
limits to be of no interest to police,'' Chotzinoff said.
   A good thing. One of the Chickens is Denver Traffic Court Judge
Ray Satter.
   It would be a mistake to call them hard-core riders. They have
canceled more trips than they have taken because comfort plays a
major role in their decision-making.
   Last Thursday, for example, the Chickens rode to the Denver
Botanic Gardens for high tea.
   They bring pate and other gourmet treats on their Denver
Symphony Orchestra benefit rides _ a premium offered to those who
donate $50 or more during the orchestra's annual fund-raiser. They
have yet to make an out-of-state trip.
   ``We were going to take our first and go to Omaha, but there
were tornadoes and rainstorms that week and I don't know what
else,'' Chotzinoff said. ``So instead we went out to the Pawnee
Grasslands, but they had no more grass than anywhere else.
   ``We did find a great truck stop south of Greeley on that
trip,'' Satter said.
</TEXT>
