<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Afghanistan     07-26 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Afghanistan,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Doubts New Soviet Troops Have Entered Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say they have come up with no
hard evidence that Soviet troops are returning to Afghanistan,
despite a statement Saturday from Pakistan's President Mohammad Zia
al-Haq.
   The officials did tell The Associated Press on Monday, however,
that the Soviets would have difficulty meeting the Aug. 15 deadline
for withdrawing half the 115,000 troops they had in Afghanistan.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said Monday, ``We
fully expect the Soviets to honor their obligation under the Geneva
accords, to have half their troops out of Afghanistan by Aug. 15th,
and we'll continue to watch the situation carefully.''
   Redman said the United States had received assurances from
Moscow ``that they intend to meet their Afghan accord
responsibilities.''
   ``The basic fact of the matter is there is no evidence of a
re-introduction of Soviet troops,'' said one official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``We doubt they are sending new troops in, but it will be very
difficult to get the old ones out,'' another U.S. official said.
   The pace of withdrawal stalled over the last two or three
months, ``but they have enough time to get out by Aug. 15,'' a
third U.S. official said.
   U.S. officials still expressed concerned that some Soviet
military leaders found withdrawing under rebel fire difficult and
that the Soviet military commander in Kabul had indicated last week
that thousands of new troops would be sent to the embattled country.
   The commander's remarks were conveyed to Zia by the United
Nations team that is monitoring the Red Army's withdrawal.
   Zia then touched off alarm bells on Saturday with a statement
that the Soviets ``decided not only to stop their withdrawal, but
they have brought in something like 10,000 troops back from the
Soviet Union into Kabul because Kabul was under threat.''
   The Soviet military commander in Kabul may have spoken without
the authorization of his superiors in Moscow or he may have been
trying to unsettle the Pakistanis, who channeled U.S. weapons to
the rebels and took in hundreds of thousands of Afghan refugees,
officials said.
   ``We may never understand what happened,'' one U.S. official
said. ``Maybe the Soviet general was speaking prematurely or they
were trying to get the Pakistanis off balance when he made the
statement to Zia.''
   In Moscow, the chief of the Soviet general staff, Marshal Sergei
F. Akhromeyev, rejected the Pakistani charge over the weekend as
``pure slander'' and said the Soviet withdrawal was ``proceeding in
full compliance'' with the Geneva accords.
   The Soviets pledged in the accords signed in May to withdraw
half their troops by Aug. 15 and the remainder by Feb. 15. The Red
Army has fought for 7{ years alongside the pro-Soviet government in
Kabul against the U.S.-backed rebels, some of whom want to
establish an Islamic fundamentalist state along the lines of the
one in Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
