<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-26 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcker Says World Bank May Wither Away Unless U.S. Contributes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Volcker, the former head of the Federal
Reserve Board, says the World Bank is in danger of fading away as
the biggest source of aid to the Third World unless Congress acts
soon to make a new contribution.
   The bank, headed by Barber B. Conable, a former congressman from
New York, wants a U.S. pledge of $70.1 million a year over the next
six years for a badly-needed increase in its capital.
   ``Our influence and leadership within the bank are certainly at
stake, and I would raise the question,'' Volcker told a news
conference on Monday, ``if the United States is not going to
participate in capital increases ... whether the bank itself can
survive over a long period of time.''
   So far, 140 of the 151 governments that own the bank have
decided to contribute. President Reagan has urged approval of the
U.S. contribution, but it has been held up in Congress by
disagreement over what should be done to handle the bulk of the
Third World's $1.2 trillion debt.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Votes Delay on Use of Device To Protect Turtles From Fish</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nets
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal rules requiring shrimp fishermen to
use devices to prevent sea turtles from being snared and drowned in
nets would be delayed until next year under a compromise approved
by the Senate.
   The Senate on Monday gave voice vote approval to a compromise
worked out by opponents and backers of the regulation.
   The amendment proposed by Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., says
shrimp boats would not have to use turtle excluder devices in
offshore waters before May 1, 1989, or in inshore waters before May
1, 1990.
   The agreement allows debate to move forward on legislation to
reauthorize and strengthen the Endangered Species Act, which has
technically been without legislative authorization since Oct. 1,
1985. Senate leaders gave no indication when they expected to
complete work on the reauthorization bill.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Regulations Adopted For Horse Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horse shows for all breeds will be able to
continue under new Agriculture Department regulations that were
supported by horse organizations, according to Sen. Mitch McConnell.
   Horse shows for many breeds were closed earlier this year after
the American Horse Protection Association filed a lawsuit seeking
enforcement of regulations, primarily for walking horses, that had
adversely affected much of the industry.
   ``These recommendations were reached after weeks of negotiations
with every major horse organization throughout the country,''
McConnell, R-Ky, said Monday. ``Now that the regulations are
permanent, horse shows throughout Kentucky and the nation can
continue without the fear of being shut down.''
   Major provisions of the new regulations include a new uniform
standard for pads that would apply to all horse breeds; new rules
on pad material; rejection of a proposal by USDA to further limit
the weight of horseshoes; and new guidelines on examination
procedures for horses exhibited in walking horse shows.
</TEXT>
