<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-Beef     07-26 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-Beef,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lifts Import Ban On Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government sought to cool trade
tensions today by lifting a 3-year-old ban on imported beef, but
limited this year's shipments to 14,500 tons.
   Agriculture Minister Yun Kun-hwan, who made the announcement,
did not say how much beef will be imported after this year, but
indicated imports will be limited in order to protect the local
beef industry.
   Officials said the government will maintain an import quota
system, which has been opposed by Washington.
   The end to the import ban was designed to avoid trade friction
with foreign countries while at the same time alleviating domestic
beef shortages, Yun said.
   Washington has been pressing South Korea to drop the ban on beef
and many other imports to help correct Seoul's $10 billion trade
surplus with the United States.
   There was no immediate reaction from local farmers who have
strongly opposed imports of beef unless the government guaranteed a
definite price support system before lifting the import ban.
   Many Korean farmers went bankrupt due to an excessive import of
foreign beef cattle before the last ban was imposed in 1985.
Farmers have staged demonstrations to demand retention of the
import ban.
   Imported beef will be stockpiled in case the government needs to
stabilize prices if domestic sales prices exceed designated levels,
Yun said.
   Yun has said previously that this year's proposed quota will
include 3,000 tons of high-quality American beef for tourist
hotels. Officials said that beef could start arriving next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Quake     07-26 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Earthquake Rattles Central California Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KING CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake jarred the central
Coast Ranges area, apparently causing a small landslide near
Hollister. No damage or injuries were reported.
   The quake struck at 8:27 p.m. Monday and measured 4.5 on the
Richter scale, said the University of California Seismographic
Station at Berkeley. Its was centered 10 miles north of King City
and 40 miles southeast of Monterey, said seismologist Robert
Uhrhammer.
   State forestry workers discovered the landslide 18 miles outside
Hollister in San Bernardino County shortly after the earthquake,
said spokeswoman Debbie Fortulgaliza.
   ``I would have to think it (the earthquake) was what caused
it,'' she said. The rocks blocked a road until they were removed.
   Liz Liskey, a dispatcher with the Monterey County sheriff's
department in Salinas, said the quake was felt by people working in
the basement of the county courthouse. ``It was just a little
one,'' she said.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   An earthquake with a magnitude of 4.0 can cause moderate damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
