<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     07-26 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Governing Party Meets To Pick New Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's most powerful leaders met today to
discuss a successor to Ne Win as chairman of the country's ruling
socialist party, sources said.
   The Central Committee of the Burma Socialist Program Party
gathered to choose successors to Ne Win and party Vice Chairman San
Yu, the country's two most powerful figures, the sources said on
condition of anonymity.
   The 77-year-old Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military
coup, announced abruptly Saturday that he was resigning. He cited
his age and violent anti-government rioting in March and June as
key factors in his decision.
   The Central Committee, elected in 1985, includes about 270
members and normally abides by decisions made by the party's most
powerful body _ the 15-member Central Executive Committee.
   The most senior member of the executive committee, party General
Secretary Aye Ko, is considered Ne Win's likely successor.
   No details of the meeting were available. It comes one day after
a special party congress concluded its meetings on sweeping reform
proposals.
   The three-day congress session ended Monday with a vaguely
worded announcement, possibly reflecting splits within the party
over the dramatic events of recent days.
   The official Radio Rangoon said delegates ``firmly suggested''
against a voter referendum on whether Burma's 26 years of one-party
rule should be replaced by a multi-party system.
   The rejection of Ne Win's recommendation for the referendum was
the first known time the party had not rubber-stamped his proposals.
   Some liberalization of the economy last year has failed to stop
Burma's downward spiral. Inflation is soaring, government stores
are virtually empty and the country is saddled with a foreign debt
of about $4 billion.
</TEXT>
