<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Soviets     07-26 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soviets,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegation Leaves For Historic Visit To Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli delegation including two Soviet-born
Jews headed today for Moscow on the first such official trip in 21
years.
   The five Israelis will kick off their visit by attending Sabbath
prayers in a Moscow synagogue, where they hope to have a chance to
meet informally with Soviet Jews, said Soviet-born diplomat Meron
Gordon, who heads the group.
   In addition to Gordon, 41, who came to Israel at the age of 10,
the delegation includes Yaakov Kedmi, a former Soviet dissident
named Yasha Kazakov who came to Israel in the 1960s.
   ``We are both very moved,'' Gordon said on Israel Television.
``When we left there, we were young. I don't think either of us
ever thought we could return to the Soviet Union _ certainly not as
official representatives of Israel.''
   The delegates left for The Hague, where they are to pick up
two-month visas and then travel to Moscow on Thursday.
   The Soviet Union severed ties with Israel in 1967 after the Six
Day War to protest Israel's occupation of the territory captured
from three Arab countries.
   The two countries still have no official diplomatic relations,
but links between Moscow and Jerusalem have recently improved.
   In the summer of 1986, Israeli and Soviet delegates met in
Helsinki, Finland, for the first official session since 1967. Last
summer, a Soviet delegation arrived in Tel Aviv on two-month visas
that since have been extended.
   Before leaving from Ben Gurion International Airport, Gordon
told reporters the Israeli delegates would visit a Moscow synagogue
Friday evening for Sabbath prayers.
   The delegates, most of whom speak Russian, will work out of an
office in the Dutch Embassy, which represents Israeli interests in
the Soviet Union. One of their first jobs will be to inspect the
old Israeli Embassy building, Gordon said.
   The other delegates are Danny Megido, Gershon Gorev and Ehud
Balsar. Gorev's wife, Hasia, also is accompanying the team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
