<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Olympics     07-26 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Olympics,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Wants To Discuss Olympics Participation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea told South Korea in a
surprise letter today that it was willing to talk about entering
the Olympics in Seoul, but insisted again on discussing its demand
to co-host the Games, officials said.
   The North had said previously it would boycott the Sept. 17-Oct.
2 Games unless it was made a co-host. South Korea and the
International Olympic Committee have said some events could be held
in the North, but that the Games are awarded to a single host city
_ in this case Seoul _ and not to countries.
   Aides to Kim Chae-sun, speaker of South Korea's National
Assembly, said today's letter was from Yang Hyong Sop, chairman of
North Korea's Supreme People's Assembly. It was received at the
border truce village of Panmunjom, they added.
   As made public by the aides, the letter said, ``We are willing
to discuss the issue of our participation in the Olympics as
demanded by your side.''
   The letter came as South Korea was considering its response to
an earlier North Korean letter proposing parliamentary talks on a
non-aggression pact between the two rivals, split since 1945 into
the communist North and capitalist South. They fought a bloody war
in 1950-53.
   The new North Korean letter said, ``We propose with courtesy
that the scheduled North-South joint parliamentary conference be
held within August at the latest before the opening of the Olympics
and discuss as an urgent agenda such issues as your request for our
participation in the Olympics and our proposal for its co-hosting.''
   The South Korean government had no immediate comment.
   The IOC has said North Korea could stage archery, table tennis,
women's volleyball, preliminary soccer games and a cycling road
race. The North has insisted on more, including its own set of
opening and closing ceremonies in Pyongyang and a share of
television revenue.
   Seoul Olympic officials have said the offer to the North would
be kept open until the last possible moment in hopes of promoting
North-South reconciliation.
   South Korea's political leaders had been working to solve
differences among themselves before sending a unified response on
Monday next week to the North's earlier letter.
   South Korean government officials have been reluctant to agree
to immediate full-scale parliamentary talks, saying preliminary
negotiations are needed for such conferences.
   North Korea is one of only six countries that have not accepted
invitations to the Olympics in Seoul. The others are Cuba,
Ethiopia, Albania, Nicaragua and the Seychelles.
   A record 12,000 athletes from 161 nations are expected to
compete in the Games. The 161 include North Korean allies China and
the Soviet Union, which have no diplomatic relations with South
Korea.
</TEXT>
