<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NussbaumAppeal     07-26 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nussbaum Appeal,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conviction Overturned in Cable Franchise Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has overturned the conviction
of a public relations man accused of collaborating with the late
Queens Borough President Donald Manes in soliciting a bribe for the
awarding of a cable television franchise.
   The Appellate Division of State Supreme Court on Monday
overturned the indictment, conviction and sentence of Michael A.
Nussbaum, a political associate of Manes and one-time aide to
former Mayor John Lindsay.
   Nussbaum, 40, was convicted Aug. 7, 1987, of collaborating with
Manes in soliciting a $250,000 bribe from Al Simon, president of
Orth-O-Vision Inc., in 1981, when the company was competing for a
cable television franchise in Queens. The prosecution said Simon
refused to pay. His company did not win the franchise.
   Nussbaum, who had worked on Gov. Mario Cuomo's 1982 campaign,
was sentenced to one to three years in prison.
   In its ruling Monday, the four-judge appeals panel said it
``agreed with the defendant's contention that the evidence adduced
was legally insufficient to support his conviction.''
   Nussbaum's lawyer, Stanley S. Arkin, said Nussbaum was
``grateful and relieved'' and determined to ``get on with his
life.''
   Nussbaum was free without bail pending the appeal, living in
Queens and working as a sales consultant.
   Nussbaum's was one of three trials that stemmed from
investigations into the awarding of cable franchises in Queens.
   In another of the cases, real-estate developer John Zaccaro, the
husband of former Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine
Ferraro, was acquitted last October of working with Manes to extort
a bribe for the awarding of a cable franchise.
   In the third case, former Queens Administrative Judge Francis X.
Smith was convicted in July 1987 of perjury and criminal contempt.
He was sentenced to one year in jail but has remained free on bail
while an appeal is being prepared.
   Manes fatally stabbed himself in the heart in March 1986 as word
of the indictments leaked out.
</TEXT>
