<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Gurkhas     07-26 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Gurkhas,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ghurkas, Government Agree On Peace Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special administrative council
dominated by Gurkhas will be set up in West Bengal state as part of
a plan to end a separatist war by Gurkha militants, the government
says.
   The council will administer 1,080 square miles in the
tea-growing Darjeeling district of West Bengal.More than 1.4
million Gurkhas, who are Indians of Nepalese descent, live in the
area.
   S. Narendra, a spokesman for the Home Ministry, said the
decision was made at a meeting between Home Minister Buta Singh,
West Bengal Chief Minister Jyoti Basu and Gurkha leader Subhas
Ghising.
   The three met at Singh's residence in New Delhi. The Home
Ministry is responsible for Indian internal security.
   ``The Darjeeling Gurkha Hill Council will be set up as soon as
practicable,'' Narendra said. He estimated it would take about
three months.
   ``A final agreement will be signed at Calcutta very soon,'' he
added. Calcutta is the capital of West Bengal state.
   Militant Gurkhas launched an campaign for a separate state
within the Indian union in May 1986, claiming their cultural and
social identity was being swamped by migrants from other parts of
West Bengal.
   More than 300 people have been killed in attacks by the
militants. Most of the deaths have occurred in the Darjeeling
district, known for its tea and breath-taking views of the Himalaya
mountains.
   The separatist campaign was suspended at the end of June after
Ghising held discussions with Singh and Basu, where the creation of
the hill council was agreed to in principle.
   A sticking point, the inclusion of the word ``Gurkha'' in its
title, apparently was resolved at Monday's meeting.
   Sunday, a weekly news magazine, reported earlier that the
council would be responsible for land allotment, tourism, public
works, health and education.
   It will be made up of 42 members, with 30 to be elected and the
rest named by local legislators, the magazine said.
   Narendra said the council would be set up after the proposal
received the sanction of the West Bengal legislature and plans for
the elections were worked out.
   An estimated six million Gurkhas reside in India.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
