<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarcosOffer 3rdLd-Writethru a0514 07-26 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Offer, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted Philippine President Reportedly Offers $5 Billion To Go
Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs at end, comment from the Philippines</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos offered to give $5 billion
to the Philippines and back President Corazon Aquino if he is
allowed to return without being prosecuted, the Los Angeles Times
reported today.
   A Marcos spokesman in Hawaii called the report of the offer
absurd.
   The offer is part of a package being pursued by Marcos aides
that includes a pledge to promote national reconciliation in the
Philippines if he isn't charged with wrongdoing in the United
States, the newspaper said.
   ``If there is no indictment, he will support the government of
the Philippines,'' said Col. Arturo Aruiza at Marcos' Honolulu home
in exile. ``There will be a national reconciliation.''
   Representatives of Marcos are talking with Philippine officials,
including Mrs. Aquino's brother Jose Cojuangco and Philippine
Ambassador to the United States Emmanuel Peleaz, trying to work out
the $5 billion deal, according to A. James Gregor, a University of
California, Berkeley, political science professor.
   Gregor, who has been in direct contact with the Marcos camp in
Hawaii, and with U.S. officials in Washington, D.C., said Marcos
has agreed to stay out of Filipino politics, stay out of the
capital Manila and support Mrs. Aquino if he is allowed to return.
   But the ousted ruler, accused of siphoning billions of dollars
from the national treasury during his tenure as president, has
asked that his son Ferdinand Marcos Jr. be allowed to run for
political office, perhaps for governor of the family's home
province of Ilocos Norte, Gregor said.
   Asked about the $5 billion offer, Pelaez said, ``You have long
ears. ... I'm not sure whether I can talk about it or not. I'd
rather you didn't ask me.''
   Marcos' spokesman in Honolulu, Gemmo Trinidad, however, quoted
Marcos as saying the report about a $5 billion offer ``is totally
absurd.''
   ``The president (Marcos) told me negotiations are going on, but
they do not involve any money,'' Trinidad told The Associated
Press. He said he was not privy to information on who was
particating in the negotiations.
   Estimates of the amount of money allegedly diverted from the
Philippine treasury by Marcos and his associates range from $1
billion to $10 billion.
   The $5 billion offer was so high it reportedly caught Philippine
officials by surprise and raised suspicions as to how much money he
may have put away.
   ``That's why the negotiations haven't been easy,'' Gregor said.
``Everyone (in the Philippines) is saying, `If he's got $5 billion,
maybe he's got $40 billion.''
   In the two years since the revolution that led to Marcos' flight
to Hawaii, Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly said he couldn't return to
the Philippines.
   But recently she has softened that position, saying Marcos could
return if he agreed to stand trial.
   Federal officials in New York City have recommended that Marcos
be indicted on fraud and conspiracy charges stemming from his
alleged use of Philippine government funds to buy art and real
estate in the United States while concealing their ownership.
   In Manila, Quintin Doromal, an official of the Presidential
Commission on Good Government, said he was unaware of the offer.
The commission is responsible for tracking down and recovering
money Marcos allegedly stole during his 20 years in office.
   ``I don't think the commission knows anything about it,''
Doromal said. ``If there is such a thing, we would know something
about it but it's zero, no information along that line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTLTreasures     07-26 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Treasures,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Will Auction Gifts That Were Stored in Vault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appraiser will begin setting prices
today on gifts by PTL contributors _ ranging from old coins to fur
coats _ that were stashed in a vault at Heritage USA.
   PTL bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton said the items, which
supporters donated over a 10-year period, will be auctioned early
next month to raise money for the ailing television ministry.
   ``I don't know of a more critical time to use these gifts than
right now as we try to undergo the reorganization,'' Benton told a
reporter Monday, as he examined a bag of coins taken from a
15-by-16-foot vault at the World Outreach Center.
   Although the vault looked like any other storage closet,
valuable coins and dollars were found in some file cabinets and
stamps were organized in books or piled in envelopes. Furs were
strewn across some cartons.
   The ministry hasn't determined the value of the items, but
Benton's administrative assistant, Wally Stalnaker, said he was
told one stamp book was worth $28,000 to $30,000.
   ``We can't answer the value of what we have until the
appraisal's made, but some of these dollars in there are worth $100
or more,'' he said.
   Many of the furs that had been in the vault were sold at earlier
auctions, he said.
   ``The partners send it in just to help support the ministry,''
said Delores Jones, supervisor of cash management, as she reached
for gold bank notes and a bag of coins, some of them dating to 1853.
   Besides auctioning the valuables, ministry officials expect to
auction cars, trucks, a train, heavy equipment, some motor homes
and a boat that had been used at Heritage Lake.
</TEXT>
