<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CambodiaTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0483 07-26 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Rejects Cambodia Peace Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Sihanouk saying he will
meet with Hun Sen and guerrilla leaders. Picks up 9th graf pvs,
`Officials said ... ' EDITS thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk today rejected the Vietnamese-installed
government's latest peace plan, but said he was willing to meet
with Prime Minister Hun Sen.
   The warring Cambodian factions today met for a second day of
informal talks at the Dutch colonial summer palace of Indonesia's
late President Sukarno at Bogor, about 35 miles outside Jakarta.
   Sihanouk resigned July 10 as president of the guerrilla
coalition fighting the government and Vietnamese troops in
Cambodia. He is widely considered central to any settlement in the
9{ year civil war, but vowed he would not attend the peace talks
that began Monday.
   The talks bring together Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia and
the leaders of the three resistance groups _ Khieu Samphan of the
Communist Khmer Rouge, Son Sann of the Khmer People's National
Liberation Front, and Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who represents his
father, Sihanouk.
   In a meeting today with Japan's ambassador in Jakarta, Sihanouk
rejected a seven-point plan proposed by Hun Sen as an old proposal
aimed at preserving the current Phnom Penh government, Japanese
reporters said.
   Sihanouk told Ambassador Sumio Edamura that he was willing to
attend talks in Jakarta's presidential palace Wednesday with Hun
Sen and Sihanouk's guerrilla coalition partners, Khieu Samphan of
the Khmer Rouge and Son Sann of the Khmer People's National
Liberation Front.
   Sihanouk said he would make ``a very important speech'' then,
according to the Japanese journalists. Sihanouk, who ruled Cambodia
from 1941 to 1970, also said he would meet with President Suharto
of Indonesia at a dinner Wednesday.
   Indonesia's foreign minister, Ali Alatas, who organized the
talks today and Monday, said the atmosphere at Monday's session was
good and that the talks would last ``as long as it takes.'' He said
the Cambodian factions agreed on the need for a new coalition
government and a neutral, non-aligned Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and has more than 100,000
troops there supporting the Hun Sen government. Vietnam met the
guerrillas for the first time ever during the talks Monday.
   Officials said the Cambodians previously have agreed that an
early political settlement is necessary, that a new coalition
government must be formed and Cambodia must become a neutral and
non-aligned nation.
   But Hun Sen told reporters he and the guerrilla leaders resolved
no concrete problems Monday. He presented at the talks a
seven-point peace plan containing proposals already rejected by the
guerrillas.
   The plan said that before elections for a new government, the
status quo must be maintained _ defying guerrilla demands that Hun
Sen's government be dismantled before elections.
   In one new move, Hun Sen said that in order to bridge this
dispute he was proposing formation of a ``national reconciliation
council'' headed by Sihanouk to implement any peace agreements and
organize elections.
   The plan also repeated demands for elimination of the Khmer
Rouge leadership, and dissolution of its army, the largest of the
guerrilla forces. Only this, Hun Sen said, would ensure the Khmer
Rouge cannot return to power.
   From 1975 until Vietnam invaded, the fanatical Khmer Rouge
regime killed hundreds of thousands of people in Cambodia and
launched bloody attacks on Vietnam's western border.
   Diplomats in Thailand say the Khmer Rouge is storing arms for
all-out attacks when Vietnam withdraws all its troops by 1990, as
it has pledged.
   However, China, which arms the guerrillas, recently indicated it
was prepared to lessen its once-unequivocal support for the Khmer
Rouge and said it supported a government in which the group would
not have a dominant role.
</TEXT>
