<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     07-26 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Angry Mourners At Funeral of Christian Arab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Palestinian mourners shook their
fists and chanted anti-Israeli slogans today at a memorial service
for a Christian Arab killed by Israeli troops.
   Jeris Kunkar, 40, a tailor from the town of Beit Jalla near the
biblical city of Bethlehem, was hit by three bullets during
anti-Israeli protests Sunday.
   The army said Kunkar was shot accidentally when a soldier
chasing Arab stone-throwers stumbled and his gun discharged.
Palestinians said Kunkar was not involved in the violence and
happened to step out of his house when he was hit by bullets.
   Mourners today decked the Kunkar home with outlawed Palestinian
flags and chanted, ``With our spirit and blood, we will avenge the
martyr'' as church bells pealed in the background.
   The army stayed away from Beit Jalla during the service, Israel
radio said.
   Kunkar was the third Christian Arab to die over the past 10 days
and the fourth since the Palestinian uprising in Israeli-occupied
teritories began last Dec. 8.
   A total of 233 Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed.
   The deaths of Christian Arabs have heightened anti-Israeli
sentiment among West Bank Christians, considered more moderate than
their Moslem brethren.
   In the West Bank city of Hebron, a small home-made bomb exploded
today in the outdoor market but did not cause damage or injuries,
an army spokeswoman said. She said soldiers closed off the area and
carried out searches.
   In another development, the army asked the Foreign Ministry to
lodge a complaint against Belgium's consul in Jerusalem, Roger
Dewulf. The army charged Dewulf spat at Israeli soldiers guarding a
Palestinian prisoner and knocked away one soldier's hand.
   An army spokeswoman said the incident occurred last week outside
the military government building in Bethlehem.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the matter would be
investigated. He told The Associated Press that Dewulf acknowledged
giving the soldiers a disapproving look, but denied spitting at
them.
   Officials at the Belgian Consulate refused comment and referred
queries to the Foreign Ministry in Brussels.
</TEXT>
