<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Space     07-26 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Space,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government Ends Funding For Space Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced it will stop funding
research into the development of a space plane because the project
is too expensive for Britain.
   Instead, the plane is to be developed internationally as a joint
venture between two British companies _ Rolls Royce PLC and British
Aerospace PLC _ and foreign partners, former Trade and Industry
Minister Kenneth Clarke said Monday. Clarke, who did not name the
foreign partners, was appointed health secretary after making the
announcement.
   The Hotol _ or horizontal take-off and landing _ project is
aimed at developing an unmanned, reusable spacecraft capable of
operating like a conventional plane. Its supporters believe it
could put a satellite into orbit more cheaply than the U.S. space
shuttle.
   Clarke said the government had funded about half the $5.2
million cost of a research study on the Hotol's commercial and
technical viability, completed earlier this year by the two British
companies.
</TEXT>
