<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BridgeReopens     07-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Reopens,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Lanes Of Vital NY Artery Reopen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Williamsburg Bridge, which caused commuter
misery for three months while under repair, was fully opened to
traffic today for the first time in three months.
   ``The bridge is now stronger than it's been since World War
II,'' said Transportation Commissioner Ross Sandler as he watched
the first cars roll over the last four lanes that had been closed.
   The rusting 85-year-old span was closed April 12; two lanes for
motorists traveling from Manhattan to Brooklyn were opened in May
and another two in June. Subway service was also restored in June.
   The opening of all lanes this morning came two weeks ahead of
schedule. Brooklyn-bound trucks remain forbidden, but should be
allowed on the bridge come mid-August, Sandler said.
   Work was done on what Sandler called an emergency contract
basis, which meant workers labored seven days a week to add 150
tons of steel to the bridge. He said the total cost was just under
$10 million.
   ``We did a five-year job in three months,'' said Deputy
Transportation Commissioner Samuel Schwartz.
   An estimated 107,000 vehicles and 420 subway trains crossed the
bridge each day before its closure. The closure tied up traffic in
southern Manhattan and Brooklyn, added to problems throughout the
city and forced the city Transit Authority to reroute trains.
</TEXT>
