<2ND_LINE>PM-I-64 Bridge,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interstate 64 Bridge Closed For Structural Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOVA, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastbound motorists on Interstate 64 are
being forced to take a six-mile detour only 10 days after officials
opened the last link in a continuous highway from Virginia to St.
Louis.
   Structural problems on a bridge between Kenova and Huntington
forced highway workers to close the lanes for at least 10 days,
Highway Department spokeswoman Carol Melling said. District
Engineer Sam Beverage said the bridge had a 4-inch gap.
   On July 15, Gov. Arch Moore and other top state officials had
opened of the final 36-mile stretch of I-64 between Beckley and Sam
Black Church in southeast West Virginia.
   The link completed 1,125 miles of continuous four-lane road from
Norfolk, Va., to St. Louis on I-64, through Illinois, Indiana,
Kentucky, West Virginia and Virginia. The highway had been under
construction in West Virginia since the early 1960s.
   The closed span at Twelvepole Creek, near the Kentucky border,
is one of the oldest sections of I-64 in West Virginia and is not
part of the section just opened.
   Beverage said engineers spotted cracks last Wednesday and said
the gap had expanded to 4 inches by Sunday night.
</TEXT>
