<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r n PM-PandaPregnancy     07-26 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panda Pregnancy,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Plans Unprecedented Effort to Save Expected Panda Cub</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the National Zoo, where four
panda cubs have been stillborn or died shortly after birth, said
today an unprecedented technological effort is planned to save the
expected offspring of female giant panda Ling-Ling.
   ``We're, in fact, taking a step that's altogether unprecedented,
but really on the best medical advice,'' said Dr. Michael Robinson,
the zoo's director, in an interview on ABC's ``Good Morning
America''.
   Ling-Ling, who lives with her mate Hsing-Hsing in the zoo's
Panda House, gave birth to three stillborn cubs before giving birth
to a live cub last year. Zoo employees' hopes were raised when that
baby was born apparently healthy and screaming lustily, but the cub
died four days later.
   ``What happened last year is that the baby had no immune
system,'' said Robinson. ``When we did the autopsy, (we found)
there were no immunoglobulins in the baby's blood. And that means
that it had no protection against any kind of bacteria that it
could encounter in the world around it.''
   Robinson said zoo officials, who in the past have not intervened
with panda births for fear of alienating the mother from her baby,
will be aggressive from the start this year. They believe the
female panda will give birth this weekend or early next week.
   ``We're going to remove the baby from the mother and inject it
with immunoglobulins we've extracted from his (Hsing-Hsing's)
blood, and hope that that will confer a greater immunity than the
last one had,'' Robinson said.
   ``We're going to be extraordinarily careful about that, of
course,'' he added. ``The baby will be removed by our veterinarians
wearing surgical gloves and gowns and masks in the usual way, so it
shouldn't acquire any human odor. And we will treat it before we
return it to Ling-Ling with materials from the mother so that it
acquires her odor.''
   Zoo offiicals believe Ling-Ling is pregnant because she mated
with Hsing-Hsing three times in April during her brief annual
period of fertility, according to Robinson. He said her hormone
levels are similar to those she displayed at this stage in her
pregnancy last year.
   Zoo officials believe the 19-year-old Ling-Ling is nearing the
end of her childbearing years.
   Nobody knows how many years pandas are fertile, Robinson said.
``The estimates are between 19 and 23 or 24 years. But there are no
good longevity records on pandas from anywhere in the world, so
that's just `guess-timating'.''
   Only about 1,000 of the endangered giant pandas are alive in the
world today, including just 14 outside of China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
