<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Strike     07-26 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Strike,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Foil Strike By Train Engineers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police today arrested about 1,400
striking locomotive engineers and their relatives whose protests
paralyzed the national railway system.
   Police said thousands of riot police were mobilized to disperse
sit-ins by engineers and their supporters at railway stations in
Seoul and other cities. The strikers were demanding higher pay and
shorter working hours.
   In Seoul, hundreds of police stormed a Korean National Railroad
building and arrested about 300 engineers.
   No clashes were reported.
   Police said they would release most of the detainees, but that
others would be charged with illegal activity under laws banning
wildcat strikes by government officials.
   The state-run Korea National Railroad, a government agency, said
the strike _ which began shortly after midnight _ disrupted about
90 percent of normal daily service of 2,050 trains and affected
more than 1 million passengers.
   The engineers, who earn an average of $1,230 a month, are
demanding a 100 percent increase in wages, including overtime.
About 4,400 train engineers and their assistants work for the
national railroad.
   The railroad management has offered the workers a reduction in
working hours from the current average of 245 hours to 224 hours a
month, in addition to monthly raises from about $100 to about $138.
</TEXT>
