<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Clark     07-26 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Clark,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jack Clark, Announcer for ``Wheel Of Fortune,'' Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran announcer Jack Clark, the
announcer for NBC's popular ``Wheel of Fortune'' game show, has
died following a long battle with bone cancer. He was 62.
   Clark died Thursday at St. Joseph's Medical Center in Burbank,
said Laura Meyer, a spokeswoman for the show.
   Clark introduced Wheel hosts Pat Sajak and Vanna White. He also
announced the show's contestants, described prizes and named the
show's sponsors.
   Ms. Meyer said many fans had written letters asking about Clark
after he left the show several months ago.
   ``His voice was so well-known,'' she said.
   Clark began his career in broadcasting more than 40 years ago,
and received his first professional job as a substitute radio
announcer at KROW Radio in Oakland. After graduating, he worked as
a staff announcer for CBS radio.
   By 1952, Clark had moved to New York, where he became the
program announcer for the TV game shows ``Password,'' ``To Tell The
Truth,'' ``Split Second'' and ``The $25,000 Pyramid.''
   In the 1970s, Clark hosted TV game shows such as ``Dealer's
Choice'' and ``The Cross-Wits.''
   Clark was born in St. Joseph, Mo., and raised in California. He
is survived by his wife, Barbara, and four children.
</TEXT>
