<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DetroitNewspapers     07-26 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Drops Opposition To Detroit JOA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last newspaper union to oppose a proposed
partial merger of Detroit's two major newspapers has dropped its
objections, and backers say the plan now meets all requirements for
federal approval.
   The Newspaper Guild of Detroit on Monday said it would not
oppose a joint operating agreement between the Detroit Free Press
and The Detroit News after receiving concessions from the Free
Press, according to Don Kummer, administrator of Newspaper Guild
Local 22.
   The U.S. Justice Department's Anti-Trust Division and an
adminstrative law judge, along with suburban Detroit newspapers,
remain opposed to the plan. Five other newspaper unions have
endorsed the proposal.
   Knight Ridder Inc., owner of the Free Press, and Gannett Co.
Inc., owner of the News, filed a statement with the Justice
Department saying the merger application meets the standards for
approval set by the Newspaper Preservation Act.
   The newspapers asked the Justice Department in 1986 for an
exemption in antitrust law allowing them to merge business,
advertising and circulation departments. Editorial departments
would remain separate.
   A spokesman for Attorney General Edwin Meese III, who must rule
on such exemptions, has said he will decide on it before he leaves
office, which a spokesman has said will be by Aug. 15.
   Meese said Monday in Washington that the Guild's new position
would not affect his ruling. He declined further comment.
   Knight-Ridder has said if Meese rejects the request, it would
close the Free Press, resulting in the loss of 2,200 jobs. Both
newspapers claim they have lost millions of dollars in recent years.
   The Guild's agreement with the Free Press reduces the number of
Guild members to be laid off at the Free Press under a joint
operating agreement from 100 to no more than 75. The agreement also
guarantees the jobs of 45 maintenance workers at the News.
   The Guild represents about 650 editorial and business employees
at the Free Press and about 300 editorial workers at the News.
   The Guild filed a statement with the Justice Department which
``urges that the (merger) be approved.'' The statement said the
union has become convinced ``that the closing of the Free Press is
inevitable if the JOA is not approved.''
   Knight Ridder issued a statement Monday welcoming the Guild's
decision. News President and Publisher Louis A. Weil III declined
to comment.
   The Free Press had 1987 circulation of 639,720 daily and 724,342
on Sundays, while circulation of the News was 678,720 daily and
839,319 on Sundays, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
