<2ND_LINE>PM-Nitro Coffee,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grandson Arrested For Investigation In Coffee Tampering Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grandson of an elderly woman who found
nitroglycerin tablets in her coffee has been arrested for
investigation of attempted murder, police said.
   Alfred Sevilla, 23, was arrested Monday after numerous
inconsistencies in his story to detectives surfaced, said police
Lt. Sergio Robleto.
   Before the arrest, however, a market in the woman's eastside
neighborhood, which had sold her the coffee, pulled it from the
shelves. The brand was removed after police contacted the store,
which was not identified, and said there was a possibility the
product had been contaminated.
   Sevilla's grandmother, Irma Rangel, 67, reported finding
crushed, broken and whole white pills in a coffee jar when she
started preparing a cup on Friday, Robleto said.
   Lab tests of the pills revealed they matched those from a
prescription vial of nitroglycerin in Ms. Rangel's home, Robleto
said.
   No one in the household suffered any ill effects, Robleto said.
   Nitroglycerin is often prescribed to heart patients to dilate
blood vessels that become constricted.
