<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParkShoot 1stLd-Writethru a0510 07-26 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Park Shoot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Orders Police To Shoot Park `Hoodlums' Caught Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs at end with other shoot orders</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WADLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor B.A. Johnson has ordered police to
``shoot to stop'' anyone caught fighting in the city's park.
   ``There has been too much fighting in the park _ young men from
Louisville, young men from Bartow, young men from Wadley _ and the
only way to break it up is for police to shoot them,'' Johnson said
Monday.
   The mayor said fighting in the 12-acre Hope Williams Memorial
Park has been a frequent problem, but Sunday's brawl involving
eight youths who used ``big sticks with nails driven in them'' as
weapons prompted him to take action against such skirmishes.
   He said no one was seriously injured in the fight, but it
presented a threat to the families and children who wanted to use
the park as well as a threat to the town's reputation.
   Johnson has ordered an increased police patrol in the park
during weekends. ``There will be a full-time policeman every
Friday, Saturday and Sunday,'' Johnson said. ``They are to shoot
from the waist down only.''
   ``We're going to fix it so decent people can go to the park. All
the hoodlums in Bartow, stay in Bartow,'' he said. ``All the
hoodlums in Louisville, stay in Louisville, and all the hoodlums in
Wadley have been suspended from the park for the rest of the year.''
   Johnson said he also has increased the fine for fighting in the
park from $71.50 to $125.
   Reports from the Police Department said seven of the eight
involved in Sunday's fight were juveniles and were turned over to
juvenile authorities. The adult was charged with fighting and
released on a $125 bond.
   Wadley, Louisville and Bartow are in a rural area of eastern
Georgia about 130 miles southeast of Atlanta.
   Johnson's ``shoot to stop'' order is the latest in a series of
such orders he has issued in the past three years.
   In 1986, Johnson issued a ``shoot to wound'' order _ instructing
police officers to shoot suspected burglars from the waist down _
after a rash of burglaries in the east Georgia town of 2,700.
   In 1985, Johnson ordered police to shoot stray dogs on sight to
control the animals, which city officials said roamed the streets
in packs, destroyed property, snapped at children and howled at the
moon. He even offered a bounty of $3 for every dog shot.
   No shooting ever took place and both orders were eventually
rescinded.
   Also in 1985, Johnson ordered police to arrest anyone using
profane language in public. The order was aimed at young people
playing basketball in the city park whose games were frequently
accompanied by loud streams of what then-City Administrator Lee
Garner described as ``pure, unadulterated profanity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
