<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalStrike     07-26 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Strike,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike on at Seven Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of nurses and other hospital
workers today struck seven hospitals in a contract dispute that
focuses on health insurance benefits.
   Picket lines went up shortly after 6 a.m., union spokesman Allen
White said. The strike was the first in the 50-year history of
Local 250 of the Hospital and Institutional Workers, which has
1,700 members.
   Karen Henry, a lawyer representing the hospitals, said Monday
that patients would not be affected by the walkout by licensed
vocational nurses, aides, housekeepers and laundry workers.
   The six hospitals in San Francisco and one in neighboring Daly
City hired additional workers and also will use management
employees, she said.
   Union officials disputed the hospitals' claim that patient care
would not suffer.
   ``The union takes the stand that that attitude is irresponsible.
You can't take away 1,700 workers from seven institutions and
expect it not to have any effect,'' said Joe Twarog, Local 250's
chief negotiator.
   As Affiliated Hospitals of San Francisco, the hospitals had
negotiated with Local 250 for a new, two-year contract since
February. A federal mediator adjourned talks Saturday because no
progress had been made.
   Health insurance was the major issue in the dispute. Affiliated
Hospitals offered full coverage at no cost to employees, but a new
provision would require contributions of $30 a month from full-time
employees for family benefits.
   Also at issue were wages, with Affiliated Hospitals offering 3
percent raises for vocational nurses and lower-tier employees and
no increase for higher-tier workers. Pay currently ranges from
$7.90 an hour for housekeeping, laundry and food service employees
and hospital aides to $11.70 an hour for technicians and vocational
nurses.
   Talks continued between six of the hospitals and about 2,000
registered nurses. The California Nurses Association has voted to
strike Aug. 2 if no agreement is reached.
   The hospitals are St. Mary's, St. Francis, Marshall Hale,
Children's, Pacific Presbyterian and Mt. Zion hospitals in San
Francisco and Seton Medical Center in Daly City.
</TEXT>
