<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HijackingSuspect 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 07-26 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0556,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested In 1969 Hijacking To Cuba</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT spelling of Milo; Haziine cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   .
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who hijacked an airliner with 146
people aboard to Cuba 19 years ago has been arrested in Albany,
where she has lived for five years under assumed names, authorities
said.
   Linda Joyce Grinage, 39, was arrested Monday, said FBI agents,
who added they have 14 aliases listed for her. She was living under
the name of Haziine Eytina with her husband and five children.
   A hearing to certify Grinage's identity was postponed until
Wednesday. Grinage's husband, Milo Eytina, told acting U.S.
Magistrate Joseph Scully that a New York City lawyer had agreed to
represent his wife, but could not get to Albany today.
   Eytina, also a lawyer, said the identification of his wife as
the hijacker was ``absolute poppycock.''
   Grinage and her then-husband, Tyrone Ellington Austin, took a
2-year-old boy hostage on an Eastern Airlines flight from New
York's Kennedy International Airport to Miami on Jan. 2, 1969, then
forced the pilot at gunpoint to fly to Havana, authorities said.
   While running up the aisle, Austin shouted ``Black Power'' and
``Havana,'' according to authorities. None of the 138 passengers or
eight crew members was hurt.
   Grinage and Austin were indicted on air piracy charges later
that year, although they remained in Havana for a time after the
passengers and crew returned, according to the FBI. Austin died in
1971 from wounds he received during a shootout with New York City
police while fleeing a bank robbery.
   Authorities did not say how or when Grinage and Austin
re-entered the United States.
   Grinage had been living in the Albany area since 1983 but police
were not tipped about her whereabouts until receiving an anonymous
phone call in July 1987, said Barbara Cottrell, an assistant U.S.
attorney. Police did not make an arrest until Monday because they
needed time to confirm her identity, she said.
   Authorities did that through writing samples and telephone
records of a phone call made to the Rev. Walter Staten of New York
City, Grinage's grandfather, according to an affidavit made for a
search warrant.
   Grinage, who wore a red bandanna, jeans and a T-shirt in court,
walked by reporters without commenting.
   Eytina said he believed the arrest was a mistake.
   The charges are ``completely inconsistent with the person I
know,'' Eytina said. ``It's absolute poppycock. It makes excellent
fiction.''
   In court, Eytina said his wife ``has roots in the community, is
gainfully employed in the community and has resided in the
community for 10 years.''
   ``She is unable to respond in her present state,'' Eytina told
Scully, describing his wife as ``distraught.''
   If convicted, she could be imprisoned for 20 years to life.
   Cottrell said Grinage had at least six addresses in Albany since
1983. The prosecutor said she wasn't aware that the woman had a job.
   Cottrell said she would ask that Grinage be held without bail,
and would not comment on whether authorities would pursue charges
against Eytina.
</TEXT>
