<HEAD>Yellowstone Blaze Heads Away from Old Faithful</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE conditions today at Yellowstone;
picks up 5th graf pvs, `Nearly 15...' Subs 15th graf pvs, `In the
Teton...' with 1 graf to UPDATE acreage burned.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto IDA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters today called in helicopters and said they would use
natural barriers to try to maneuver a forest fire that burned
within 10 miles of Old Faithful geyser in parched Yellowstone
National Park.
   Helicopters slinging torches that spit a napalm-like substance
were called in, and ground crews used meadows and streams as a wall
against the fire, said Incident Commander Larry Caplinger. A final
decision on sending out the helicopters was expected later today.
   ``What we can do, we can go out to one side or the other of the
head of a fire, and ignite fire and get it to building and have it
draw the head of the fire in one direction or another,'' he said
this morning.
   ``We would just be trying to further influence the fire. It's
going in the direction that we want it to go, but the more we can
get it going in a more northerly direction, the better,'' Bob
Smart, fire planning coordinator, said today.
   About 450 firefighters moved into the area Monday, and by
tonight the total was expected to swell to 800 to protect the Old
Faithful complex of hotels and cabins from the North Fork fire,
which covered more than 2,700 acres.
   While officials earlier had said the fire burned to within eight
miles of the geyser, Caplinger said it was still 10 to 12 miles to
the west today and burning toward the northeast.
   ``The fire will burn to the northeast and will miss the Old
Faithful area,'' Fire Information Officer Lee Poague predicted late
Monday. ``We're not in as much jeopardy as we thought we were.''
   Blazes in America's oldest national park have blackened about
52,400 acres of its 2.2 million acres, which is mostly in Wyoming's
northwest corner but extends into Idaho and Montana. In addition to
Wyoming, wildfires burned in sections of seven other Western states
and Alaska.
   Nearly 15 miles southeast of Old Faithful, hot embers Monday
night rained down on Grant Village, burning through power lines as
the 4,500-acre Shoshone fire and the 3,000-acre Red fire approached
the area.
   The fire did not damage a small hotel, National Park Service
staff apartments and several house trailers in the area because
they were made of cinder block and other non-flammable materials,
Poague said.
   The area was evacuated last weekend, along with the Lewis Lake
campground nearly 10 miles to the southwest and the park's southern
entrance was closed.
   At Lewis Lake, the fires burned to within one-eighth of a mile
of the campground, and crews hosed down structures to keep them
from catching fire, Poague said. About 500 firefighters battled
both blazes.
   The threat to the Old Faithful area had seemed more serious
because of aerial surveys and misleading winds, Poague said.
   Ground winds blew the blaze northeast into backcountry where it
could burn untended, away from the geyser that erupts every 30 to
100 minutes, Poague said. But another wind at a higher altitude
blew smoke west, toward Old Faithful, making it seem the blaze was
headed that way.
   No services or accommodations at Old Faithful have been closed,
but visitors have been advised such action may be necessary, said
park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo.
   About 1,200 guests generally spend a night at the historic Old
Faithful Inn, the Snow Lodge and cabins in the area around Old
Faithful, said park Assistant Superintendent Ben Clary.
   Crews also fought the 31,500-acre Clover Mist fire in the park's
eastern half to keep it out of adjacent Shoshone National Forest,
Poague said.
   In the Teton Wilderness along Yellowstone's southern border,
more than 700 firefighters made progress today along the northern
side of the 24,400-acre Mink Creek fire, working to keep it from
spreading into Yellowstone Meadows and Shoshone, officials said.
   Precipitation at Yellowstone is 7.5 inches below normal for the
year, and the Old Faithful area got just 0.75 of an inch of rain in
June, the National Weather Service said.
   Other fires crackled across hundreds of acres of brush and
forest elsewhere in Wyoming and in parts of Idaho, Washington,
Oregon, Utah, Colorado and Montana. Temperatures Monday climbed to
more than 100 degrees in sections of Oregon and Washington.
   Firefighters in central and northern California mopped up dozens
of little fires while more lightning strikes were reported in the
Sierra Nevada range. Crews virtually extinguished a pair of fires
in Calaveras County that burned about 11,000 acres and eight homes,
officials said.
   In Alaska, where more than 50 fires have charred about 1.2
million acres, firefighters were battling only 22 of the blazes.
   Among the many fires in Alaska, one near Waring Mountain, east
of Kotzebue in northwest Alaska, had jumped in size by 10,000
acres, spreading to 207,000 acres, the Bureau of Land Management
reported Monday.
   BLM spokeswoman Sue Mitchell said the blaze destroyed an
unoccupied cabin and authorities were unsure if it was abandoned or
in use.
   Fire lines were holding in check a 323,000-acre fire near
Livengood in interior Alaska. It was just seven miles from the
trans-Alaska oil pipeline, but the line was in no danger, Mitchell
said.
</TEXT>
