<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZeroTolerance     07-26 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zero Tolerance,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Drops Proceedings Against Research Vessel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is dropping forfeiture
proceedings against the owners of a top ocean research vessel that
had been seized under the government's ``zero tolerance'' anti-drug
policy, an attorney said.
   The multimillion-dollar vessel is being released because the
Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution of Massachusetts didn't know
any drugs were aboard, according to its attorney, Raymond Zvetina.
   Zvetina said he was notified Monday that the U.S. Treasury
Department has decided to drop forfeiture proceedings. The vessel
had been seized May 18 after Customs officers found a trace of
marijuana and two drug-related pipes when the vessel returned from
a trip off the coast of South America.
   Atlantis II, a 210-foot vessel that participated in the 1986
exploration of the sunken liner Titanic, had been allowed to
continue its scheduled scientific voyages, but the institute was
required to inform Customs of its movement pending the outcome of
forfeiture proceedings.
   According to the Treasury Department, the forfeiture proceedings
will be formally terminated after Woods Hole pays the expenses of
the seizure.
   However, Zvetina said the institute may not have to pay any
expenses because its personnel operated the ship during the entire
seizure period.
   The Treasury Department, which has authority over Customs,
determined the institute was innocent because it had no knowledge
of the drugs and had taken reasonable precautions to prevent a
violation, Zvetina said.
   Richard F. Morris, the crew member in whose stateroom the
marijuana was found, pleaded guilty in May to a misdemeanor charge
of possession of a controlled substance. Morris, 27, of Buzzards
Bay, Mass., was sentenced to one year of unsupervised probation and
fined $100.
   Capt. Joe Coburn, marine operations manager for the institute,
said Morris also was put on three months' suspension.
</TEXT>
