<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlindSchool     07-26 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blind School,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex Charges Against Teacher Prompt Changes At School For Deaf and
Blind</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only state-supported school in
Florida for the deaf and blind has tightened its hiring procedures
as a result of sex charges brought by male students against a
former dormitory teacher.
   The Florida School for the Deaf and Blind, whose alumni include
musician Ray Charles, now requires six, instead of three,
references from prospective employees and includes more questions
on job applications about contact with children.
   In addition, non-teaching staffers must undergo fingerprint and
criminal background checks. All new Florida teachers, including
those at the St. Augustine school, must already undergo such checks
to be certified.
   Dormitory teacher Charles Johnston, 22, was fired in April when
he was charged with sexually molesting 17 of the boys he was
entrusted to protect.
   Johnston, hired in 1985, pleaded innocent and is being held
without bail in the St. Johns County Jail pending a September trial.
   His accusers include 19 deaf boys aged 9 to 14 who are students
at the school founded in 1885. Most of the 550 students at the
school are deaf and live on campus.
   ``There has been an enormous shock because the individual
alleged to have done this is a person (who) had earned the trust of
many kids, parents,'' Principal Kenneth D. Randall said in an
interview published in Monday's editions of The Tampa Tribune.
   As a dormitory teacher, Johnston looked after the boys and
taught them how to dress, clean and study. He also supervised them
in games.
   Johnston is the fifth school employee since 1986 to be arrested
and fired on charges involving students at the school.
   In separate, unrelated cases, a classroom teacher and three
dormitory staffers pleaded no contest to charges including child
abuse, attempted lewd and lascivious assault, or solicitation of
sexual activity by someone in a custodial position.
   School administrators have hired a psychologist as a consultant
and are offering counseling to the students and their families.
</TEXT>
