<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BerriganSentenced     07-26 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Berrigan Sentenced,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philip Berrigan Sentenced to Six Months in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace activist Philip Berrigan was sentenced
today to six months in jail in connection with an Easter
demonstration aboard a warship in which the ship's missile
launchers were ``symbolically disarmed.''
   U.S. Magistrate Tommy Miller ordered about 40 of Berrigan's
supporters to leave the courtroom when the group began reading a
statement.
   One man was dragged from the courtroom, but there were no
arrests. The demonstration continued in a hallway.
   Berrigan, 64, a former priest and longtime activist who resisted
the draft during the Vietnam War and now operates a Christian peace
mission in Baltimore, faced a maximum six months in prison on his
conviction of misdemeanor trespassing.
   Berrigan, along with Gregory Boertje, 32, Andrew Lawrence, 27,
and Sister Margaret McKenna, 57, were convicted by Miller in May of
misdemeanor trespassing in connection with the demonstration aboard
the battleship Iowa.
   The four ``symbolically disarmed'' the ship's cruise missile
launchers by beating on them with hammers and smearing them with
blood.
   They boarded the warship as part of an open house at the Norfolk
Naval Base, slipped away from their escorts and attacked the
armored launchers, doing minor damage.
   The four are members of the anti-nuclear group Plowshares
founded by Berrigan. The group claims the missiles are outlawed by
international law, and that their actions to symbolically disarm
the weapons were not illegal because they had no criminal intent.
   Sister McKenna received a two-year suspended sentence and was
placed on probation on the condition she not enter a military
establishment.
   Lawrence received a 4-month sentence and Boertje a 6-month term.
Both also were ordered to appear in federal court in Pennsylvania,
Lawrence for a probation violation hearing and Boertje for a
fugitive warrant.
   Boertje is wanted for failing to appear at a 1987 sentencing for
a similar demonstration. In that incident, protesters entered the
Willow Grove Naval Base outside Philadelphia and took hammers to
several aircraft, doing more than $165,000 in damage. Boertje faces
a possible 11{-year sentence in that case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
