<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0503 07-26 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Belt Much Of The Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 6th graf, `Elsewhere in ...,' to
UPDATE with storm knocking out electricity in Michigan. Picks up in
7th graf, `In Missouri ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the nation today, bringing
rain to drought-parched land, after severe storms belted the
Midwest and South with tornadoes, lightning, hail and fierce winds
that killed two people.
   A cold front hammered violent storms through the central United
States on Monday, producing severe weather in Michigan, Missouri
and Illinois.
   In Arkansas, a late evening thunderstorm whipped up high winds
that caused widespread damage around Pine Bluff. One person was
killed when a tree was blown onto an occupied car.
   In Michigan, lightning struck and killed a Jackson County woman
as thunderstorms packing winds up to 60 mph raced across the
state's southeastern Lower Peninsula, knocking out power to
thousands.
   Two tornadoes ripped through southeastern Michigan Monday
afternoon and a third touched down a few hours later, uprooting
trees and damaging crops near the eastern town of Lapeer.
   Elsewhere in Michigan, thunderstorms unleashed winds that downed
large trees near Alma, Saginaw County and Lapeer County and hail up
to an inch in diameter.
   The storm knocked out power to 20,288 Consumers Power Co.
customers in the southern Lower Peninsula; power was restored this
morning to all but 5,480 customers, company spokesman Kelly Farr.
About 1,200 Detroit Edison Co. customers scattered across southeast
Michigan also lost power, but only about 150 were without power
this morning, the utility said.
   In Missouri, thunderstorms generated high winds that downed
trees near Buffalo, Nevada, Cape Girardeau and Blodgett.
   Thunderstorms developing along the same cold front produced
severe weather at a few places in Illinois, Kansas and Oklahoma.
   In Illinois, farmers hoping for a little rain instead saw crops
battered by damaging hail as storms moved across the state,
stripping leaves off plants and causing spotty power outages from
Chicago to southern Illinois.
   More than 2 inches of rain fell at Cooksville in McLean County,
while more than 1.5 inches fell in Chicago and Springfield.
   Foul weather across central and south Florida damaged homes,
uprooted trees, downed power lines and left potholes up to 2 feet
long in a runway at Miami International Airport apparently caused
by lightning strikes.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over portions of the southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley,
the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and inland areas of the northern and
middle Atlantic Coast, lso over the south Atlantic coastal states
and eastern portions of the Gulf Coast states; and widely scattered
thunderstorms near Lake Superior and across the mountain areas of
the Western states.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s along the Pacific
Coast and the shores of the upper Great Lakes and in northern
Maine, between 95 and 105 degrees through the southern Plains,
western portions of the northern Plains and lower elevations west
of the Rockies; between 105 and 115 in the desert Southwest; and
between the 80s and low 90s throughout the rest of the United
States.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 94 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 76 partly cloudy; Boston 70 foggy; Buffalo 69
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 77 foggy; Cincinnati 66 foggy; Cleveland
65 showery; Detroit 63 partly cloudy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New
York 74 fair; Philadelphia 73 hazy; Pittsburgh 67 cloudy; Portland,
Maine 63 foggy; Washington 76 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 62 partly cloudy; Chicago 67 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 80 fair; Denver 70 cloudy; Des Moines 64 fair;
Indianapolis 66 foggy; Kansas City 66 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 67
fair; Nashville 74 cloudy; New Orleans 74 fair; St. Louis 70 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 80 partly cloudy; Anchorage 60 fair; Las
Vegas 93 fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 96 cloudy; Salt Lake
City 74 fair; San Diego 70 hazy; San Francisco 59 fair; Seattle 73
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 70 fair; Toronto 66 foggy.
</TEXT>
