<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen-Nicaragua     07-26 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Nicaragua,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lugar Presses Bentsen to Keep Supporting Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top Republican on the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee made a public appeal today for Lloyd Bentsen,
the new Democratic vice presidential nominee, to continue to vote
for aid to the Nicaraguan Contras despite the opposition of Michael
Dukakis.
   ``We believe we ought to have that vote,'' Sen. Richard Lugar of
Indiana told reporters. ``He voted consistently in support in the
past.''
   ``My guess is there will be a lot of criticism of Sen. Bentsen
if he abstains or doesn't vote on the Contra aid package,'' he
said. ``He has stood for that and been part of the bipartisan
coalition and to suddenly opt out now would be very strange.''
   Bentsen has supported President Reagan's requests for aid to the
Contra rebels in the past. A forthcoming vote that is expected in
the Senate would be his first opportunity to cast a vote on the
issue since becoming the running-mate of Democratic presidential
nominee Dukakis, who opposes Contra aid.
   Lugar commented after a meeting of GOP congressional leaders
with the president at the White House.
   He said the Contra issue was discussed and ``there was a general
consensus that the legislation ought to proceed.''
   He said there was no discussion of figures.
   ``We believe there ought to be military assistance,'' Lugar
said. ``We believe those funds will bring about some credibility in
negotiations.''
   ``Without there being humanitarian assistance, at least with
some military on the way if it doesn't work out, the thing really
won't accomplish what we want,'' he said.
</TEXT>
