<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Taxes     07-26 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taxes,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Error-Correcting Bill Wins Committee OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee today approved a
bill of several hundred pages designed to correct errors in the
1986 tax overhaul.
   Attached to the bill, which won unanimous approval, was a
provision exempting farmers from paying the federal tax on diesel
fuel they buy for off-road use. A 1987 change requires them to pay
the tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and then apply for a refund at
yearend.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the committee, said the
``technical corrections'' bill is too important to clutter with
other amendments that might delay its enactment. But he said
committee staff will attempt to put together a package of unrelated
tax amendments that would be added to the bill when it reaches the
Senate floor, if a majority of committee members can agree.
   That presumably would include, for example, an amendment
allowing free-lance writers and artists to deduct certain expenses
even before a book or painting begins producing revenue. Another
likely amendment would free owners of mutual fund shares from
paying a tax on certain operating expenses of the fund.
   Those provisions and numerous others were added to the
technical-corections bill by the House Ways and Means Committee, as
were selected tax increases targeted to pay for the tax benefits.
The House bill, for example, would impose a tax of $2.67 a pound on
pipe tobacco and bar moonlighters and others who work out of their
homes from deducting any part of their base monthly telephone bill.
</TEXT>
