<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--German-Vegetables     07-26 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--German-Vegetables,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germans Trading in Their Beloved Wurst for Vegetables</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germans increasingly are snubbing
their traditional wurst and potatoes for vegetables.
   Vegetable consumption climbed from 152 pounds per person in 1982
to 170 pounds last year and is expected to continue to increase,
according to the Central Marketing Association for German
Agriculture.
   West German officials are among those lining up for plates of
leafy greens and vegetables. There's a new daily salad buffet
available at the commissary for employees at the office of
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Vegetable dishes have also become a favorite at the cafeteria
for federal lawmakers, even though the traditional breaded cutlet,
sausages and ham sandwiches still are popular.
   The environmentalist Greens Party led the charge in altering the
menu at federal government cafeterias to include vegetarian dishes.
   Chefs at Kohl's personal kitchen say the chancellor sometimes
orders food from the commissary available to his employees, but
they refuse to say whether the portly politician is among those who
make a beeline for the salad buffet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
