<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Vatican-AIDS     07-26 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Vatican-AIDS,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Criticizes Italian TV Promoting Condom Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican's daily newspaper on Tuesday
criticized advertisements on Italian television that recommend
using condoms to prevent the spread of AIDS.
   The article in L'Osservatore Romano reaffirmed the Vatican's
opposition to promoting the use of condoms in the fight against
acquired immune deficiency syndrome, declaring that, as with
smoking, the best medical advice is abstinence.
   The Vatican commentary said the theory of not striking at the
roots of evil but only its consequences has resulted in the
promotion of condoms as the ``routine remedy'' of dealing with what
is presented as ``the evil of the century.''
   In a major statement in March, the Vatican newspaper said the
issue of sexual permissiveness was the ``true cause'' of the AIDS
problem.
   The latest commentary said the TV spots fit into the logic that
``the essential issue is not to prevent the evil but to control its
effects.''
   The spots, contracted by the Ministry of Health, begin Tuesday
on RAI-TV's three channels and run through Aug. 8, and then again
in mid-September.
</TEXT>
