<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     07-26 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Delegation To Moscow, First Visit in 21 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of Israeli diplomats, including a former
Soviet dissident, left Tuesday for Moscow in a visit seen here as
critically important to Soviet-Israeli relations, which were
severed 21 years ago.
   The five delegates plan to join in Sabbath prayers at the main
synagogue on Friday evening in Moscow and to make themselves highly
visible among Soviet Jews, many of whom have been choosing to
emigrate to the United States and Europe instead of Israel.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who met Tuesday with visiting
Russian Orthodox Metropolitan Filaret, said he hoped for a
substantial improvement in Soviet-Israeli relations.
   The visit will be especially emotional for two of the Israelis.
Delegation head Meron Gordon emigrated from the Soviet Union at the
age of 10, and Yaakov Kedmi, 43, is a former Soviet Jewish
dissident who came here at the age of 24.
   ``We are both very moved,'' Gordon, 41, said on Israel
Television. ``When we left there, we were young. I don't think
either of us ever thought we could return to the Soviet Union _
certainly not as official representatives of Israel.''
   Yeshayahu Anug, deputy director of the Foreign Ministry, spent
the last year heading efforts aimed at gaining Soviet permission
for the official Israeli visit.
   He called it a ``major event'' and added ``the atmosphere is
promising ... but we don't intend to conquer the Soviet Union in
one day.''
   He said the immediate purpose of the delegation was to help
process Israeli visas both for Soviets wishing to emigrate and
those wishing to visit.
   From January to June, 6,017 Soviet Jews emigrated and 840 of
those went to Israel, according to the Geneva-based
Intergovermental Committee For Migration.
   In addition, the team will inspect the empty Israeli Embassy
building, for which Israel pays about $100,000 annual rent.
   Anug said the delegation's limited mandate could be expanded,
although there was no plan for it to take part in political talks
with Soviet officials.
   The diplomats traveled Tuesday to The Hague, where they are to
pick up two-month Soviet visas and then leave Thursday for Moscow.
Israel hopes the delegates will be allowed to stay longer.
   The Soviet Union severed ties with Israel after the 1967 Middle
East War to protest Israel's occupation of territory captured from
three Arab countries.
   Israel and the Soviet Union still have no official diplomatic
relations, but links between Moscow and Jerusalem have recently
improved.
   In the summer of 1986, Israeli and Soviet delegates met in
Helsinki, Finland, for the first official session since 1967. Last
summer, a Soviet delegation arrived in Tel Aviv on two-month visas
that since have been extended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
