<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BushJr-Kennedy     07-26 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush Jr-Kennedy,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Son Defends His Father's Actions as Vice President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush Jr. says his father was
``right where he was supposed to be as vice president'' in response
to the rhetorical attack from Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy and
other Democrats of ``Where was George?''
   Kennedy, in a speech at last week's Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta, wondered why the likely Republican
presidential nominee didn't take a stand against such controversial
Reagan administration policies as the sale of arms to Iran in
exchange for hostages.
   ``Where was George?'' the Massachusetts senator asked repeatedly.
   But the younger Bush, in a brief campaign stop Monday, said,
``George was right where he was supposed to be as vice president of
the United States, a loyal, solid vice president who is willing to
take the good news out of this administration, and the bad news.''
   ``And for every policy that didn't work, I hope Teddy stands up
and says, `Thank you, George,' for fighting for an economy that has
a 5.2 percent unemployment rate. Or `Thank you, George' for
fighting for a military buildup that's now kept the Russians at the
negotiating table so that for the first time in my lifetime, we
have eliminated an entire class of nuclear weapons.
   ``And `Thank you, George' for fighting for conservative judges
up and down the judicial system. That's what he ought to be
saying,'' he said.
   Bush, appearing with a local Republican candidate, predicted a
``tough, close election'' between his father and Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis.
</TEXT>
