<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Mideast     07-26 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Mideast,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Officials Set Talks On Mideast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's top Mideast
official will meet next week with his Soviet counterpart to discuss
developments in the Persian Gulf and the stalled Arab-Israeli peace
process, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy will meet in Geneva
early next week with Vladimir Polyakov, a specialist on the Middle
East at the Soviet foreign ministry, said the official. He spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Murphy-Polyakov meeting is part of regularly scheduled
contacts between the two officials, although they have increased
the pace of their meetings this year, said the official. They last
met in March.
   Murphy will travel to the Mideast after the Geneva meeting, said
another official. He declined to elaborate or to be named.
   Arab-Israeli peace moves have been moribund since attempts
earlier this year by Secretary of State George Shultz to bring the
sides to the negotiating table and defuse the Palestinian uprising
in Israeli-occupied territories.
   The United States appears to have placed its peace plan on hold,
pending the outcome of general elections in both countries in
November.
   The Soviet Union is seeking an increased role in the peace
process, which so far has been dominated by the United States.
   In the Gulf, the superpowers are cooperating in supporting
attempts by U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar to bring
about a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   The two neighbors, who have been at war for almost eight years,
agreed last week to accept a year-old U.N. cease-fire resolution
designed to end the conflict. Perez de Cuellar is meeting this week
in New York with representatives from both sides to work out
implementation of the cease-fire.
   Murphy and Polyakov are also expected to discuss implementation
of the cease-fire, as well as rehabilitation plans for the
devastated region. Japan has offered to provide financial help for
rehabilitation projects.
   The Soviets enjoy good ties with both parties, while the United
States is seeking to renew the dialogue it had with Iran before
ties were broken following the 1979 take-over of the U.S. embassy
in Tehran by Iranian militants.
</TEXT>
