<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Liechtenstein     07-26 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Liechtenstein,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principality Marks 50th Anniversary of Ruling Monarch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tiny principality of
Liechtenstein on Tuesday marked the 50th anniversary of the coming
to power of Prince Franz Josef II, Europe's longest-reigning head
of state.
   Parliament held a special session in honor of the 81-year-old
monarch, and a portrait of the prince etched onto Liechtenstein
marble was unveiled in the government building in the capital,
Vaduz.
   Franz Josef is the second-longest ruling head of state in the
world, behind Japan's Emperor Hirohito, 87, who has reigned for 62
years.
   He oversees a 62-square-mile principality with a homogeneous
population of 27,000.
   Four years ago, Franz Josef turned over administrative duties to
his eldest son, Hans Adam, and since then his role largely has been
ceremonial.
   Under Franz Josef's rule, Liechtenstein moved from being a poor
agrarian state to a modern industrial nation. The prince also is
credited with resolving internal political unrest before World War
II and with keeping the principality, nestled between Switzerland
and Austria, neutral during the war.
</TEXT>
