<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Foreign Minister Accuses Iraq of Threatening Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs, peace talks begin a day early. Picks up
5th graf pvs ``Velayati declined...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar today held
the first round of peace talks on implementing a cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq War.
   As he arrived at U.N. headquarters, Velayati condemned the
latest Iraqi offensive and said Iraq was jeopardizing peace efforts
by using outlawed chemical weapons.
   Perez de Cuellar said he would hold negotiations today with
Velayati on a cease-fire, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange,
formal peace talks and a U.N. peace plan. The talks had been set
for Wednesday.
   Further talks with Velayati and his Iraqi counterpart, Tariq
Aziz, are to be held Wednesday.
   Aziz was scheduled to arrive in New York later today. It was not
known if he would see the secretary-general today.
   U.N. officials said Perez de Cuellar was aided by senior
political, military and legal officers. Perez de Cuellar said
Monday he is optimistic a truce date can be set within 10 days.
   Iran announced July 18 that it accepted the year-old Security
Council resolution calling for a cease-fire in the nearly
8-year-old war. Iraq previously accepted the resolution.
   Since Friday, Iraq has captured Iranian territory and prisoners
in a series of attacks but has said it did not intend to keep the
land. Iraq has said it intended to take the prisoners to improve
its bargaining position in cease-fire talks.
   ``They have intensified the war on the front ... in the last few
hours they have attacked some cities and invaded our border,''
Velayati said today.
   He said Iraqi officials declared Monday that their forces would
withdraw from Iran by midnight. However, he said, Iraq invaded two
northwestern cities ``and still the war is going on very seriously
and they have used chemical weapons on a large scale.''
   Velayati declined to answer reporters' questions about the
possibility of restoring a dialogue with the United States.
   Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, said
today it would be ``very difficult'' for the United States to
normalize relations with Iran before the nine U.S. hostages were
freed from captivity in Lebanon.
   ``There's no question that the people that are holding the
hostages have some kind of allegiance or connection with Iran,''
Walters said in an interview on CBS' ``This Morning.''
   ``I think it would be very dfficult for us to justify anything
unless they released the hostages,'' he said.
   The longest-held among the 18 foreign hostages believed held in
Lebanon is Terry Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman on Monday reaffirmed
the U.S. willingness to hold a dialogue with Iran. He told
reporters the United States sent Iran a message last week raising
the possibility of talks, but no reply had yet been received.
   The United States broke diplomatic relations with Tehran after
Iranian revolutionaries stormed the U.S. Embassy there in 1980 and
took hostages. The last 52 U.S. hostages in Iran were freed 444
days later.
   A seven-member U.N. team, meanwhile, arrived in Tehran today to
work out the technical details of the cease-fire and was to visit
Baghdad later in the week.
   U.N. team leader Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset said he would explore
ways to implement and maintain a truce, Iran's Islamic Republic
News Agency reported in a dispatch monitored in Cyprus.
   Five of the officials are from the Jerusalem-based U.N. Truce
Supervision Organization and two are from United Nations
headquarters in New York.
   Other U.N. experts already were in Tehran to determine the
status of prisoners of war. An exchange of prisoners is a key
aspect of the U.N. cease-fire resolution.
</TEXT>
