<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Labor-HHS 1stLd-Writethru a0438 07-26 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Labor-HHS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Oppose Abortions for Rape, Incest Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 6 grafs, pension controversy averted; picks up 5th
graf pvs, Sen. Jesse.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today side-stepped a controversial
pension issue during debate on the fiscal 1989 health and human
services spending bill, after having rejected attempts to terminate
the nation's family planning program.
   The massive $137 billion bill, which also contains money for the
departments of labor and education, is traditionally a lightning
rod for controversy.
   President Reagan has said he would veto the entire bill based on
a Senate provision permitting Medicaid funds for abortions where
pregnancy is the result of rape or incest. Current law permits
payments only where the life of the mother is endangered.
   Senators agreed today to leave out another provision opposed by
Reagan, a one-year moratorium on companies cashing out overfunded
pension plans. The Senate Appropriations Committee had approved the
moratorium, but the full Senate instead passed a resolution
directing the Finance Committee to deal with the issue.
   Hundreds of companies have dipped into their plans and labor
leaders say the money is often used for mergers or other business
moves not in workers' interests. ``Company after company has turned
its pension plan into a piggybank'' while paying meager benefits to
retirees, said Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, chief sponsor of the
provision.
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., a leading opponent of the moratorium,
said the Metzenbaum approach would have encouraged companies to
underfund their plans. He also said the Appropriations Committee
had no expertise in the complicated area of pension law.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., lost attempts Monday to eliminate the
$140 million Title X family planning program and to require
unmarried minors seeking contraceptives from federally funded
clinics to have written parental consent.
   The Senate voted 65-21 against getting rid of Title X and 54-34
against the mandatory parental consent proposal.
   In other action Monday on the labor-HHS spending bill, the
Senate approved by voice vote an abortion ``conscience clause''
sponsored by Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.
   The provision says none of the money in the bill can be used to
require any person or entity to perform or facilitate abortions. It
applies to medical personnel or denominational hospitals with
religious or moral objections to abortion.
   Title X provides money to states, local health departments and
private groups for family planning clinics serving primarily
low-income women.
   Helms alleged that Title X recipients are using federal funds
for abortion-related services and for ``secret sex programs for our
nation's teen-agers.''
   ``The federal government takes money from American parents and
then uses that money to give contraceptives ... to their
children,'' Helms said. ``This is wrong. This is immoral.''
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., countered that ``Title X is not an
abortion program. It's a knowledge program. It has been enormously
successful.''
</TEXT>
