<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThomasReed     07-26 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thomas Reed,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Shifts Reed Extortion Trial To Mobile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ordered state Rep.
Thomas Reed's extortion trial moved from Montgomery to Mobile after
Reed's attorneys complained that pre-trial publicity made a fair
trial impossible.
   The veteran Tuskegee lawmaker is also president of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in Alabama.
   He is charged with accepting $10,000 in cash and between $5,000
and $10,000 in restaurant equipment from the family of convicted
murderer Anthony Dennis Chesser to secure his early release from
prison.
   Reed was scheduled for trial Aug. 8, but U.S. District Judge
Joel Dubina moved it to Sept. 26 in Mobile. Dubina will still
preside.
   The six week delay is to allow one of Reed's defense attorneys,
former Lt. Gov. Bill Baxley, to recover from a bleeding ulcer.
   In a court hearing today, Reed's defense team presented two
television reporters who testified about the extensive coverage
Reed's case received on their Montgomery stations.
   A private investigator working for Reed's lawyers said he had
interviewed more than 300 people in central and south Alabama about
the Reed case and at least 90 percent were convinced Reed was
guilty.
   Private investigator Sam Wright said the least opinionated
people he found in his survey were in the Mobile area.
   After listening to the testimony Dubina agreed to move the trial.
   ``I think that's some indication the judge agrees Mr. Reed has
been mistreated, or treated differently,'' Baxley said.
</TEXT>
