<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma-Leader     07-26 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Leader,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hardliner Emerged as Burma's Top Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sein Lwin first rose to prominence in
Burma by commanding an army company that shot and killed 22
protesting students in a 1962 riot at Rangoon University.
   Last March, when thousands of students went on a rampage in some
of the worst rioting in Burma's history, it again was Sein Lwin who
led the forces that put them down.
   Analysts had suggested the 64-year-old hardliner would be a
logical scapegoat as the government of Ne Win, his close ally,
sought to appease critics and stabilize the country.
   Instead, Sein Lwin emerged Tuesday as Burma's most powerful
leader, succeeding Ne Win, who resigned Saturday.
   The new chairman of the Burma Socialist Program Party _
virtually the country's sole political institution _ is like almost
all of its members a retired military officer.
   He joined the army in 1942 when Burmese officers, including Ne
Win, were siding with Japan against the Allies _ specifically
Britain, which had colonized the onetime kingdom.
   As the war progressed, the officers switched allegiance to the
Allies, realizing Japan posed as much a threat to Burmese
independence as had the British. Independence from Britain in 1948
was followed by a chaotic, 14-year experiment with democracy.
   That experiment ended in 1962, the year Ne Win seized power in a
military coup and began to enforce his brand of economic socialism,
military-backed authoritarian rule and isolation from much of the
world.
   That same year, Sein Lwin led his army unit in quelling the
protest at Rangoon University, firmly establishing his reputation
as an unbending leader prepared to wield an iron fist to root out
opposition.
   Little has been pubished about Sein Lwin and others in Burma's
senior hierarchy, most of whom live secluded lives away from the
public eye.
   Sein Lwin retired from the army and in 1977 became a member of
the party's guiding body, the Central Executive Committee. He took
the No. 4 party slot of joint general secretary in 1985.
   Also in 1985, he was named secretary of the Council of State,
the No. 3 position in the government after president and vice
president. The 28-member council directs all state organs.
   He has also held ministerial portfolios for cooperatives,
transport, communications, and home affairs.
   On March 18, in a day that was later dubbed ``Bloody Friday,''
thousands of students stormed through downtown Rangoon, burning
cars and shouting anti-government slogans for the second time in
three months.
   The ``Lon Htein,'' or riot police, were called out, reinforced
by regular army units and armored vehicles. According to Western
diplomatic and Burmese sources, Sein Lwin commanded the police from
a tactical command headquarters at the government broadcast station.
   Sein Lwin overruled some leaders who wanted to handle the riot
more leniently, the sources said. The government has since admitted
to 43 deaths but more than 100 people are believed to have been
killed.
   Analysts, among them the respected Hong Kong-based Far Eastern
Economic Review, had suggested Sein Lwin would take the fall for
the violence, which deepened anti-government sentiments.
   Home Minister Min Goung resigned, several other officials were
sacked or reprimanded. On Tuesday, the nation's prime minister and
attorney general were dismissed in connection with the riots, and
Sein Lwin emerged as leader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
