<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BackStudy     07-26 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Back Study,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Many Lower Back Disc Operations May Be Unnecessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spine specialist who prescribed back
surgery for football star Joe Montana says at least twice as many
operations as necessary are performed for ruptured discs in the
lower back.
   Dr. Jeffrey Saal of the San Francisco Spine Institute said
surgeons generally use the wrong criteria in deciding to operate.
He reported findings of his three-year study, co-written with his
brother, Dr. Joel Saal, to the North American Spine Society in
Colorado Springs, Colo., on Monday.
   These include severe pain, leg weakness, failure to respond to
bed rest and diagnostic exams showing a fragment of the disc's
nucleus has broken through the disc wall and is pressing against a
nerve root.
   None of those, Saal said, should be used as overwhelming
evidence that surgery is needed. Instead, the decision should be
based on the patients' level of function and whether that can be
improved by an active rehabilitation program, he said.
   ``More than 20 percent of patients with (lower back) disc
problems have surgery but less than 10 percent may really need it
if there are no other problems, such as stenosis, or narrowing of
the spine,'' Saal said in an interview.
   Other studies have noted the presence of stenosis as a reason
for failed lumbar disc surgery and estimated the presence of
stenosis in 30 percent of those patients.
   Rapid, progressive weakness in the leg is an indication surgery
is needed, Saal said. Montana had those symptoms, along with
stenosis, before his surgery in 1986.
   Montana's back surgery was so successful, it was commonly
referred to on the sports pages as a ``miracle.'' At mid-season,
doctors said the surgery would sideline him for the rest of the
year, possibly forever. But he was back on the field in weeks to
lead the 49ers in the playoffs.
   Most patients with ruptured lumbar discs have less severe
symptoms and can return to work and sports within four months after
starting active, non-operative treatment, Saal said.
   ``He's probably correct,'' said Frances Conley, chief of
neurosurgery at the Palo Alto Veterans Hospital and associate
professor of surgery at Stanford University. ``Far too much surgery
has been done on lumbar discs, and we're becoming more aware about
how much it's been overdone now because we have better tools, such
as magnetic resonance imaging.''
   Saal's treatment included teaching patients how to reduce the
risks of further injury, training for spine stabilization and
exercises to develop overall body strength and flexibility while
the disc heals itself. Injections or drugs sometimes were used to
block pain and reduce swelling.
   Such treatment, he said, can cost up to $3,500, compared with
more than $30,000 for surgery and post-operative care, while
involving much less risk.
   More than 2 million Americans suffer from ruptured discs in
their necks and lower backs, and they spend more than $3 billion
annually on lumbar disc treatment, according to the American
Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons.
   An estimated 237,000 operations on discs in the neck and back
were performed in 1986, according to the National Center for Health
Statistics.
   Ronald Mortara, neurosurgeon at University Hospital in Boston
and associate professor at the Boston University School of
Medicine, said he agreed that lumbar disc surgery is sometimes
performed unnecessarily but was unaware of any studies indicating
how often that occurs.
   But he was skeptical of Saal's claim that 90 percent of lumbar
disc patients could be healed without surgery if they have severe
pain.
   ``We're quite conservative here, as a rule,'' he said. ``But if
the patients have failed bed rest, physical therapy, pain
medication, antispasm drugs and are out of work and can't do the
things they like, then surgery is probably indicated.''
   Saal's study, based on 59 patients averaging 35 years old and
thought to be free of stenosis, found their symptoms _ sciatic pain
in their toes, legs or buttocks, a tingling sensation in their toes
and weakness in their feet _ lasted an average of five months.
   Only six patients required surgery after the non-operative
program, but four of those were found to have stenosis.
   Eighteen patients asked surgeons for a second opinion of their
cases and all were recommended for surgery as soon as possible to
avoid long term complications. Fifteen of those, however, rated
themselves good or excellent after treatment without surgery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
