<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReluctantStars     07-26 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reluctant Stars,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Screenwriter Seeks Feature Movie Role for Hometown Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A screenwriter wants his home town to be
in pictures, but he has encountered some reluctant stars.
   Public and private school officials are concerned about the
script, in which students flout authority to keep their school from
closing.
   ``We'll be equated to whatever takes place'' in the film, said
Sister Kevyn Maiers, administrator at Cathedral High School, where
much of the filming would take place.
   There's another set of problems at Apollo High School, where
screenwriter Steve Sommers was graduated in 1976.
   ``The script calls for a car on the football field. Especially
during the time of football season, that creates some concern,''
said Kathy Zavala, community relations specialist for St. Cloud's
public school district.
   The moviemakers would like to film two Apollo football games,
but don't want to become the main attraction themselves at the
games, she said.
   But Sommers, writer-director of ``Catch Me If You Can,'' says
the script is ``very innocent.''
   ``In the end, the school principal is the hero. He's revered
throughout,'' Sommers said Tuesday from his office in the Los
Angeles area, where casting is under way.
   Sommers wouldn't reveal many details about the script, but said
it's generally ``about a principal who believes in kids and kids
believe in him. And there's a romance about two kids from the
opposite sides of the track who get together to do something
positive'' to keep their school open.
   ``There's no sex at all. There's a big kiss at the end,''
Sommers added.
   About two weeks of filming in St. Cloud would begin in
September, and the public and private school boards are expected to
decide in the next few weeks whether to approve the project.
   Sommers, who also graduated from St. John's University at
Collegeville, said he expects approval.
   ``It'll be great for the school. I'm from St. Cloud and I'd
never do anything to offend or embarrass anybody there. I love my
home town. My family still lives there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
