<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Citizens'Posse     07-26 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citizens' Posse,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angered Onlookers Give Chase, Nab Purse-Snatching Cyclist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a bicyclist grabbed 80-year-old Sara
Foster's purse as she was walking home from the grocery store, Lee
Dowd raced to the rescue. So did Jack Price. So did three
construction workers.
   ``This is one grateful old lady,'' Mrs. Foster said, recounting
the events of Monday.
   She said she had set her shopping bag down on a fire hydrant,
put her purse inside it ``and I took about four steps when that
young man came by ... just picked my purse right out, right out of
the bag, and kept on going.''
   Ms. Dowd, 34, was driving by when she saw the man steal the
purse and she began chasing him.
   ``The creep,'' she said. ``I figured he could ride his bike for
as long as he wanted to but I could chase him. I thought about
hitting him, but I didn't do it because I knew I'd get sued.''
   Price, 30, was driving behind Ms. Dowd, and he too gave chase.
   ``Hang on tight,'' he told his 6- and 8-year-old daughters. ``A
lady's in trouble.''
   Trapped in a cul-de-sac, the bicyclist ditched the purse and
jumped over a fence.
   Mrs. Dowd returned the purse, containing $26 and eyeglasses, to
Mrs. Foster. Meanwhile, Price gunned his car around the block to
catch the thief on the other side, but missed him.
   He asked several construction workers if they had seen a guy in
a plaid shirt.
   Clint Hutchinson began looking for him, saw the man peeking
around the corner of an apartment building and ran toward him.
Hutchinson also yelled to an elderly man on his front porch to call
police.
   Two other construction workers, Kevin Godfrey, 18, and Tom
Haywiser, 28, sprinted toward the man in the plaid shirt. ``You
know anything about a purse-snatching?'' they yelled.
   ``I don't want no drugs,'' the man hollered back, and he ran,
with the pair right behind.
   Half a mile later, Godfrey tackled the man in a mall.
   ``The security guard walked up to me. He didn't know what to
think. I was huffing and puffing and all I could say was `Call the
police,''' Godfrey said.
   But officers John Bowden and Darrell Hasty were already there.
The elderly man and at least two other residents had been phoning
details of the chase along the way.
   Jackie Lee Hadley, 19, was arrested and in the Orange County
Jail without bond Tuesday, charged with strong-arm robbery.
</TEXT>
