<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WilliamsburgReopens     07-26 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Williamsburg Reopens,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neglected Span Reopened After Surface Facelift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Williamsburg Bridge, closed when inspectors
discovered such extensive corrosion they feared it might collapse,
was reopened Tuesday following nearly $10 million in surface work.
   ``The bridge is now stronger than it's been since World War
II,'' said Transportation Commissioner Ross Sandler, who watched
the first cars roll over the span linking Brooklyn and Manhattan at
7:45 a.m.
   The bridge was built in 1903 for bicycles and horse-drawn
buggies. By the time it was closed April 12 it was carrying more
than 100,000 vehicles and 420 trains daily.
   The closing of the bridge affected millions of daily commuters
not only on that structure but on the neighboring Manhattan and
Brooklyn bridges, to which displaced traffic was rerouted.
   Two lanes for motorists were opened in May and another two in
June. Tuesday's ceremony marked the opening of all eight lanes to
cars. Brooklyn-bound trucks remain forbidden, but should be allowed
on the bridge by mid-August, Sandler said.
   Sandler said the city was able to complete the work two weeks
ahead of schedule because contractors and city employees worked
seven days a week, adding some 150 tons of steel to the structure.
   More extensive, long-term work _ particularly on the approach
roadways leading to the bridge _ is still needed, Sandler said.
   A $350 million, seven-year project will begin once federal and
state funds are secured. Closures then will be one lane at a time,
he said.
   ``We now know what we need to do to preserve this bridge,'' said
Sandler. ``When we're done it will be like new and should last
hundreds of years _ if we take care of it.''
</TEXT>
