<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Cholera     07-26 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Cholera,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cholera Spreads, Many Of The 157 Dead Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contaminated rainwater in the slums of
New Delhi is blamed by city officials for an epidemic of
water-borne diseases that killed 14 more lives Tuesday, bringing
the death toll to 157.
   At least 317 people suffering from gastroenteritis and cholera
were hospitalized Tuesday and that the epidemic is spreading to new
areas of the Indian capital.
   More than 4,400 residents, mostly children, are hospitalized
with the diseases, caused by contaminated water from monsoon rains
that has seeped into the city's primitive pipes and wells.
   About 1,200 new cases were reported Monday from nine areas of
New Delhi with a combined population of half a million people. Most
of the earlier cases were reported from only two neighborhoods.
   More than 11,700 people have sought treatment since July 9.
   Officials say they have inoculated more than 200,000 people to
halt the spread of the diseases.
   Dr. Raj Saxena, a physician in the district of Sunder Nagri,
says he and his team are inoculating 30 people every hour.
   ``But it seems it's not working,'' he said. ``Frankly speaking,
the situation is out of our hands. The damage has been done, we are
just trying to check it.''
   Hit hardest by the epidemic are slums built after 1975 in
outlying areas to the east.
   Of New Delhi's 8 million people, 2.4 million people live in
slums, 25 percent of which have no power supply, 49 percent no tap
water and 32 percent no toilet facilities.
   The impoverished Nand Nagri district, east of the Yamuna River,
was the first area hit by the epidemic and is worst-affected. It
has 50,000 residents.
   Garbage in the area has not been collected for four or five
months after a dispute between the Delhi Development Authority and
the Municipal Corp. over which agency was responsible for the slum
areas.
   Health officials say rain water flowing through garbage and
sewage into shallow wells is spreading the diseases among the
congested dwellings.
   Health officials ordered city wells shut off and water tanked
in. Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi toured the area last week and
ordered the garbage cleared.
   But the Indian Express newspaper reported Tuesday that the slums
``still looked like cesspools.''
   Dr. T.S. Rana, a private physician with a clinic in Nand Nagri,
said the number of cases may be greater than reported.
   ``At least four to five people are dying of cholera from this
area daily who are not reported,'' he said.
   ``People here do not have money to take patients to hospitals,''
he said. ``They try the local doctors and then just pray, and
cholera is a disease which does not respond to prayer.''
   The monsoon rains began in New Delhi in the last week of June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
