<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Americans     07-26 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Americans,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Serviceman Killed Near Base, American Woman Slain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen shot and killed a U.S. Air
Force sergeant while he was jogging with his dogs near Clark Air
Base, in an incident that may have been caused by a marital
dispute, police said Tuesday.
   In a separate incident, police said the Filipino wife of an
American serviceman was slain Sunday near the base, about 50 miles
north of Manila.
   In a third incident, police said two Belgian Embassy officials
were shot and wounded Sunday south of the capital, and the Filipino
companion of one of them was shot dead. Police said robbery
appeared to be the motive in the last two cases.
   Tech. Sgt. Richard Blackmer, 31, of the Cleveland suburb of
Brook Park, was jogging near his home about one mile from the
base's main gate about 9:30 p.m. Monday when gunmen in a car opened
fire with M-16 rifles, killing him and his two dogs, police said.
   Investigators, who requested anonymity, said a preliminary
investigation indicated the killing may have been caused by a
marital dispute.
   They said Blackmer was estranged from his Filipino wife and was
living with another woman. Police Monday picked up the wife, Maria,
for questioning but said no charges were filed.
   Police Capt. Gener Mangune said Mrs. Blackmer refused to answer
questions and expressed resentment over receiving a smaller amount
of financial support than Blackmer was paying to his common-law
wife.
   Meanwhile, U.S. authorities said Esther Billa Heacox, 41, the
wife of Navy Petty Officer James A. Heacox, was found stabbed to
death about three miles north of Clark Air Base.
   Master Sgt. James Katzman of the Clark Public Affairs Office
said Mrs. Heacox's body was found in a car after witnesses saw two
Filipino men fleeing from the vehicle, which had run off the road.
   The woman's husband, assigned to a Navy communications station
in nearby Tarlac province, said the victim was on her way to Clark
when she was killed. He said his wife's jewelry and about $150 were
missing.
   In Manila, a gunman wounded a Belgian diplomat and shot dead his
Filipino companion, Adorata Capistrano, in an apparent robbery
attempt Sunday near the Taal volcano, a tourist resort about 30
miles south of Manila, according to a Belgian Embassy official.
   He said Benoit Standaert, second secretary at the embassy,
suffered two gunshot wounds but was released from the hospital.
   Embassy spokeswoman Marie Louise Vanherk quoted police in
Batangas province as saying that they suspected robbery was the
motive because the gunman fled with Ms. Capistrano's purse.
   Nearly 40 people have been killed in communities around Clark
Air Base this year. Police say many of the killings were blamed on
communist rebels, who have been fighting to overthrow the
Philippine government since 1969 and have threatened to attack
American military personnel.
   Blackmer was the first American service member slain in the
Philippines since October, when the rebels killed two Air Force
enlisted men, a retired Air Force sergeant and a Filipino civilian
of U.S. ancestry.
   But a Filipino investigator who requested anonymity said the
style in which Blackmer was killed and the weapons used did not fit
the pattern of guerrilla atacks.
   A base spokeswoman, Air Force Capt. Maryellen Jaddick, said U.S.
authorities had not imposed any new restrictions on the nearly
26,000 American troops, Defense Department civilians and dependents
stationed at the base.
</TEXT>
