<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Officials Condemn Activists in Territorial Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenia's Communist Party leaders leveled an
unusually harsh attack Tuesday on activists who sought annexation
of an Armenian region in a neighboring republic, indicating the
activists could no longer count on high-level support.
   The party position, outlined in the Communist Party newspaper
Pravda, came after Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev gave a
hardline speech rejecting the transfer of Nagorno-Karabakh, a
mostly Armenian enclave in the republic of Azerbaijan, to the
jurisdiction of neighboring Armenia.
   Activists in Armenia and in the disputed region itself have been
pushing for the transfer since February, and Armenia's legislature
voted in June to accept the area.
   But Azerbaijani authorities opposed the idea, and the Kremlin
last week deemed annexation ``impossible.''
   Pravda reported Tuesday that party leaders in Armenia met a day
earlier to discuss ``the instigatory character of speeches at
meetings'' held in Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
   The leaders ``condemned the extremist, instigatory, politically
harmful speeches and urged ... all the ideological agencies to
launch effective efforts to expose the anti-people character ... of
the activists,'' Pravda reported.
   About three-quarters of Nagorno-Karabakh's 162,000 residents are
Armenians, and they have complained of discrimination at the hands
of Azerbaijani authorities. Armenians are mostly Christian, while
Azerbaijan is predominantly Moslem.
   Widespread general strikes and work stoppages that have
disrupted the disputed region for two months began subsiding
Monday, when Tass said 78 percent of the region's workers showed up
at their jobs.
   On Tuesday, more than 85 percent of the first-shift workers in
the 17 largest factories in Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh's main
city, reported for work, Tass said.
   It said all the region's factories, stores, service shops and
public transport agencies were working for the second day in a row.
   Some Armenians have vowed to continue the fight for annexation,
but central authorities have made it clear that police will come
down harder on future demonstrations or strikes.
   The Tass report from Stepanakert indicated Communist Party
leaders were conducting a mass campaign to persuade
Nagorno-Karabakh's residents that the Kremlin's rejection of their
demands was correct.
   Activists in Yerevan called last week for a five-day strike to
protest the July 18 decision by the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet, but most residents ignored the call.
</TEXT>
