<1ST_LINE>r p AM-KuninRuns     07-26 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kunin Runs,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Governor Announces Bid For A Third Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin has announced a bid
for a third two-year term, promising to work for a universal health
care plan similar to that recently adopted in Massachusetts.
   ``It's a basic need that must be met,'' the 54-year-old Democrat
said in a speech delivered Monday at Burlington's new community
boathouse. ``Every Vermonter has the right to good health care
services, and no Vermonter should be denied such services because
he or she can't pay for them.''
   Also on the agenda is implementation of a controversial law to
control growth, which Kunin championed during the last legislative
session. The law requires that communities planning for growth
follow specific guidelines. It also increased the property transfer
tax to help pay for planning.
   Kunin doesn't have a challenger in the September primary
election. She is likely to face House Republican Leader Michael
Bernhardt of Londonderry in November. Bernhardt also is unopposed
in the primary.
   Kunin said after her speech that she did not have a specific
plan to fund the health care program but suggested that it would be
funded jointly by the public and private sectors.
   The Massachusetts law requires the state by 1992 to arrange
pooled insurance for small businesses and individuals, which
participants can buy on a sliding fee scale based on income.
   The law also requires businesses with more than five full-time
employees to offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment
surcharge to help the state provide coverage to the uninsured.
   Kunin is a strong backer of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
the Democratic presidential nominee.
</TEXT>
