<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Hungary     07-26 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Hungary,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader Dampens Hopes for Soviet Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Grosz Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian Prime Minister Karoly Grosz dampened
expectations Tuesday of a unilateral withdrawal of Soviet troops
from his Warsaw Pact country, saying any withdrawal of the Red Army
should be linked to troop reductions elsewhere in Europe.
   Grosz said he had talked about the presenceof 65,000 Soviet
troops in Hungary with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and ``we
agreed to continue this discussion.''
   But in a speech and a news conference in Washington on Tuesday,
Grosz, who heads the Hungarian Communist Party, said, ``To withdraw
forces from Hungary, others would have to be disbanded as well.''
   He plugged hard for U.S. trade and promised widespread economic
and political reforms while acknowledging Hungary was plagued with
problems of alcohol and stagnant factories.
   Grosz said the Hungarian constitution would be revised next year
and that four times as many Hungarians were permitted to leave the
country to visit abroad in the first half of this year than in the
first six months of 1987.
   Grosz in May succeeded Janos Kadar, who took charge in Budapest
in 1956 as Soviet troops suppressed what Grosz called a
``counterrevolutionary'' uprising.
   He will see President Reagan on Wednesday and has spent a week
traveling in the United States sampling the products of capitalism
and committing Hungary to a more independent course than the
country followed under Kadar.
   Explaining Hungary's economic problems, Grosz said the country
had not moved fast enough on the political front to expand the
rights of the individual workers and factory managers to make their
own decisions.
   ``Political without economic reform, no, it's not possible,'' he
said, speaking through a translator.
   On the same theme, Grosz said, ``The two processes must be
fitted to each other. You cannot separate them practically.
Political and economic endeavors take place in one body.''
   He said writers were gaining more freedom and all Hungarians
were able to express their views, although the Communist Party also
retains the right to do so.
   At the same time, Grosz said works by Hungarian expatriates were
not permitted into the country ``if they are against the
constitution'' and that he was against removing Hungary from the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Speculation that Gorbachev would withdraw the Red Army
unilaterally from Hungary has circulated for at least a month. U.S.
officials, citing intelligence sources, kept the rumors moving. But
they have not panned out.
   Grosz's remarks suggested Gorbachev would blend any withdrawal
from Hungary into larger negotiations between NATO and the Warsaw
Pact on an overall reduction of conventional troops, armor and
aircraft in Europe.
   No date has been set for negotiations, with the chief stumbling
block a U.S. demand that the Soviets agree to hold simultaneous
talks about human rights improvements at home and in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
