<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Election 2ndLd-Writethru a0625 07-26 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Election, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0625,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Blames Shamir's Party for Palestinian Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs Restoring Shamir's first name and UPDATING
with high court decision on dispute. PICKS up 4th graf pvs bgng,
Aides to Peres ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres on Tuesday
accused Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of possibly missing a chance
to end the Palestinian uprising by not accepting the U.S. plan to
resolve the dispute.
   Legislators who spoke on condition of anonymity reported on the
shouting match in a closed-door meeting of the Defense and Foreign
Affairs Committee, which signaled the start of Israel's election
campaign.
   Also Tuesday, the Supreme Court rejected an appeal by the
governing Likud bloc to intervene in a pre-elections squabble,
paving the way for holding national and municipal elections on
separate dates, which Peres' left-of-center Labor party favors.
   Likud has asked the high court to intervene in Monday's
legislative decision to oust a Likud committee chairman who blocked
a bill separating national and local elections.
   The decision means the bill will probably pass, a defeat for
Likud, which had hoped to ride on the coattails of strong local
councils and win more votes to the parliament.
   Peres said Shamir's rightist Likud party inspired the
Palestinian uprising by rejecting Secretary of State George P.
Shultz's peace initiatives, which include an international Middle
East conference.
   Aides to Peres said he intends to make the peace negotiations a
central element in his campaign for the premiership in the November
elections.
   Peres' right-wing adversaries, led by Shamir, have also vowed to
make peace in the occupied territories central to the campaign, and
to attack Labor Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin for his failure to
quell the nearly 7-month-old Arab uprising, in which 233
Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed.
   Labor supports a retreat from the occupied territories in return
for peace, while Likud opposes any concessions to the Arabs. The
two parties have shared governmental powers after a 1984 coalition
agreement was forged to break an election stalemate.
   Peres opened the two-hour foreign policy briefing by lashing out
at Shamir, who implied that Labor sided with Egypt in a 1986
Israeli government decision to submit a border dispute to
international arbitration.
   Recent Israeli news reports said the arbitors may restore to
Egypt the strip of desert beach called Taba, which Israel seized
when it occupied Sinai in the 1967 Middle East War.
   ``This is the first time in my life that someone who also voted
for the arbitration tries to absolve himself of responsibility,''
Peres was quoted by Labor legislators as saying.
   Peres accused Shamir of ``missing a chance for peace'' by
failing to accept Shultz's plan.
   ``If it weren't for the sabotage of the peace process, of the
Shultz initiative, by half the government, then maybe we wouldn't
be in the middle of the intefadeh,'' Peres reportedly said, using
the Arabic word for ``uprising.''
   Likud legislator Eliahu Ben-Elissar interrupted Peres, shouting,
``You're not coming here with clean hands!''
   He called Peres a ``bolshevik,'' referring to the Labor Party's
left-leaning ideology.
   Peres responded by shouting at Ben-Elissar, ``You're always
slandering! You act like a fascist!'' according to Labor legislator
Micha Harish.
   Harish said the debate reflected the significance of the peace
issue in the election campaign. ``It will be without a doubt the
central issue,' he said.
   Pollsters predict a tight race between Labor and Likud, with the
latter holding a slight edge largely due to support for Israeli
hawkishness in response to the Palestinian uprising.
</TEXT>
