<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissileProtesters     07-26 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missile Protesters,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Of Peace Activists Sentenced For Iowa Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace activist Philip Berrigan was sentenced
to six months in jail Tuesday for trespassing on a Navy warship.
   ``You have eight prior felony convictions and at least nine
misdemeanor convictions ... because of that you have forfeited the
right to vote or be a candidate, to do things where you can make a
difference,'' federal Magistrate Tommy Miller said in setting the
maximum sentence.
   Miller ordered the courtroom cleared for the sentencing after
about three dozen Berrigan supporters began reading a statement in
unison.
   Berrigan, along with Gregory Boertje, 32, Andrew Lawrence, 27,
and Sister Margaret McKenna, 57, admitted boarding the battleship
Iowa during an open house at the Norfolk Naval Base, slipping away
from escorts and attacking two of the ship's cruise missile
launchers with hammers, boltcutters and vials of blood. They did
only minor damage to the armored launchers.
   The four claimed their action was the ``symbolic disarming'' of
nuclear weapons that they said were illegal under international law.
   Miller found all four guilty of misdemeanor trespassing in May.
   At Tuesday's sentencing, Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey M.
Wasileski said the sincerity of the four did not excuse their
actions.
   ``Mr. Berrigan's record shows 20 years of offenses in the name
of his cause,'' Wasileski said. ``It saddens the government that he
should so thoroughly reject the democratic process.''
   Berrigan offered no evidence or argument during the sentencing.
   Previously, Sister McKenna was placed on two years probation on
the condition she not enter a military establishment. Lawrence
received a 4-month jail sentence and Boertje six months.
</TEXT>
