<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Airliner-Report     07-26 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Report,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Will Release Unclassified Report on Downing of Iran Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon will release an unclassified
report on the downing of Iran Air flight 655 as soon as possible,
Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said Tuesday, but he declined to set
a date.
   Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty, who is supervising the
investigation, will prepare classified and unclassified versions of
the report on why the USS Vincennes shot down an Iran Air A300
Airbus with 290 people aboard on July 3. U.S. officials said the
ship mistook the airliner for an attacking F-14 fighter.
   ``The investigating group is working on a concurrent
unclassified version of the report in addition to the normal
classified report,'' Howard said.
   The report will go first to Fogarty's immediate superior, the
commander of U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, Gen. George B. Crist,
then to the Joint Chiefs of Staff and finally to Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci before it is released. Each layer in the command
structure usually takes a week to review such a report, Howard said.
   ``I don't have a timetable for release,'' said Howard. Fogarty,
originally asked to complete his investigation by July 15, was
granted an extension through the end of July.
   Howard said the Pentagon was trying to avoid the delay
experienced release of a report on an attack by an Iraqi fighter
against the USS Stark on May 17, 1987.
   ``In the case of the Stark investigation, it was five months
before the report was actually released. We'd like to do a better
job of getting it to you earlier,'' said Howard.
   The spokesman said it was ``unlikely'' that the report would be
released before Carlucci returns Aug. 8 from a trip to the Soviet
Union and Turkey.
</TEXT>
