<HEAD>Vanderbilt Heir Eulogized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and relatives on Tuesday eulogized
Carter Cooper, the Vanderbilt heir who committed suicide by leaping
from his mother's 14th-floor apartment despite her entreaties.
   First lady Nancy Reagan was among the dignitaries and
celebrities at the funeral at St. James Episcopal Church on
Manhattan's Upper East Side. The sky darkened and rain fell as the
service began. Cooper died Friday at age 23.
   The ceremony was closed, leaving reporters and onlookers outside
under umbrellas and awnings. Inside, one of Cooper's brothers and
three friends eulogized him during the 75-minute service, attendees
said.
   Mrs. Reagan and Gloria Vanderbilt, who is Cooper's mother,
embraced after the funeral in Mrs. Reagan's limousine. The women
are longtime friends.
   Cooper, who had been under treatment for depression, jumped to
his death from a window in Ms. Vanderbilt's Upper East Side
apartment Friday, police said. Son of the late Wyatt Cooper, he was
graduated last year from Princeton University and worked as a
magazine writer and editor.
   He was the third of Ms. Vanderbilt's four sons.
   Ms. Vanderbilt, known for the blue jeans that bear her name, is
the great-great granddaughter of railroad and shipping magnate
Cornelius Vanderbilt. She was dubbed ``the poor little rich girl''
after she became the focus of a heated custody battle in the 1930s.
