<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OldFaithful     07-26 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Old Faithful,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Faithful Yellowstone's Biggest Attraction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yellowstone Fire Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old Faithful Geyser,
shooting water hotter than 200 degrees as high as 184 feet in the
air, is Yellowstone National Park's most popular tourist attraction
and often is considered the symbol of the country's national park
system.
   The geyser is about 10 miles east of the 5,500-acre ``North
Fork'' fire, and firefighters are trying to help wind turn the
blaze from the area.
   While the geyser, one of more than 200 in Yellowstone, is not
the most powerful in the park, it is the best-known, attracting 78
percent of the park's visitors as it erupts 21 to 23 times a day at
intervals from 33 minutes to more than two hours.
   The geyser was discovered by an exploring party in 1870, two
years before the park was established by Congress.
   A geyser is a hot spring from which water and steam are ejected
periodically. The eruptions are caused by the contact between
ground water and rock that is hot enough to create steam.
   The Old Faithful Inn, built in 1904, was the first building in
the area, which now has three lodges, including one for use during
the winter.
   The inn, placed on the U.S. Department of the Interior's list of
national historic landmarks in 1987, was expanded in 1913 and 1927
to provide 324 rooms.
   Other accommodations at the site include the Old Faithful Lodge
cabins, providing 132 rooms, and the Old Faithful Snow Lodge, which
remains open in winter, with 65 rooms.
   Old Faithful is the one of two areas of the park open for winter
users who reach the area on cross-country skis or by snowmobile.
Mammoth Hot Springs is also open in winter.
   Other services at Old Faithful include a general store and two
service stations, one of which remains open in the winter. There
are no campgrounds in the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1702EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Wright-Ethics     07-26 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Ethics Panel Names Democratic Activist To Head Wright Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee named attorney
Richard J. Phelan to conduct an ethics investigation against House
Speaker Jim Wright, and Phelan, a prominent Chicago Democrat,
promised ``an independent, full review'' of allegations that Wright
abused his office for personal gain.
   Committee Chairman Julian C. Dixon, D-Calif., said Democratic
and Republican members of the evenly divided 12-member panel had
agreed on the selection of Phelan, and were satisified that he
could do an impartial job even though he has been active in
Democratic campaigns and fund raising.
   The committee is satisfied, ``notwithstanding the fact that he
has exercised his right (to political activity), based on his
ability and his reputation, that he can in this case be fair and
impartial,'' Dixon said.
   Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind., the panel's senior Republican,
concurred.
   Dixon said the committee had decided to hire outside counsel
when it formally opened its six-count investigation of Wright,
D-Texas, on June 9, but had withheld announcement of the decision
until someone was chosen for the job.
   The contract with Phelan's firm, Phelan, Pope & John, will be
for no more than $300,000, he said. Dixon said he could not
estimate how long the investigation will take to complete.
   ``As I see our job, it's to conduct an independent, full review
of all the facts that have been presented in the inquiry and report
back to the committee,'' Phelan told reporters in a brief
appearance outside the closed committee room.
   ``The fact that I'm a Democrat doesn't stand in my way of being
fair and full,'' he added. ``I would hope that no citizen would be
branded unfair or unobjective simply because he exercised his basic
American right.'' He said his selection was ``a great opportunity
for me, and I appreciate the confidence the committee had. I'm
going to do my very, very best.''
   But Dixon, in response to a question, said Phelan would not be
authorized to go beyond the scope of the six-count resolution of
inquiry unanimously adopted by the panel on June 9.
   That drew a complaint from Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., Wright's
chief accuser, who said no inquiry could be considered independent
if it does not permit investigators to follow leads to their
conclusions.
   ``The independent counsel has to be truly independent,''
Gingrich said. ``He cannot be on a short leash held by the
Democratic chairman of the committee.''
   Gingrich objected to the choice of Phelan, whom he called a
partisan Democrat. The Chicago lawyer has been a fund-raiser for
the presidential campaign of Democratic Sen. Paul Simon of
Illinois, according to an article in the January issue of the
American Lawyer.
   Phelan's selection also was criticized by Citizens for Reagan,
which sent a Mailgram to the committee saying, ``The appointment of
liberal Democrat activist Richard Phelan as outside counsel in the
Wright case certainly calls into question the independence of the
ethics committee inquiry.''
   Wright complained that Gingrich appears to be trying to set
impossible standards for the investigation so he can criticize it _
no matter what the outcome _ as a whitewash.
   ``Failing to have any substance on which to rely, they are
trying to lay the impression that the inevitable result of a clear
bill of health is somehow a whitewash,'' Wright said. ``They would
have said that no matter whom they chose'' as outside counsel, he
added.
   Wright is under formal investigation on charges of using his
office to lobby federal officials and others on matters in which he
had a financial interest, and for alleged improprieties in the
publication of a book by a campaign contractor for which Wright
received unusually high royalties, among other charges.
   Just a few hours before the announcment, the lobbying group
Common Cause asked the committee to demonstrate publicly that any
outside counsel will have authority and independence.
   The request, in a letter from Common Cause Chairman Archibald
Cox to Dixon, said that could be done by giving the investigator
full authority to investigate, review documents, issue subpoenas
and present evidence to the panel; to hire whatever staff is needed
to conduct the inquiry; and to recommend formal charges be brought
before the committee if warranted.
   The panel also should guarantee that the outside counsel ``shall
be free, after discussion with the committee, to make such public
statements and reports as the counsel deems appropriate,'' Cox said.
   Dixon declined to respond publicly to the Common Cause letter.
He said the panel had been considering Phelan as outside counsel
for several weeks and said the Chicago attorney had been
interviewed individually by all Republican and Democratic members
of the committee.
   Wright said he does not know Phelan, but added, ``apparently,
he's a reputable attorney.''
</TEXT>
