<HEAD>With AM-Yellowstone Fire Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire-prone Western states are especially susceptible to forest
and prairie fires this season because of drought. Here is a list of
some major fires that were still burning as of Tuesday and the
acreage destroyed:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALASKA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 fires over 1.2 million acres including:
   Waring Mountain, 207,000 acres.
   Livengood, 323,000 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ARIZONA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Arizona near St. George, Utah, 1,000 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sawtooth National Forest, 2,200 acres.
   Frank Church-River of No Return Wilderness, two fires.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OREGON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Deschutes River Canyon, 780 acres.
   Collier State Park, Chiloquin, 155 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTAH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area, Utah. 1,580 acres.
   East Grassy fire west of Tooele, 2,500 acres.
   Echo, 550 acres.
   Big Cottonwood Canyon, 38 acres.
   First Water fire, west of Price, 5-10 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WYOMING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Yellowstone National Park, twelve fires over 52,400 acres.
   Teton Wilderness, 24,400 acres.
