<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Jackson     07-26 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Camp Awaiting Word From Jackson Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top aides to Michael Dukakis said Tuesday they
expected Jesse Jackson to take a short vacation before campaigning
for the Democratic presidential nominee but that some Jackson aides
could join the Dukakis effort within days.
   ``We're talking about people at every level and things look real
good,'' said Donna Brazile, Dukakis' deputy national field
director. ``A lot of progress has been made since the convention.''
   Top Jackson aides were huddling Tuesday in Chicago to discuss
their future and Brazile said the Dukakis campaign expected to
receive a list of names of Jackson workers interested in working on
the fall campaign.
   ``We'll be talking to them in the next 24 hours and hopefully
we'll have something to announce within 72 hours or so,'' Brazile
said in a telephone interview.
   The Dukakis campaign has several state director posts vacant and
has said it will recruit Jackson organizers for some of them.
Brazile and Charlie Baker, the Dukakis campaign's national field
director, met with several Jackson field staffers Friday in Atlanta
before returning home from the Democratic National Convention.
   As for Jackson himself, Dukakis aides said no definite campaign
schedule has been worked out as yet.
   Joseph Warren, the Dukakis campaign secretary who has assumed
the added title of general election campaign coordinator, said it
was his understanding that Jackson wanted to take a brief vacation.
   ``We're anxious for him to get going but that hasn't been worked
out yet,'' said Warren, a college classmate of Jackson and the
ranking black in the Dukakis campaign.
   When Jackson does travel, Warren said he expected the money to
come from the Democratic Party because the trips will be focusing
on voter registration and related efforts more than direct
campaigning for Dukakis.
   ``But that has not been totally settled yet, either,'' Warren
said. ``We know that that we're going to find the money to get him
around.''
   Brazile said she has asked Jackson aides interested in joining
the Dukakis camp to express their interest soon so that the
campaign can draft its fall campaign payroll by early August.
   In addition, she said Dukakis and aides would use the next few
campaign trips to reach out to volunteers and elected officials who
supported Jackson during the primaries. Meetings are planned in
Cleveland and Milwaukee during the Dukakis campaign swing this
weekend, she said.
   Brazile, who worked for Jackson in 1984, said Dukakis has moved
to include Jackson supporters much faster than 1984 nominee Walter
Mondale.
   ``It took a long time for the Mondale people to get us on board,
late August,'' she said. ``We're in a much better position.''
</TEXT>
