<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VoodooGrave     07-26 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voodoo Grave,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Woman Believed Victim of Voodoo Obsession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A married woman missing for nearly two
months may have been killed and buried in a desolate grave beneath
a crude cross, the victim of her lover's suicidal obsession with
voodoo, police said Tuesday.
   Caroline M. Rubia's disappearance June 2 and the discovery of a
makeshift altar and mystical paraphernalia in her boyfriend's
closet have led detectives on a search through the strange
subculture of the primitive religion.
   Police theorize that Rubia, 52, was killed by her lover of 20
years, a roofing contractor who changed his name in 1979 from
Charles William Turner to Che Francois Toussaint.
   Toussaint, 47, was found dead in his bed of cyanide poisoning
when investigators broke into his barricaded home June 7 expecting
to find Rubia's body.
   Investigators found a crude altar and other items in his closet,
including three snapshots of Rubia covered with salt and three
one-quart Mason jars turned upside down with a strip of tape
labeled ``Me'' on one, a second labeled ``Carol Rubia'' with ``Stop
it!'' written underneath and a third reading ``Carol and I.''
   The jars were covered with salt and contained spices, peppers
and molasses. A recipe found in Toussaint's garbage can mixed
tartar powder, crushed red pepper and crosses.
   Investigators went to a Berkeley religion expert with the items.
They also presented the expert with desperate letters Toussaint
mailed before his suicide blaming Rubia and her ``witchcraft'' for
his bad health and business failures.
   The expert theorized Toussaint buried Rubia in a way that would
prevent her spirit from escaping. He said the grave likely would be
covered with salt and pins and that the victim's hands probably
would be tied.
   ``Salt and pins were to keep her spirit confined, even in death,
and that's why the expert was sure she was tied, too,'' said Young.
   Authorities are hoping the expert will help them find Rubia's
body.
   Her bloody prescription glasses were found in Toussaint's pickup
truck after he committed suicide.
   The Berkeley expert, a self-described ``good witch'' who police
did not name, told officers the items are those used in voodoo, an
African-born religion based on a belief in sorcery.
   The jars, molasses and spices were supposed to seal in bad
spirits and prevent them from attacking Toussaint, the expert said.
   ``He wanted a barrier between him and her in both worlds,''
Young said. Toussaint's ex-wife said Toussaint was fearful of
spirits when married to her and would cover her doll collection to
smother its power.
   Toussaint told friends Rubia was slowly poisoning him, said
Detective Sharon Young, of the San Jose Police Department's
missing-persons unit.
   Rubia attended a Catholic retreat shortly before her
disappearance at which she decided to leave her lover and devote
herself to her husband and family, Young said.
</TEXT>
