<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     07-26 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral of Sikh Officials Killed by Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of mourners chanted prayers
Tuesday as the bodies of the head priest of the Golden Temple and
another Sikh leader were cremated the day after they were slain by
extremists.
   The bodies of Sohan Singh, head priest of Sikhism's holiest
shrine in Amritsar, and Bhan Singh, a scholar and secretary of the
Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee, which manages the temple,
were borne in separate processions from their homes to the Golden
Temple.
   They were then laid out at nearby cremation grounds, where Sikh
rites and prayers chanted by 3,000 mourners accompanied the burning
of the bodies on funeral pyres.
   ``This is an attack on all Sikhs because the post of head priest
carries special status and honor among us,'' said former Sikh chief
priest Kirpal Singh, who performed the last rites.
   Sikh gunmen opened fire Monday on Sohan Singh, Bhan Singh and
Mal Singh Ghuman, another temple official, as they emerged from a
meeting at a college in Ludhiana, about 75 miles southeast of
Amritsar. Ghuman was seriously injured in the attack but was
reported out of danger Tuesday after surgery.
   The Khalistan Liberation Force and the Babbar Khalsa group _
both extremist groups _ claimed the killings in a handwritten note
found Tuesday outside the house of a journalist from a
Punjabi-language newspaper. The reporter asked that his name not be
used.
   Underground Sikh groups in the northern Punjab region have been
waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for an independent homeland.
   A.P. Pandey, a senior police official in Ludhiana, said the note
gave no clue to help in the statewide manhunt for the killers. He
said there had been no breakthrough in the case.
   On Tuesday, three more people, including two members of one
family, were killed in attacks blamed on Sikh extremists, United
News of India reported.
   The latest casualties raised the death toll to nearly 1,600 in
the guerrilla war this year.
   Militant Sikhs, who are a majority in Punjab but make up less
than 2 percent of India's population, charge they are discriminated
against by the majority Hindus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
