<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HijackingSuspect     07-26 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested in 1969 Hijacking Was Teacher's Aide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Haziine is cq; also Ey Tina cq in 16th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of helping hijack an
airliner to Cuba in 1969 worked as a preschool teacher's aide for
the last five years before authorities ended her 19 years as a
fugitive.
   Neighbors and her employer said Tuesday they were surprised to
learn that the quiet, friendly woman they knew as Haziine Eytina
had been using that name and 13 other aliases to keep the FBI off
her trail.
   ``We were just as shocked as everybody when the FBI was outside
with guns pointed at everybody,'' said Betty Bellino, director of
the Masterson Day Care Center a few doors away from Eytina's
apartment in a working-class neighborhood of Albany.
   Rifle-toting FBI agents surrounded the home of 39-year-old Linda
Joyce Grinage and her husband, lawyer Mylo Eytina, and took her
into custody Monday on a charge of air piracy, which carries a
sentence of 20 years to life in prison.
   The glum-looking Grinage, who wouldn't talk to reporters while
being led away in handcuffs from brief court appearances Monday and
Tuesday, had worked for five years as a bus monitor and teacher's
aide for Head Start, a preschool for low-income youngsters, said
Robert Burns, of the organization's board of directors.
   On Jan. 2, 1969, authorities say, Grinage and her then-husband,
Tyrone Ellington Austin, took a 2-year-old boy hostage on an
Eastern Airlines flight from New York's Kennedy International
Airport to Miami, then forced the pilot at gunpoint to fly to
Havana.
   The woman, who had an infant strapped to her back, ran up the
aisle of the plane screaming, followed by Austin shouting ``Black
power, Havana'' to terrified passengers and crew, according to news
accounts of the hijacking.
   It was unclear how Grinage returned to the United States, but
authorities said they lost track of her during the 1970s. Austin
died in 1971 from gunshot wounds suffered in a bank robbery attempt
in New York City.
   An anonymous phone caller tipped off authorities a year ago that
Grinage was living in Albany, and time was taken to nail down the
case, said Barbara Cottrell, an assistant U.S. attorney.
   Eytina said the charges against his wife were ``absolute
poppycock.'' He said his wife had lived and worked in Albany for 10
years, although police said they had only traced her Albany
residence to 1983.
   ``I think people should speak highly of me and my wife because
we've worked diligently to be spoken highly of,'' Eytina said
Tuesday, after a federal hearing to establish his wife's identity
was put off for one day.
   The couple had six children, but one was killed last year in an
auto accident, said Wayne Alford, a spokesman for the FBI's Albany
office. He said he didn't know how long the couple had been married.
   Grinage, who gave Head Start officials the name of Haziine Ey
Tina, had caused no problems at work, Burns said. He said officials
checked child abuse records and references and made an ``informal''
check with local police.
   ``If we had any indication that this was a hostage-taker, we
wouldn't be sitting here today,'' Burns said. ``There's nothing
significant in her five-year history that would indicate there was
any abuse or violence toward children.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
