<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Mills     07-26 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Mills,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Ambassador to Ecuador, Afghanistan and Jordan Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheldon Mills, a former U.S.
ambassador to Ecuador, Afghanistan and Jordan, has died of heart
failure at age 83.
   Mills died July 20 at the Valle Verde Retirement Community
complex, where he resided with his wife of 56 years, Francesca
Dekum Mills, said a spokesman at the McDermott-Crockett Mortuary,
which handled the private graveside services.
   Mills, born in Seattle, graduated from Reed College in Oregon in
1927. The following year, he was appointed as a U.S. Foreign
Service officer, launching a diplomatic career that spanned more
than 32 years.
   He was stationed in La Paz, Bolivia, from 1929 to 1931; in
Panama from 1931 to 1934; in Bucharest, Rumania, from 1934 to 1939;
in Santiago, Chile, from 1940 to 1943; in New Dehli from 1943 to
1946; at the State Department in Washington, D.C., from 1946 to
1949; in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 1950 to 1952; and again in
India from 1952 to 1954.
   In 1954, he started a two-year stint as ambassador to Ecuador.
He spent three years as ambassador to Afghanistan beginning in 1956
and concluded his career as ambassador to Jordan from 1959 to 1961.
   Mills was a member of the Channel City Club, the Cosmopolitan
Club, the Santa Barbara Council on Foreign Relations, the American
Foreign Service Association and Diplomatic and Consular Officials
Retired.
   In addition to his wife, survivors include three daughters,
Sheila Richter of St. Paul, Minn., Mary Presby of Los Angeles, and
Linda Sepprelle, who is working in the American Embassy in Rome,
Italy; seven grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
