<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-26 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAND SPRINGS, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smokey Tennison reads the business
section every day, edits a newspaper and plans to become president
of the United States someday.
   That is, if the 11-year-old doesn't take a shine to being host
of a late-night television program after he appears on ``The
Tonight Show with Johnny Carson'' this week.
   Smokey, who prefers suits and ties to jeans and T-shirts, is on
a campaign to keep his ``Garfield News'' alive at Garfield
Elementary School.
   He and some friends put together seven issues of the newspaper
during the school year.
   But Garfield Principal Denis Clark told Smokey he couldn't
distribute the paper at school this fall because of spelling
mistakes, lack of adult supervision and the amount of time Smokey
spent on the paper.
   Right now, one of his concerns, Smokey said, is what to wear on
the nationally televised program. He said he's leaning toward
wearing a suit, but definitely will wear a tie.
   ``Why don't you just look like a normal 11-year-old?'' asked his
mother, Sue Tennison.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>POTOMAC, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several residents of a Potomac neighborhood
say they are just as likely to hear a sermon preached on their
telephone lines as they are to hear the person on the other end of
the line.
   Carolyn Anderson is one of several residents who for the last
several years have picked up Christian broadcasts from a nearby
radio station on their telephones, home computers, home intercom
systems, and other electronic systems.
   ``I can hear it through the telephones all the time, everytime I
pick up the telephone,'' Ms. Anderson said. ``I've kept my
telephone conversations shorter because sometimes it's as loud as
the person I'm talking to.''
   The neighborhood, in the Bedfordshire section of Potomac, is
next to the Falls Road Public Golf Course, site of transmitting
towers for WCTN.
   John Vogt, executive vice president and general manager of WCTN,
said the problem is as frustrating for the station as it is for
residents.
   ``We definitely want to be a service to the community not an
annoyance,'' Vogt said.
   Ivy Pascal, a neighbor of Ms. Anderson, said once the broadcast
blared out of a bedroom telephone while it was on the hook.
   ``It was preaching hell and damnation, and I was lying on my bed
minding my own business. I had to unplug my phone,'' Ms. Pascal
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROOPVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birtie and John Weaver began their union
when Teddy Roosevelt was president and have seen it through two
World Wars, the advent of airplane phones, and more than 100
great-grandchildren.
   On Monday they celebrated their 81st anniversary.
   ``We think as much of one another as we did when we were
married,'' said Weaver, 96. Mrs. Weaver is 97.
   The Weavers have been nationally recognized as the
longest-married couple in the United States by Worldwide Marriage
Encounter, a non-profit organization.
   Their marriage began in defiance when as teen-agers, they eloped
from the disapproving frowns of her parents in rural south Georgia.
They took to back roads and finally found a justice of the peace
who consented to marry the young rebels.
   Six of the Weavers' 13 children are alive _ the oldest is 75 and
the youngest 45. The couple has about 50 grandchildren, more than
100 great-grandchildren and some 25 great-great-grandchildren.
   Neither of them had visited a hospital until their ninth decade,
and now they rely on daily visits from their children for meals and
household tending.
</TEXT>
