<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Palestinian     07-26 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Palestinian,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Identity Check for Palestinian Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian who may be linked with a
terrorist attack aboard a Greek cruise ship appeared in court
Tuesday, but the hearing was postponed after he claimed he had not
been briefed on the case.
   After the complaint, a new hearing to check the identity of the
Palestinian, identified as 39-year-old Mohammed Rashid, was set for
Aug. 2, a judicial spokesman said.
   Rashid was sentenced July 13 to seven months for entering Greece
on a forged passport. Greece is considering a U.S. request for his
extradition on charges of planting a bomb on a Pan Am jumbo jet
that killed a Japanese teen-ager and injured 15 in Hawaii in 1982.
   Police theorize that a machine gun and grenade attack against
the City of Poros cruise ship on July 11 was a bungled attempt to
hijack the ship and force Rashid's release.
   The assault left nine people dead and more than 90 injured.
   Tuesday's hearing before an appeal court prosecutor was a
routine procedure in cases where mistaken identity is claimed, said
the judicial spokesman, who requested anonymity in keeping with
Greek practice.
   Rashid claims his real name is Mohammed Hamdan and told
reporters at the court ``the Greek police arrested the wrong man.''
   He was arrested May 29 at Athens Airport while carrying a forged
Syrian passport in the name of Mohammed Hamdan.
   He was identified when his fingerprints matched those of Rashid,
who was jailed in Greece from 1973-76 on narcotics smuggling
charges, police said.
   Rashid also is accused of bombing a TWA jetliner over Greece in
April 1986. Four people, among them a baby girl, died when the
explosion blasted them out of the plane.
</TEXT>
