<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci-DefenseProbe     07-26 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-Defense Probe,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Chief Says He Will `Move Decisively'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Tuesday he will ``move decisively'' and quickly against defense
contractors implicated in the ongoing bribery investigation as soon
as he receives more details from the Justice Department.
   Carlucci has already ordered a number of changes in the way the
Pentagon buys weapons and more are likely as a result of the
investigation, he told the House Armed Services Committee.
   The Justice Department probe centers on allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of whom are former Pentagon
employes, bribed Defense Department officials for inside details
about contracts. No charges have yet been filed.
   Carlucci said he had no new details about the two-year-old
investigation, which became public June 14 when subpoenas were
served around the nation.
   At one point, Carlucci ordered contacts frozen on nine military
programs because of the possibility that they may have been
tainted, but he rescinded that order 10 days later when a quick
review showed there were no problems.
   Carlucci acted after an affidavit for a search warrant was
unsealed in Dallas, providing details about the Justice Department
investigation.
   The Justice Department has sought to have the affidavits sealed,
but several news organizations have challenged that action.
   Carlucci promised to ``move decisively ... as soon as we receive
facts from the Justice investigation.''
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the committee, noted that
``in the next few weeks, it is expected that the United States
attorney will authorize the release of information on the
investigation now under court seal.''
   ``When that information is available, the Department of Defense
will have more specifics on contracts or source selections that may
have been influenced by improper activities,'' he noted.
   Carlucci repeated his appeals to Congress to wait until all the
facts are made public before ordering sweeping overhauls in the
complicated Pentagon purchasing procedures.
   Carlucci said he meets daily with a special task force he set up
last month to track the investigation and recommend changes.
   ``My instructions do not limit the nature of the changes,'' he
said. ``Nothing is sacred _ neither organizational structure,
regulations, nor the need to change existing law.''
   Carlucci cast cold water on one proposal which has surfaced in
Congress _ holding corporate chief executives responsible for their
firms' actions. ``I think it's really impractical,'' he said, and
would probably only result in firms declining to bid for Pentagon
contracts.
   ``Ill-conceived reforms can quickly convince many firms that
defense business does not provide a sufficient chance for a
reasonable profit to make it worthwhile or compensate for the
perennial `stops and starts' of military business,'' he said.
   He said profit-and-earning ``ratios in the industry are alrady
low. If we drive them down further, industry will lack the capital
to keep up with modernization.''
   He also warned against wide-ranging bans that attempt to close
the so-called ``revolving door'' between government and private
employment, such as working for the Pentagon and then going to work
for a defense contractor.
   ``The problems we face in attracting into government service
talented individuals from the private sector would be exacerbated
by the imposition of a broad post-government employment bar,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
