<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pentagon-Drugs     07-26 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon-Drugs,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Reports Drug, Alcohol Abuse Declines In Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug and alcohol abuse in the armed forces is
steadily declining from the alarmingly high levels of 1980,
Pentagon officials said Tuesday.
   ``We are pleased with this latest decline, which can be
attributed to the message that has been sent out to all our
military personnel: If you want to stay in, you have to stay off
drugs,'' said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard.
   The percentage of military personnel acknowledgng the use of
illicit drugs in the 30 days prior to their being surveyed dropped
from 27 percent in 1980, to 19 percent in 1982, 9 percent in 1985
and 5.5 percent in 1988.
   Alarm bells rang when the results of the first drug survey were
released by the Pentagon in 1980. Comprehensive anonymous surveys
have been conducted in 1980, 1982, 1985 and this year.
   In the latest survey, conducted for the Pentagon by the Research
Triangle Institute, the 17,213 men and women taking part did not
put their names on the forms, and the exercise was not intended to
root out abusers. Those answering the questionaires were chosen to
provide a representative sampling of those in the armed forces by
age, sex, ethnic group, rank and branch of service.
   Military officials also conduct random urine tests of suspected
drug abusers, and those results also show a declining rate of use,
officials say.
   The most common illegal drug was marijuana, used by 3 percent
within the previous 30 days, down from 7 percent in 1985, and by 7
percent within the previous 12 months, down from 11 percent in 1985.
   Marijuana use was highest in the lower enlisted ranks, with 6
percent reporting use within the previous 30 days compared to 11
percent in 1985 and 15 percent within the previous 12 months,
compared to 19 percent in 1985.
   Drinking also fell in the military, according to the survey.
Heavy drinking, defined as consumption of five or more drinks at
least once a week, was reported by 9 percent, down from 12 percent
in 1985.
   And cigarette smoking was down to 57 percent who reported no
puffing in the previous 30 days, compared to 54 percent in 1985.
Twenty-three percent smoked a pack a day or more, compared to 27
percent in 1985.
   The final report, with a more complete breakdown of drug,
alcohol and tobacco use, was to be complete in December, Pentagon
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
