<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Palestinian Girl</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-12, with new info, Rabin comment, army confirming
death, more details of shootings. Pick up 6th pvs: According to
Arab...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops fatally shot a 13-year-old
Palestinian girl and wounded three youths during fighting Tuesday
in occupied Gaza City, Arab hospital officials reported.
   The army confirmed the girl's death but said it had not
determined the cause.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin toured a detention center in Gaza
and vowed to quell the eight-month old Palestinian uprising in the
occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   ``We don't accept the present level of violence,'' Rabin told
Israel television. ``On the contrary, today we have the methods. It
will take some time but we shall succeed.'' He did not elaborate.
   The military commander of the West Bank lifted a curfew that had
confined more than 120,000 Nablus residents to their homes since
last Thursday, the army announced.
   It said Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna took the action as a gesture of
goodwill for the holiday of Eid al-Adha, the Moslem Feast of
Sacrifice.
   In Gaza, 13-year-old Suheir Fuad Afana of the Beach refugee camp
was critically wounded when she was hit in the stomach by army
gunfire, said a Shifa Hospital surgeon. The girl died on the
operating table, according to the doctor, who spoke on the
condition he not be identified.
   Hospital officials said troops also shot and wounded three boys
ranging in age from 11 to 15 and that all three were hit in the
lower body.
   Army officials confirmed the death but said they were unable to
determine the cause because the family took the girl's body from
the hospital.
   They said an army unit sent to break up a riot in the Beach camp
opened fire when Palestinians ``hurled bricks at it from a close
distance.''
   The army said soldiers fired at the brick throwers and it was
checking to determine if the girl's death was a result of the
shooting.
   A curfew was imposed on the Beach camp, home to about 42,000
Palestinians.
   According to Arab reports, the clashes started about 6 p.m., and
protests continued for several hours after the girl was killed. An
Arab reporter said the body was brought back to the camp where
residents marched, shouting ``Allahu akbar!'' or ``God is great!''
   The fatality brought to 234 the number of Palestinians killed
since the Dec. 8 start of the uprising, in which four Israelis also
have died.
   In the West Bank, an army spokesman quoted Mitzna as saying he
lifted curfews after Arab leaders had appealed to the army's civil
administration to ease the restrictions.
   Right-wing Israeli settlers, who built their West Bank homes in
the heart of the Arab city of Hebron, warned of an escalation of
violence following a bomb blast earlier in the day.
   The settlers told Israel army radio they might retaliate for a
small, homemade bomb that caused no injuries when it exploded near
a playground.
   In the West Bank town of Beit Jalla, hundreds of Palestinians
mourned a man killed by soldiers Sunday.
   The mourners draped the dead man's home with outlawed
Palestinian flags, and chanted ``With our spirit and blood, we will
avenge the martyr!''
   Palestinians say Jeris Kunkar, 40, was an innocent passer-by who
was shot to death by troops chasing a stone-throwing group of Arab
youths. The army said Kunkar, who was hit by three bullets, was
shot when a soldier tripped and his gun fired accidentally.
   Troops stayed out of Beit Jalla during the service to reduce
tensions, Israeli radio said.
   In the predominantly Arab Israeli city of Jaffa, near Tel Aviv,
police arrested three Arab citizens suspected of destroying $1.25
million worth of Jewish property through vandalism and arson, the
Itim news agency reported.
   All of the damage was done during the Palestinian uprising, and
the suspects apparently were motivated by sympathies with the Arabs
in the occupied territories, Itim said.
</TEXT>
