<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese 1stAdd a0710 07-26 0979</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese, 1st Add, a0710,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: said Weld.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The judiciary committee, controlled by Democrats, said it wanted
to investigate the departures of Burns and Weld to determine
whether operations of the department were affected by Meese's legal
troubles.
   Weld said that on the morning he and Burns resigned, the
criminal division chief told Meese:
   ``Ed I don't gainsay that there are other reasons why you might
have wanted to push these two projects (a $32 million engine
contract for Wedtech and the Iraqi oil pipeline) _ redeem the
campaign pledge in the South Bronx, save our cities, peace in the
Middle East. That is not the question.''
   ``The question,'' Weld said he conveyed to the attorney general,
``is whether Mr. Meese is taking official actions that he knows are
going to redound to the financial benefit of his friend'' Wallach.
   Meese ``did a lot for Mr. Wallach. No doubt he was front and
center'' for Wallach, said Weld.
   ``Mr. Meese took unusual actions to advance the ends requested
of him by Mr. Wallach,'' said Weld.
   In connection with the Iraqi oil pipeline project involving
Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport, ``Mr. Wallach within two hours of
being retained by Mr. Rappaport calls up Ed Meese,'' said Weld.
``There's no doubt in Mr. Wallach's mind about why he has been
retained. Mr. Meese understands that he's been retained by Mr.
Rappaport. Mr. Wallach says `help us with this pipeline.''' Meese
arranged a meeting for Wallach with National Security Adviser
Robert McFarlane and the attorney general met briefly on the
pipeline project with then-Prime Minister Shimon Peres.
   Weld also commented on the $150,000 payment from Rappaport for
Wallach's service which Wallach directed be sent directly to Chinn,
who in effect combined it with Meese's and other investors' money
to obtain hard-to-get brand-new stock issues. Weld said he knew in
April 1987 that Wallach had gone to Meese and told the attorney
general, ``I am worried about how this looks.''
   According to McKay's report issued earlier this month, Meese
testified that Wallach ``was somewhat apprehensive that ... someone
would think that there was something strange about'' the payment.
   Wallach had not reported the $150,000 on his tax return, a fact
which McKay said Wallach ``apparently made no mention'' of to Meese
or Rappaport, said McKay's report. Weld noted that Meese ``did not
relay that conversation (about the disposition of the $150,000) to
anybody else.''
   Even Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, was critical of Meese's
relationship with Wallach, but he placed the blame all on Wallach,
saying ``I don't think he was a good friend.'' Of Meese, Hatch
said, ``I don't think there is a dishonest bone in his body. He was
done in by his friends.''
   When Hatch challenged Burns' assertion that morale was low in
the department because of McKay's investigation of Meese, Burns
replied, ``There is no way one can draw down the shade.''
   ``As time went on, it became apparent to me that morale at the
Department of Justice was deteriorating rapidly,'' Burns said in
his prepared testimony. ``I heard complaints everywhere. I heard
stories of employees being embarrassed and ridiculed. One employee
had to leave a party of friends when the personal abuse became
intolerable. Graffiti containing obscenities appeared in the very
halls of the Justice Department. One Justice Department employee
was upbraided by a desk clerk at a hotel on checking in because he
was associated with the Meese Justice Department.''
   ``I say `big deal,''' Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., responded.
Humphrey dismissed the abuse at a party and being upbraided by a
desk clerk as the kind of criticism that is leveled in a time of
great public controversy.
   Asked by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., what they would have done
had they come under criminal investigation, Burns said he would
have ``seriously considered'' stepping aside while Weld said have
``seriously thought about the leave of absence route.''
   Burns said he decided last November that he would leave in
January, and Weld said the issue first came up in a discussion
between the two men in December.
   ``He was more concerned than I at the outset'' about problems
the probe of Meese was causing the Justice Department, Weld said.
``In the end, I passed'' Burns ``on the outside lane'' in terms of
concern leading to a decision to resign.
   Weld said he discussed resignation with Solicitor General
Charles Fried, the department's No. 4 official, the day before
Weld's departure. Weld agreed with a characterization by Humphrey
that he ``planted'' the idea of resigning with Fried, but said he
did not suggest it.
   Regarding their decision to resign the same day, Weld said he
and Burns were ``trying to steer a middle course'' between leaving
silently and holding a news conference on the Justice Department
steps announcing they were quitting in protest. The two remained
silent about their reasons for resigning until the judiciary
committee session.
   Regarding the early April meeting in which he urged Meese to
distance himself from Meese, Burns said the attorney general told
him that Wallach ``is going to be in my office tomorrow morning''
returning from overseas. ``I don't know if Mr. Meese did or he
didn't'' meet with Wallach subsequently, said Burns.
   Because he felt there were obvious violations of ethics
regulations, ``I would have taken a hike whether or not I felt it
was over the line,'' Weld said of his resignation.
   Weld called the Arpil White House discussion with Reagan and
Bush ``a fairly grim meeting'' while Burns said ``things were very
frank and very candid in the extreme.''
   When Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, questioned Weld about who
might have leaked the substance of the White House meeting with
Reagan the day after it occurred, Weld responded, ``I did nothing''
and insisted he ``did everything to prevent it.'' When pressed
about leaking details of private conversations with the president,
he responded, ``Twern't me.''
</TEXT>
