<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Korea     07-26 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Korea,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Orders Flags Lowered on 35th Anniversary of Korean War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan met with a group of veterans
of the Korean War on Tuesday and ordered flags flown at half staff
on Wednesday in remembrance of the cease-fire that ended the
conflict 35 years ago.
   Reagan met with members of the Korean War Veterans Memorial
Advisory Board and others. Retired Army Gen. Richard Stilwell is
chairman of the board.
   He also issued a proclamation declaring the current week as
National Week of Recognition and Remembrance for Those Who Served
in the Korean War.
   He ordered the flags flown at half staff ``as a symbol of our
gratitude to those who died as a result of their service in Korea
and of our steadfast commitment to preserving the values for which
they fought.''
   ``As we approach the 35th anniversary of the cease-fire that
marked the end of active combat in the Korean War, it is
appropriate that we take time to remember and express our gratitude
to those who served in that fierce conflict,'' the president said.
   Reagan's actions were requested in a resolution passed by
Congress.
   Congress two years ago approved construction of a Korean War
Veterans Memorial, to be located on the Mall southeast of the
Lincoln Memorial.
   Construction is likely to be completed early in the next decade.
</TEXT>
