<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Opposition     07-26 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Opposition,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Opposition Parties Unite to Challenge Gandhi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Indian opposition parties announced
Tuesday they will merge to challenge Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's
governing Congress Party.
   The announcement was made by V.P. Singh, a former defense
minister and leader of the Jan Morcha, or the People's Forum.
   Singh said the new party ``would spare no efforts ... to fulfill
the aspirations of the people of India, who are today groaning
under the corrupt and authoritarian rule of the Congress.''
   Singh, a former Gandhi ally turned foe, defeated the Congress
Party candidate for a seat in Parliament in a June by-election in
Uttar Pradesh state.
   The united opposition party, to be called the Samajvadi Janata
Dal, or Socialist People's Party, will be formed by Aug. 15, Singh
said. The decision came after meetings with leaders from Singh's
party, the Janata Party, the Lok Dal and the Congress-S Party. The
Congress-S is a splinter group of Gandhi's party.
   ``The merger will shake these gentlemen a bit _ these Congress
wallahs,'' said veteran opposition leader Biju Patnaik. ``Wallah''
is Hindi for man.
   The new party is expected to field candidates in parliamentary
elections to take place before January 1990.
   Major opposition parties merged into the Janata Party to defeat
the Congress in general elections in 1977, but the government
served only two years of its five-year term.
   The Parliament dissolved in 1979 after the coalition split and
bickered over the choice for prime minister.
   Patnaik said the leadership of the new party has not been
decided.
   The four parties control only two of India's 25 state assemblies
_ northern Haryana and southern Karnataka _ and their members hold
just 21 seats in the 544-member law-making lower house of
Parliament.
   Gandhi's Congress Party holds more than 400 seats in the lower
house, but its fortunes have been declining since it swept to
victory in the 1984 general elections.
   The Congress Party has lost 10 of 14 state elections held since
then. It also lost four of the seven Parliament seats in the
by-elections.
   Much of the Congress Party's decline has been blamed on
allegations of inefficiency and corruption in government.
   News media and opposition politicans have alleged that kickbacks
were paid on major defense contracts and that some money may have
gone to Gandhi allies. The Congress Party has denied that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
