<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-26 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Scatter Rain, Some Hail over Central, Eastern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms scattered rain and hail over much of the central
and eastern portions of the country Tuesday, but rainfall amounts
were mostly moderate.
   In the South, showers and thunderstorms covered northern
Louisiana, southeastern Arkansas and northwestern Mississippi, as
well as northwestern Florida. Alexandria, La., received just under
three-quarters of an inch of rain in six hours.
   Thunderstorms also stretched from the lower Great Lakes to New
England and down across the central Appalachians. Hail up to one
inch in diameter pelted Wernersville, Pa., while Elmira, N.Y.,
recorded 0.88 inch of rain in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Rain diminished in the central Plains during the morning, but
thunderstorms were scattered over southern Kansas and northeast
Oklahoma in the afternoon.
   Thunderstorms in northeastern South Dakota dropped half-inch
hail and heavy rain on Aberdeen, and storms also were reported in
Nevada.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures around the nation ranged from 62
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., and North Bend, Ore., to 108
degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The nation's overnight low was 42
degrees at Pacific City, Ore., and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms to
extend from the Atlantic Coast to the Appalachians, and from
Georgia and Florida to Mississippi and southeast Louisiana.
Scattered showers also were predicted for the eastern part of Upper
Michigan and central Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s and 80s were forecast in much of the East, from
the Great Lakes to New England and the Middle Atlantic states, and
in the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. Highs were forecast to reach 100
degrees or more in northern and central Texas and eastern Montana,
and up to 115 through the desert Southwest. Highs in most other
parts of the nation were expected to be in the 90s.
</TEXT>
