<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SteakBoneStabbing     07-26 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steak Bone Stabbing,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Sentenced In Stabbing With Steak Bone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUTLER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison inmate was sentenced to 10
years in prison for stabbing another prisoner with a steak bone,
and as a result of the attack inmates in solitary confinement don't
eat T-bone steaks any more.
   A Union County jury Monday convicted Miguel Menendez of
aggravated assault and possession of contraband in the Nov. 11,
1987, stabbing of Fidel Campos at Union Correctional Institution
near Raiford.
   Menendez was sentenced to 10 years for each conviction. The
sentences will be served concurrently.
   Campos was stabbed with the sharpened bone from a T-bone steak
that had been served the previous night to Menendez and other
inmates in solitary confinement, according to court testimony.
   Campos was stabbed in his back and leg and was treated at a
hospital.
   Sgt. M.S. Vinci, who witnessed the attack, testified in the
trial that T-bone steaks should not have been served to inmates
confined for disciplinary reasons.
   ``It was an oversight, passing this kind of bone on to
confinement inmates,'' he said.
   As a result of the attack, the Corrections Department
implemented a new policy that prohibits T-bone steaks and pork
chops with bones from being served to inmates in solitary
confinement, said Paula Tully, a department spokeswoman. Food
service policy did not previously specify cuts of meat that should
not be served.
   Steaks are served to inmates once every six weeks, she said.
   Menendez claimed he stabbed Campos in self defense after the
inmate threatened him and swung a razor blade at him in an exercise
area. Menendez said he found the bone on the ground as Campos
approached.
   He is currently serving a 15-year sentence for trafficking in
cocaine. According to Department of Corrections records, Menendez
entered prison on Dec. 31, 1986.
   Carol Roney, a deputy court clerk in Union County, said Menendez
will not begin serving the new sentences until he completes his
current term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
