<2ND_LINE>AM-GSA Bribery,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GSA Official And North Carolina Businessmen Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Services Administration official and
the heads of a North Carolina business were indicted Tuesday by a
federal grand jury on conspiracy, fraud and bribery charges,
according to U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens.
   Named in the seven-count indictment were Lester H. Finotti Jr.,
chief of the accounts management and claims branch of the GSA's
Office of Transportation Audits; William H. White, Jr., president
Southern Investment Co., of Fayetteville, N.C., and Carmine W.
DePietro, the company's executive vice president.
   According to the 23-page indictment, the North Carolina
businessmen paid more than $24,000 over an 18-month period from
March 1985 to September 1986 to Finotti in exchange for his help in
advancing the business interests of Southern Investment. The pair
also provided Finotti with the use of a 1985 red Thunderbird, the
indictment alleged.
   Operating as a factoring agent, the North Carolina-based company
purchased the government bills of lading issued by transportation
companies shipping goods and equipment for the federal government.
According to the indictment, the company bought the bills from
transportation companies at a discount and submitted them to GSA
for payment at face value.
   Finotti was charged with manipulating payment of government
bills of lading for the benefit of Southern Investment.
   White, 59, of Pinehurst, N.C. and Fredericksburg, Va., and
DePietro, 53, also of Fredericksburg, were each charged with one
count of conspiracy to defraud the United States and one count of
bribery of a public official.
   Finotti, 56, of Waldorf, Md., was charged with one count of
conspiracy to defraud the United States, one count of accepting a
bribe, three counts of conflict of interest and one count of making
a false statement on his financial disclosure forms.
</TEXT>
