money for recruiting the support of American dissidents.
   The state has based much of its arguments on information
supplied by two unnamed informants but has so far failed to charge
Hawamda or seven other people arrested in the case last week.
   Bryan said he was convinced Hawamda had sufficient ties in the
United States that he would not flee the country pending resolution
of the case.
