<DOCNO> AP880726-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TumorTreatment     07-26 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tumor Treatment,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Fights Brain Cancer With Innovative Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AH1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager fighting the most malignant type
of brain tumor is being treated with a relatively new technique
that involves inserting tubes and radioactive beads into his head.
   Michael Anderson, 18, was a week away from graduating from
Wolbach High School this spring when he suffered a seizure. Doctors
found he had a brain tumor just under 2 inches in diameter.
   Dr. Kevin Shewe, a radiation oncologist at Omaha's Clarkson
Hospital, said standard therapy for the fast-growing tumor is
surgery followed by radiation and chemotherapy, but the average
patient survives only 40 to 50 weeks.
   About 20 percent of patients live two years; none has survived
five.
   The new procedure combines surgery, chemotherapy and external
and internal radiation, and doctors hope it will increase
Anderson's survival rate.
   Preliminary tests on the newer treatment indicated the median
survival time for patients has been extended to 87 weeks, Shewe
said.
   The treatment is a five-step process, Shewe said.
   The first involves completing in three weeks rather than six the
external radiation given before surgery. The compact treatment time
may increase the effectiveness, Shewe said. The second step,
chemotherapy, takes place concurrently, the doctor said.
   Step three is surgery to remove the tumor.
   Step four for Anderson began when tiny radioactive beads were
inserted through his scalp and into the center and around the tumor
site to attack any remaining tumor cells, doctors said.
   The procedure utilizes sophisticated imaging equipment that
shows cross-sections of the brain and a computer that helps plot
the precise location of the tumor site.
   Neurosurgeon John Greene drilled seven tiny holes in the skull
and inserted seven tubes, or catheters, each less than a tenth of
an inch in diameter. Each of the tubes was glued to a tiny button
sewn to the scalp to hold it in place.
   A brain scan ensured the catheters were correctly positioned,
and Shewe then inserted the radioactive beads. The radioactive
materials remain at the tumor site for 96 hours before being
removed.
   Anderson is scheduled to go home this week. He'll return for
chemotherapy once every six weeks for a year, the fifth step in the
therapy.
   Use of the implant began in 1977. In 1980, doctors first used
the insertable catheter tubes with removable caps.
   And in 1983, at the University of California at San Francisco,
doctors began to use the implants to treat patients with so-called
``high-grade tumors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     07-26 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All-Night Talks Conclude With Hints of Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weary negotiators went home to sleep Tuesday
after 20 hours of talks and a mediator's deadline failed to produce
a settlement in the Writers Guild strike that has crippled
Hollywood.
   Representatives of the Writers Guild of America and the Alliance
of Motion Picture and Television Producers broke off talks about 11
a.m. Tuesday. The talks, which featured two federal mediators, had
begun at 3 p.m. the day before.
   One of the mediators, Floyd Wood, district director for the
Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, said no new sessions
were scheduled. He declined to discuss what had happened in the
talks or characterize them in any way.
   On Monday, Wood had set a midnight deadline for an end to the
talks, but declined to say what he would do if the no settlement
was reached by that time. When the hour came, he extended the
deadline.
   The series of talks that began Saturday were the first between
full bargaining teams for both sides in a month.
   Del Reisman, co-chairman of the WGA's negotiating committee,
said Tuesday that he was neither ``discouraged nor encouraged'' by
the contract talks. The WGA strike, which began March 7, is now
entering its 21st week.
   Both sides in the strike have been asked by a federal mediator
to maintain a news blackout, and detailed information about the
bargaining sessions has been scant.
   But a source familiar with the talks, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said there were some signs of progress Tuesday. The
source indicated that the WGA and the producers had begun to
address in earnest the divisive issue of television residual
payments.
   Throughout the protracted strike, which has led to sweeping
layoffs in Hollywood, the writers and the producers have disagreed
sharply over payments for one-hour television shows rebroadcast
domestically and all television programs rebroadcast overseas.
   Brian Walton, executive director of WGA West, said the talks had
left him drained, and that he was going home to sleep.
   The union said it was proceeding with plans to picket the
offices of television producer Aaron Spelling and Warner Bros. and
Columbia studios Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, a collection of some of Hollywood's top writers are
taking out full-page advertisements in Wednesday's issues of
entertainment industry newspapers in a show of support for guild
leaders.
   The advertisement is signed by 150 writers, directors and
producers, including makers of the television shows ``Family
Ties,'' ``Cheers'' and ``thirtysomething,'' and the films ``Down
and Out in Beverly Hills'' and ``Sunset Boulevard.''
   It is being published in response to actions by a group of
dissident writers who are threatening to resign from the WGA if the
strike is not ended immediately.
   ``I signed the ad because I was afraid that the producers
alliance might be waiting to see what the fallout would be, who
would break ranks,'' said Allan Burns, a creator of the ``Mary
Tyler Moore Show.'' ``The alliance shouldn't count on anyone
breaking ranks.''
   Lionel Chetwynd, a spokesman for the dissident group, the
Writers Coalition, dismissed the advertisement Tuesday. And he said
his group feared that the recess of negotiations may mean that
contract talks have collapsed.
   ``We're very pessimistic,'' Chetwynd said. ``We are horrified
that after all these talks, they can't close a deal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
