<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GerneySettlement 1stLd-Writethru a0694 07-26 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gerney Settlement, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0694,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brigitte Gerney to Get Nearly $10 Million over 20 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `She said...', with
background on how settlement reached, who took part. Picsk up 8th
graf pvs, Palmieri, 54...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose legs were crushed when a
construction crane collapsed on her and whose bravery during the
rescue won the nation's admiration will collect nearly $10 million
for the injuries she suffered.
   Brigitte Gerney will receive $1 million immediately, $27,625 a
month for a year, then the same monthly payment for the rest of her
life with a compounded 3 percent increase each year, it was
announced Tuesday.
   Mrs. Gerney, 52, was injured in May 1985 when a 35-ton crane,
operated by an unlicensed worker, fell on her legs as she passed a
site where a 42-story apartment house was being built.
   She told of the pain she went through when she testified at the
trial of Lino Palmieri, the site foreman, and Crimmins Construction
Co., the company Palmieri worked for.
   ``I heard all the bones cracking,'' she said. ``I screamed for
help. `Help me! Help me! Get me out!'''
   She said she lay beneath the crane for six hours, in agony and
with her legs crushed, while Detective Paul Ragonese pleaded with
her to hang on to life.
   The payment, which settles a lawsuit filed by Mrs. Gerney
against Crimmins and a number of other defendants, was reached
after a session Monday in the courtroom of a New York trial judge,
David B. Saxe. The judge offered guidance to the participants but
did not hold a formal hearing.
   The money is to be paid to Mrs. Gerney through an annuity the
defendants are setting up with an insurance company. The defendants
in the lawsuit include the city, Crimmins, and several other
construction-related companies.
   The suit was filed shortly after the criminal case ended in
spring 1986.
   Palmieri, 54, was fined $5,000, put on five years' probation and
ordered to perform community service for allowing an unqualified
person, Richard Ricciardi, to operate the crane. Crimmins
Construction was fined $10,000.
   Ricciardi, 31, pleaded guilty to second-degree assault, was
sentenced to a few months in jail and was placed on probation.
   Mrs. Gerney underwent at least seven operations on her legs.
President Reagan called her during her recovery and Nancy Reagan
visited. Mayor Edward I. Koch threw a party for her.
   The settlement said that in the event of Mrs. Gerney's death,
her estate will receive the money for a minimum of 20 years. The
total for a 20-year period would be $9,906,738. Her life expectancy
is 29 years, said her lawyer, Robert Conason.
   Mrs. Gerney could not be reached for comment and Conason would
not disclose her whereabouts. ``She's a very private person,'' he
said. ``She instructed us to say nothing.''
</TEXT>
