<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-IPI,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IPI Protests South African Registration of Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Press Institute said Tuesday it
has written South African President P.W. Botha protesting his
nation's plan to require the registration of journalists.
   The institute, which has about 2,000 journalists, editors and
publishers among its members, said the step increases the South
African government's ``already deplorable degree of control over
the media.''
   IPI director Peter Galliner urged Botha to withdraw the
``repressive'' policy saying it would ``allow the government to
have ultimate control over who may practice as a journalist.''
   Under regulations published June 10 by the South African
government, anyone carrying out ``news agency'' business must be
registered with the government beginning July 31 or face a 10-year
prison term or a $10,000 fine.
