<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Mine     07-26 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Mine,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Begin To End Mine Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mine workers and the government held
negotiations Tuesday aimed at ending a nationwide strike affecting
Peru's silver production, officials said. No progress was
immediately reported.
   The National Federation of Mine, Metal and Steel Workers and the
Labor Ministry said the first negotiations since the strike began
July 18 were held Monday and Tuesday.
   The federation, which claims to represent 75 percent of Peru's
estimated 80,000 to 100,000 mine workers, said strikers are
demanding that all labor contracts for individual unions be
negotiated jointly.
   The federation said more than 90 percent of the mining industry
has been paralyzed by the strike. Industry analysts, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the figure was closer to 60 percent.
   Peru is the world's second leading producer of silver behind
Mexico and a major source of copper, lead, zinc and gold. Mining
traditionally accounts for half of Peru's exports.
   The government said last week it would not sign new sales
contracts for state-controlled silver, about 42 percent of the
nation's annual output of 60 million ounces, in an effort to boost
its dwindling foreign reserves.
   Peru's decision to boost its dwindling reserves is part of an
effort to secure credits to combat consumer shortages and help the
economy by importing food and capital goods.
   The government hopes to use its silver reserves as security to
finance up to $600 million in import credits, the official gazette
El Peruano reported Tuesday.
</TEXT>
