<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BritainTax 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain Tax, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0761,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Property Tax Bill Survives Challenge in House Of Lords</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf pvs, But Lord ... to fix spelling of Hailsham.
No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A property tax bill completed its stormy passage
through Parliament Tuesday when the House of Lords backed down from
threats to amend it.
   The House of Lords, the unelected upper chamber of Parliament,
decided without a vote to not act on some members's demands that
changes be made in the measure. Opponents of the bill said the
proposed flat-rate community tax is unfair to the poor.
   ``The government themselves are likely to come to regret today's
decision,'' said Lord Allen of Abbeydale.
   The bill is expected to be approved later this week by Queen
Elizabeth II.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher pledged in the 1987 election
campaign to revise the system of local property taxes known as the
``rates'' that help finance local governments.
   Advocates of the new plan said the old rates system was unfair
because the burden was not shared equally, falling on local
businesses and some householders while other people paid nothing.
   The new measure will replace the rates with a flat-rate system
of payments. Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative Party government calls
the new system a community charge to be paid by almost everyone.
Critics said it will especially hurt the poor because, unlike a
graduated income tax, it takes no account of a person's ability to
pay.
   The House of Lords withdrew its challenge to the measure in the
face of a constitutional clash with the elected House of Commons.
The Commons approved the proposal in April.
   The House of Lords has no power to interfere with the
government's taxation legislation but can delay enactment of other
laws for up to 13 months.
   Members of the House of Lords who wanted to ammend the tax
measure said the bill did not come under the House of Commons'
``financial privilege'' because it affected local government.
   ``Though we should respect Commons financial privilege with the
greatest care, we should also respect our own privileges and
feelings and should not allow them to be eroded or diminished,''
said Lord Henderson of Brompton during the debate that lasted
nearly three hours.
   But Lord Hailsham said the House of Commons always had claimed
privileges when introducing general taxes. ``It is the duty of any
(government) minister to insist on privilege and give no further
reasons'' for rejecting amendments by the House of Lords, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880726-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marcos-Offer     07-26 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos-Offer,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Denies Report of $5 Billion Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
on Tuesday denied a newspaper report that he offered the Philippine
government $5 billion to allow him to return to his homeland
without fear of criminal prosecution.
   ``My going home depends on principle, not cash,'' Marcos said.
``Yes, negotiations are going on, as they have for the past several
months, but money is not involved.''
   Later, through a spokesman, Marcos indicated he wouldn't discuss
details of the negotiations, on the advice of his attorney. He said
he had records that could prove he didn't offer any money.
   A professor quoted in the story published by the Los Angeles
Times on Tuesday also said it was inaccurate.
   A. James Gregor, political science professor and Philippines
expert at the University of California at Berkeley, was quoted by
the Times as saying Marcos offered to return $5 billion to the
Philippines, support President Corazon Aquino and stay out of
politics to ensure his return to his home province of Ilocos Norte.
   ``I heard that figure second- or third-hand during a meeting
with a Philippine official,'' Gregor said. ``I have no direct
knowledge of money being offered by anyone. I have heard figures,
but indirectly, ranging from $250 million to $20 billion.''
   Tom McCarthy, the night news editor in the Times' Washington
bureau who edited the story, stood by the report.
   ``It accurately reflects what we were told by him (Gregor) and
other sources,'' he said.
   Marcos has been living in Hawaii since he was deposed in
February 1986. The Philippines is trying to recoup billions of
dollars Marcos allegedly siphoned out of the country during his
reign.
   Gregor said Tuesday he met in June in Washington with members of
Congress as well as Philippine ambassador Emmanuel Pelaez to
discuss ways to negotiate Marcos' return. It was during a meeting
that included Pelaez that money was mentioned, he said.
   Gregor said he advised U.S. and Philippine officials against
indicting Marcos in the United States because it would set a
dangerous precedent for future political exiles. Instead, he
suggested that Marcos be allowed to return to his homeland as long
as he promised he and his family would stay out of politics.
   Pelaez sent the suggestion to Mrs. Aquino even though he favors
prosecuting Marcos for allegedly taking funds from the Philippines,
Gregor said.
   Gregor said he saw one document during the negotiations that was
addressed to Mrs. Aquino and signed by Marcos. He said it did not
mention any payment.
   A State Department spokesman said Tuesday the United States was
not involved in the negotiations but that Marcos would have to get
permission to return from the Philippine government before the
United States would let him leave Hawaii.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
