<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-UN 2ndLd-Writethru a0763 07-26 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-UN, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0763,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Begins Urgent Talks On Cease-fire With Iranian Minister</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for 3rd graf pvs, Both men ... to UPDATE with
meetings ending for the night, Iranian minister saying Iran will
teach Iraq ``a lesson'' if attacks don't end, details. Pickup 4th
graf pvs, Perez de ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. secretary-general met twice with
Iran's foreign minister Tuesday in the first formal round of talks
to put a cease-fire into effect in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq War.
   Ali Akbar Velayati said after the first afternoon meeting with
U.N. chief Javier Perez de Cuellar that the talks were
``constructive and fruitful'' and covered the steps to carry out a
truce and peace plan.
   Perez de Cuellar has said he hopes next week he can announce the
dates for a cease-fire.
   ``We are trying to set a timetable for the implementation plan
of the secretary-general and we also talked about the recent
escalation of the war on our border with the Iraqis,'' Velayati
told reporters at the end of second talks Tuesday night.
   ``We said (to the secretary-general) that if they continue their
attack, we will give them a lesson that they won't forget,''
Velayati said.
   Perez de Cuellar is to hold separate talks with Velayati and
Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz on Wednesday. The U.N. chief said
he dispensed with formalities and begin intensive peace talks
Tuesday, one day ahead of schedule, because the Iranian envoy
already had arrived.
   Velayati came to New York Monday and Aziz arrived Tuesday. Aziz
did not make an arrival statement.
   Before meeting with Perez de Cuellar, Velayati told reporters
Tuesday that Iraq was trying to sabotage the peace process by
invading Iran and using chemical wapons on a large scale.
   ``The war is still going on very seriously,'' he said, despite
Iraq's statements it was withdrawing from Iranian territory.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman urged
Iran and Iraq to exercise maximum restraint, saying, ``Continuation
of fighting does nothing to enhance the common goal of a negotiated
settlement.''
   Velayati and Perez de Cuellar discussed implementation of
Security Council Resolution 598, which was passed unanimously on
July 20, 1987, and which demands an immediate cease-fire in the
Persian Gulf conflict. It also calls for withdrawal to recognized
borders, prisoner exchange, peace negotiations and an investigation
to determine which side started the war.
   Iraq quickly accepted the resolution last year on condition Iran
do the same, but Iran waited until last week, July 18, before
announcing its acceptance.
   Although Iraq asked for direct talks with Iran in New York,
Perez de Cuellar said he would not try to compel the two sides to
meet face to face initially.
   While talks were under way in New York, two U.N. teams were at
work in Tehran, the Iranian capital. One was laboring over truce
details and the other was inquiring into the prisoners-of-war
situation.
   The cease-fire would be monitored and supervised by about 250
U.N. peacekeeping troops.
   Vernon A. Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said Tuesday on the CBS television program ``This Morning'' that it
would be possible to work out a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq in
the next two months.
   U.N. officials have said the U.N. budget crisis will make it
hard, perhaps impossible to finance the peacekeeping force, unless
the United States and other debtors pay their arrears.
   Such a force could cost $20 million to $30 million a year,
according to early estimates.
   Francoic Giuliani, spokesman for the secretary-general, told
reporters Tuesday the organization is expected to run out of
operating funds at the end of October.
   Washington has been withholding full dues payments to demand
U.N. spending reforms.
 
</TEXT>
