<DOCNO> AP880726-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Britain     07-26 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Britain,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gromyko Says Relations With Britain at a Postwar High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Andrei A. Gromyko said Tuesday that
Soviet relations with Britain have reached a postwar high but that
greater cooperation between the countries is ``absolutely
essential'' to bring about disarmament.
   Gromyko's remarks came during a meeting with Sir Bryan
Cartledge, the British ambassador, who is leaving Moscow after
three years. A report on the meeting was distributed by the
official Tass news agency.
   Tass said Cartledge noted that trade and economic ties between
London and Moscow had been broadening during his stay in the Soviet
Union and relations had improved.
   ``From the point of view of the Soviet side, too, our relations
have grown richer,'' Gromyko said. ``Never before in the postwar
period have they been at such a level as now. But even this level
can and should be raised further.''
   Gromyko, who served as foreign minister for 28 years, said
differences remained between the countries, in the first place over
nuclear weapons.
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has proposed a three-stage
plan to scrap all nuclear arms by the year 2000. But Britain's
prime minister, Margaret Thatcher, credits the weapons with helping
deter war between East and West since the end of World War II.
   Britain, a member of NATO, has its own nuclear arms.
   ``Being realists, we do not close our eyes to existing
disagreements, first of all those concerning nuclear weapons,''
Gromyko said. ``At the same time, and this is confirmed by the
experience of our relations, Soviet-British cooperation in arms
reduction is not only possible but absolutely essential.''
   He said British support played a ``positive role'' in bringing
about the superpower treaty signed in December that bans all
medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles.
   Cartledge arrived in Moscow as ambassador in July 1985, four
months after Gorbachev became Communist Party chief. Tass said
Cartledge said ``he was greatly impressed by the changes under way
in Soviet society, especially debureacratization'' as a part of
Gorbachev's reform drive.
   ``I like your word debureaucratization, although we don't use
it,'' the 79-year-old Gromyko answered.
</TEXT>
