<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Sarney     07-26 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Sarney,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sarney Warns New Constitution Could Make Brazil `Ungovernable'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney said late
Tuesday that approval of a proposed new constitution could make
Brazil ``ungovernable,'' spurring inflation and slashing economic
growth.
   ``There is no way to estimate the economic, social and political
impact of many of the articles,'' Sarney said in an address on
national television. ``If passed as it is, the charter will cause
economic and fiscal chaos and Brazilians will pay the costs.''
   The broadcast was Sarney's last-ditch attempt to remove several
proposals from the new document that will replace a 1969
constitution handed down by military generals.
   Legislators doubling as a consituent assembly have been working
on the document for 18 months and final voting on the draft began
Tuesday.
   The document includes proposal to limit annual interest rates to
12 percent, to give Brazilians control of all mining operations, to
cut the voting age from 18 to 16, and to grant the unrestricted
right to strike and a six-hour work day.
   All are clauses Sarney would like to defeat.
   He estimated the government's additional costs imposed by
clauses in the new document would be $9.5 billion. Inflation now is
23 percent monthly, the foreign debt $121 billion and unemployment
about 25 percent.
   ``I am worried the constitution could turn this country
ungovernable,'' Sarney said. ``We don't have the funds to implement
all the provisions people would be led to think were their due.''
   Sarney called a clause that would grant an amnesty to thousands
of debtors ``clearly unjust.''
   ``Many small businessmen sweated to pay their debts,'' he said.
   ``The constitution will signal the type of country we will
become,'' Sarney said. ``As the constitution stands, Brazil ...
will become a country that could have been but wasn't, a country
without a future.''
   The second round of voting is expected to last through September.
   Sarney, a 57-year-old provincial politician and poet from the
poor northeastern state of Maranhao, came to power in March 1985 as
the vice president for the popular statesman Tancredo Neves, who
died before taking office.
   They were elected in indirect electoral college voting called by
the military, which put Sarney on the Neves ticket. The vote was to
pave the way for civilian government after 21 years of military
rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
