<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IrelandPilgrimage     07-26 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland Pilgrimage,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal O'Connor Calls For New U.S. Immigration Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York ended
a pilgrimage across Ireland Tuesday, saying he will ask President
Reagan to grant amnesty for Irish and other illegal aliens in the
United States.
   O'Connor said he would ask Reagan next week, ``very formally and
with as much conviction as I can muster,'' for an executive order
granting amnesty.
   ``Our society and economy could absorb a lot more (immigrants)
from Ireland, from Latin American and many other countries,'' he
said.
   The New York archbishop's six-day pilgrimage was dedicated
mainly to praying for peace and reconciliation in Northern Ireland.
But in the Irish Republic a far more pressing concern is Irish
citizens living illegally in the United States.
   Social service agencies estimate the number of illegal Irish at
between 125,000 to 175,000, with more than two-thirds of them in
the New York area.
   Preaching at St. Mary's Cathedral in his last public Mass in
Ireland, O'Connor lamented ``the indignity of having sons and
daughters have to leave for another land because their land offers
them no opportunity.''
   Many Irish-Americans _ even those who, like O'Connor, were born
in the United States _ are familiar with the hardship of
immigration, and feel today that they are ``living almost as
exiles,'' he said.
   The Roman Catholic cardinal, a former naval chaplain who has had
close contact with the Reagan administration, told reporters after
the Mass that he hoped a presidential amnesty order would cover not
only undocumented immigrants from Ireland but ``a lot of others who
were not included in that window of opportunity.''
   He was referring to the Immigration and Naturalization Service's
amnesty program, under which those who had lived and worked
continuously in the United States since 1982 could apply for legal
residency. He said illegal Irish immigrants, in particular, need an
executive order because most arrived in the United States after
1982 as Ireland's economy faltered.
   The pilgrimage took the cardinal, New York Mayor Edward I. Koch
and about 500 other people from the Shrine of Our Lady of Knock in
the wild boglands of west Ireland to St. Peter's Cathedral in the
urban battlefields of west Belfast to St. Mary's, a 613-year-old
domed temple in the midst of busy Dublin. Koch flew back to New
York on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
