<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cuba 2ndLd-Writethru a0788 07-26 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0788,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castro Tells Cuba To Prepare for Return of Its Soldiers from
Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with Angola remarks, edits to trim and conform
throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL A. SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Fidel Castro told Cubans Tuesday
to prepare for the return of thousands of their soldiers from
Angola if a peace agreement can be reached for that southern
African country.
   In a three-hour speech marking the 35th anniversary of the
launching of his leftist revolution, Castro also defended his
``rectification'' campaign for economic reform and said
Soviet-style reforms are not needed in Cuba. He called capitalist
economic policies ``complete trash.''
   Castro confirmed reports that Cuba recently sent reinforcements
to Angola, where it is estimated that at least 50,000 Cuban
military personnel are helping the Marxist government battle rebels
backed by South Africa and the United States.
   He said the reinforcements were needed to create proper
conditions for a political solution in Angola.
   The governments of Angola, Cuba and South Africa reached an
agreement this month for the removal of foreign troops from Angola
and independence for South-West Africa, the territory administered
by South Africa.
   The United States was represented at the talks.
   South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, lies between South
Africa and Angola
   Castro said he did not want to prejudice the continuing
negotiations on Angola by going into detail on their status, but
declared: ``We really are on the threshholds of a political
solution.''
   Portugal granted independence to Angola in 1975, and Marxist
forces defeated pro-Western groups in the civil war that followed.
   U.S. State Department sources have said Cuba sent up to 15,000
more soldiers into Angola since last fall to augment its presence
of 40,000 military personnel.
   Castro did not say how many reinforcements were sent, but said
the deployment was needed and could not be done halfway.
   ``Our objective was not a military victory but a political, just
solution to the conflict,'' he said.
   Cuban forces will remain in Angola ``until the minute'' a peace
agreement is signed, Castro added.
   He said Cuban troops returning from Angola once a peace pact is
concluded would be welcomed back ``to the battle for the
development of our country.''
   He rejected suggestions from the West that socialist countries
must adopt capitalist policies to move their societies forward.
   Castro called capitalist methods ``complete trash'' and added:
``We will not weaken the role of plans or development programs.''
   He said the same was true for Cuba's one-party Communist system
and no room existed for opposition groups.
   ``The (Communist) party is the one responsible for our country.
Here there is only one party,'' he said.
   Referring to economic and political reforms being pursued by the
Soviet Union under Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other Soviet bloc
countries, Casto said those who urge adoption of those programs in
Cuba have ``an incorrect attitude, an ignorant attitude.''
   ``We will never forget where we are located, and it isn't in the
Black Sea, but in the Caribbean Sea,'' Castro he said. ``Not 90
miles from Odessa, but 90 miles from Miami.''
   In the past two years, Cuba has abandoned economic incentives
aimed at boosting production and implemented a campaign of ``moral
persuasion'' that emphasizes greater worker discipline.
   ``It would be totally incorrect for us to copy mechanically the
solutions of other countries,'' Castro said, and what may be best
for the Soviet bloc may not work for Cuba.
   Noting that Japan achieved its status as one of the world's most
powerful nations economically with an average of six vacation days
per worker each year, Castro called on Cubans to achieve more
during the working hours they have. He said he wasn't suggesting
taking away vacations or increasing work schedules in Cuba.
   Two years ago, Castro declared that worker absenteeism and
inefficient production threatened to make Cuba a nation of
freeloaders.
   The Cuban leader cited a lengthy list of recent industrial and
public works projects in Santiago, Cuba's second-largest city with
a population of 962,000.
   Earlier Tuesday, Cubans marked the revolution's 35th anniversary
by staging a symbolic attack on a military barracks that now is an
elementary school.
   Castro attended a ceremony in Santiago at 5 a.m., the exact time
his revolution began, and watched youth groups mount a mock assault
on the Moncada Garrison in this eastern Cuban city.
   Although the 1953 attack failed, the brutality with which it was
suppressed sparked popular support for Castro's fight to overthrow
rightist dictator Fulgencio Bastista.
   Castro was imprisoned and later released. He fled the island,
but returned with revolutionary forces aboard the yacht Granma in
1956 to start his guerrilla war in the mountains.
   The struggle ended in a triumphant march into Havana on Jan. 1,
1959, to begin Communist rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
