<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-26 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar, reflecting its recent strength
overseas, gained slightly in Tokyo today while stock prices
rebounded in slow trading.
   The dollar opened at 132.25 yen and rose to 132.60 before edging
down to close at 132.15, up 0.35 yen from Monday's close.
   ``Although there is no energy in the market that could keep
carrying the dollar higher, the dollar seems to be receiving enough
support to keep itself above the 132-yen level, at least for the
time being,'' a trader at the Bank of Tokyo said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which shed 117 points Monday, gained 120.23 points
or 0.44 percent to close at 27,303.76 in thin trading.
   ``It appears the market is going to hold back until the U.S. GNP
figures,'' said one dealer.
   Investors on the stock market were taking a wait-and-see
attitude ahead of Wednesday's scheduled announcement in Washington
of second-quarter figures for the gross national product, the total
retail value of goods and services produced by the country's
economy in a given period.
   ``If the U.S. GNP number is too strong, people are concerned
about inflation in the United States,'' said Hisamichi Sawa of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
</TEXT>
