<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PrimeComputer     07-26 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Computer,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Withdraws Mini-Supercomputer From Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. is withdrawing its
MXCL5 mini-supercomputer from the marketplace and taking a $5
million charge against its second-quarter earnings.
   The company also said Monday it is canceling a marketing
agreement with Cydrome Inc. of Milpitas, Calif., which manufactured
the computer.
   Prime attributed the withdrawal of the MXCL5 to slower growth in
the mini-supercomputer field and aggressive pricing by the
company's competitors.
   ``Because of the intensely competitive pricing environment, we
determined that sales of this product would not contribute
significantly to the overall profitability of Prime,'' Prime
President Joe M. Henson said in a prepared statement.
   Henson said Prime would continue to evaluate the special-purpose
processor market, which Prime entered in January in an attempt to
compete with field leaders Alliant Computer Systems Corp. of Acton
and Convex Computer Corp. of Richardson, Texas.
   Company officials said the second-quarter earnings reduction
would amount to about 10 cents a share. Analysts had forecast
earnings of about 23 cents to 27 cents a share. Prime is to
announce quarterly earnings Thursday.
   The base price for the standard MXCL5 system was $579,000, while
a more fully configured model was price at $774,000. The Unix-based
system was designed for sophisticated engineering and scientific
number-crunching.
   Prime announced in May it was laying off about 700 employees
because of job redundancies and attrition after a February merger
with Computervision Inc. The merger moved Prime to second in the
computer-aided design and computer-aided manufacturing market
behind International Business Machines Corp.
   The company reported first quarter net income of $14.5 million
of revenues of $363.7 million, including Computervision operations.
</TEXT>
