<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RobinsReorganization     07-26 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robins Reorganization,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalkon Shield Maker's Reorganization Confirmed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today confirmed A.H. Robins
Co.'s Chapter 11 reorganization plan, including $2.475 billion to
compensate women injured by the Dalkon Shield birth control device.
   The order entered by U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr.
will become final if no appeals are filed by Aug. 25. However,
Merhige and attorneys in the case have said previously such appeals
were likely.
   The reorganization of Robins, a Richmond-based pharmaceutical
manufacturer, includes the company's merger with New York-based
American Home Products Corp. in a $700 million exchange of stock.
   At a hearing last week, attorneys for Robins said more than 94
percent of Dalkon Shield claimants who cast ballots on the
reorganization plan voted for acceptance. Almost 72 percent of the
195,000 claimants returned ballots.
   Robins stockholders approved the reorganization plan by more
than a 99 percent vote.
   If any appeals are filed, payment of larger claims for Dalkon
Shield injuries would be delayed. However, the company will place
$100 million in the Dalkon Shield trust fund to pay smaller claims
pending resolution of appeals.
   Robins filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors in August
1985 as lawsuits mounted against the birth control device, which
the company marketed in the early 1970s.
</TEXT>
