<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-26 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0303</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices hovered in a narrow range today,
continuing Monday's mixed pattern.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.45 to 2,076.28 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 399 up, 430 down and 506
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 18.40 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said many investors were avoiding making big
commitments in advance of the Commerce Department's report due out
Wednesday on the gross national product for the second quarter of
the year.
   Private estimates generally call for inflation-adjusted GNP
growth to come in at about the same 3.6 percent annual rate
reported for the first quarter.
   Anything much higher than that might intensify worries about
inflation and higher interest rates, brokers said.
   Today the government said new factory orders for durable goods
jumped 8.8 percent in June. However, brokers said the figure wasn't
regarded as conclusive, because most of the increase came in
military goods, a category that is often subject to wide
month-by-month fluctuations.
   Microsoft fell 3 to 57{ in over-the-counter trading. The company
reported higher quarterly profits, but the results evidently fell
short of many investors' expectations.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.14 to 149.88. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .16 at 304.84.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average gained 10.84 to
2,071.83.
   But declining issues slightly outnumbered advances on the NYSE,
with 676 up, 752 down and 503 unchanged. Big Board volume came to
215.14 million shares, against 148.88 million in the previous
session.
</TEXT>
