<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-EuropeanCars Adv31   07-26 1079</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-European Cars, Adv 31,1112</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Western European Car Industry Is Booming, Alas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Western European car industry, the world's
largest, is enjoying record sales as consumers from Britain to
Italy flock to showrooms eager to buy ``new wheels.''
   While this is undoubtedly good news, some industry people,
believe it or not, find it distinctly worrying.
   The reason is that the boom has attracted more competitors in
what already is a fiercely competitive market. That has heightened
fears that the field will become overcrowded, leaving the car
makers vulnerable in a downturn, which could come as soon as next
year.
   ``The market is booming,'' said Sanjay Dabysing, head of the
automotive group at DRI Europe Ltd., a private economic forecasting
firm in London.
   Sales, which have been buoyant in Europe since the mid-1980s,
are expected to grow to a record 12.5 million cars this year from
12.4 million in 1987, DRI said.
   In comparison, 11.3 million cars were sold in North America and
3.3 million in Japan in the most recent year.
   ``It's a representation of the reasonably good economic growth
in Europe in recent years,'' said Garel Rhys, an automotive
economist at the University of Cardiff.
   The sales growth stems from strong consumer spending created by
income growth, tax cuts and an increasing willingness among
Europeans to take on debt, the experts said. In addition, more
businesses are using company cars, they said.
   Britain, Spain and Italy have been experiencing particularly
strong demand, while sales have been slowed somewhat in West
Germany by a sluggish economy.
   Import restraints and the overall buoyancy of the market have
encouraged Japanese manufacturers to build more plants in Europe.
The market also has attracted other Asian and Eastern European
competitors, like the makers of South Korea's Hyundai and
Yugoslavia's inexpensive Yugo.
   U.S. automakers have stepped up their activity by buying up
European luxury car makers. General Motors Corp. has bought Lotus
Group of Cos.; Chrysler Corp. has bought Automobili Lamborghini SpA
and Ford Motor Co., which already owns Aston Martin Lagonda Ltd.,
is rumored to be interested in Jaguar PLC.
   ``The market has become more competitive,'' Dabysing said.
   Most of the competition still comes from other Europeans. Unlike
the United States, where the Big Three automakers control the
market, Europe has a large number of domestically based
manufacturers.
   The top six auto makers and their market shares in 1987,
according to DRI, were: Volkswagen AG, 14.9 percent; Fiat Auto SpA,
14.2 percent; the combination of Peugeot S.A. and Automobiles
Citroen S.A., 12.2 percent; Ford, 12 percent; Renault S.A., 10.6
percent, and General Motors, 10.6 percent.
   The biggest rivalry among the Europeans is between Volkswagen
and Fiat, both of which are trying to expand their markets across
the continent in anticipation of the Common Market's elimination of
most trade barriers in 1992.
   Fiat, for instance, makes 60 percent of its sales in Italy, but
expects to face new threats at home once trade restrictions on
imports are lifted across the European Economic Community.
   The Japanese, meanwhile, have already captured 11.4 percent of
the European market, mostly through imports, DRI said.
   ``The Japanese are now moving on to the next stage as they have
in America, trying to diffuse the controversy that their sales have
created in Europe,'' Rhys said.
   The pioneer, Nissan Motor Co., operates a plant in Sunderland,
England, and has already doubled its planned 1992 capacity to
200,000 cars.
   ``There is no doubt that manufacturers like Toyota (Motor Corp.)
and Mazda (Motor Corp.) and Mitsubishi (Motors Corp.) will follow
this route. Where and when is difficult to answer, but they will be
coming,'' Dabysing said, adding that the Japanese might also bring
over cars it makes in North America.
   Indeed, John Grant, vice president for business strategy for
Ford of Europe Inc. in Brentwood, England, said that's ``the
biggest worry we have.''
   The Japanese companies, already the most productive car makers,
will be able to cut costs further when they set up more operations
in Europe, which will save them considerable transportation costs.
   ``We will get an excess capacity situation again, which will
increase the cost pressures on everybody and will increase the
competitive pressures,'' Grant said.
   The market could develop an excess capacity of 1 million cars,
he estimated.
   The 12-nation EEC has yet to decide whether it will restrict
Japanese imports after 1992, when it becomes a barrier-free
marketplace. The experts are expecting the EEC to choose a
voluntary quota on Japanese car sales, perhaps limiting them to 10
percent of the market.
   ``Some people argue that there are too many independent
manufacturers in Europe,'' Rhys said.``If the market turned off
considerably in the future, the firms would find it difficult to
make profits and the question would be, how do the firms survive?''
   The companies have toughened up by striving to become more
productive and to produce higher quality cars, in an effort to
close those gaps with the Japanese leaders.
   Western European makers have also joined forces, either through
mergers or through joint ventures to produce various components,
and in one case, an entire car. Renault and Volksagen are working
together on an automatic gear box; Peugeot, Volvo A.B. and Renault
are working on an engine; Rover Group PLC and Honda Motor Co.
developed a car together, the Rover 800 also called the Honda
Legend.
   This has helped the Western European makers _ which do not enjoy
the economies of scale the Americans have _ to become more
profitable.
   Although the drop in the dollar has hurt luxury car makers who
export to the United States, Dabysing said that in 1987, ``they
(the major European car makers) made money on the operations level
for the first time in a long, long time and 1988 is proving to be a
good year, too.''
   The cloud on the horizon is the setback the industry is
expecting in 1989. The experts are forcasting sales of 11.5 million
cars to 11.75 million cars, a decline of as much as 8 percent.
   But the competitors won't be put off, the experts said.
   ``It's entrepreneurship. Hope springs eternal in the human
breast,'' Rhys said. ``Everybody feels they can make a lot of
money. It's a very big market and they want to be in it and they
want to be in it in a bigger way in the future.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
