<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-26 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures prices opened sharply lower again
today on the Chicago Board of Trade but analysts said the markets
may be nearing the bottom of a week-long slide prompted by recent
rains in the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   ``I think the market's gone too far down,'' said Cathy Leow,
assistant vice president in charge of grain futures trading for
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``I think the market's overdone the rains we've gotten and it's
still ignoring the fact that we have a phenomenal amount of (crop)
damage,'' she said.
   Scattered showers in the Midwest during the past week improved
the condition of corn and soybean crops in most major growing
states, according to agricultural experts. And the National Weather
Service's latest 6-to-10-day outlook predicts normal precipitation
in the region early next week.
   But Ms. Leow said losses totaling more than $2 a bushel in the
soybean pit in the past seven sessions do not reflect the
irreparable damage already done to the crop.
   In early trading, wheat was 4 cents to 6{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.65 a bushel; corn was 11{
cents to 13{ cents lower with September at $2.91 a bushel; oats
were 4{ cents to 6{ cents lower with September at $2.47{ a bushel;
soybeans were 24 cents to 30 cents lower with August at $7.74 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed to lower in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .37 cent lower with August at 66.27
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .20 cent higher
with August at 77.50 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent lower to .38
cent higher with August at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .42 cent to 1.35 cents lower with August at 35.45 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher while pork futures were sharply
lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
