<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Beef     07-26 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Beef,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lifts Import Ban On Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea announced Tuesday it was
lifting a three-year-old ban on imports of foreign beef, but said
it would maintain an import quota system that has been opposed by
the United States.
   Agriculture Minister Yun Kun-hwan said imports for 1988 would be
limited to 14,500 tons. Yun did not say how much beef would be
imported after this year, but indicated imports would be limited in
order to protect the local beef industry.
   The end to the import ban was designed to avoid trade friction
with foreign countries while at the same time alleviating domestic
beef shortages, Yun said.
   The United States has been pressing South Korea to drop the ban
on beef imports to help correct Seoul's $10 billion trade imbalance
with Washington. The United States is also pressing South Korea to
drop restrictions or bans on many other imports and opposes the
beef quota system.
   There was no immediate reaction from local farmers who have
strongly opposed imports of beef unless the government guaranteed a
definite price support system before lifting the import ban.
   Many Korean farmers went bankrupt due to an excessive import of
foreign beef cattle before the last ban was imposed in 1985.
Farmers have staged demonstrations to demand retention of the
import ban.
   As reported previously, Yun said the proposed tonnage would
include 3,000 tons of high quality beef for use at tourist hotels
to be imported from the United States. Officials said high quality
beef could start arriving next month.
   The remaining 11,500 tons of both high quality and ordinary
quality beef would be for general public consumption with sales
open to the United States, Australia and other bidders.
   Yun said imported beef will be stockpiled for sales in case
domestic sales prices exceed designated levels to seek price
stabilization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
