<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Reagan-PlantClosing 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Plant Closing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Hear GOP Views On Plant Closing Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout. Moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican congressional leaders told
President Reagan today to use his ``best instincts'' in considering
whether to veto the plant- closing bill. One key GOP senator
predicted the legislation will become law no matter what the
president does.
   House Republican leader Robert Michel of Illinois told reporters
that ``arguments were made on both sides of the issue'' in a
meeting of GOP leaders with the president at the White House.
   ``Some of us in the House of Representatives made the point that
we were within the range of being able to sustain the president's
veto if there were some work done and there wasn't a diminution of
votes on the Democratic side,'' Michel said.
   ``There were arguments made on the other side too that frankly
it was probably impossible to sustain in the Senate and that maybe
the president would want to give consideration to simply letting it
become law,'' he said.
   Michel said the president ``did not give an expression one way
or another at all'' as to his intentions. The president told
reporters at the opening of the meeting that he never decides about
a bill until it reaches his desk.
   When asked what he believed the president would do, Michel said,
``He's a very pragmatic individual and has been over eight years of
time. I think the last word that was said was,`Mr. President, just
use your best instincts.''
   Michel said that ``arguments were made with respect to how it
may or may not affect the campaign,'' but Sen. Richard Lugar,
R-Ind., said, ``I don't think it will make much difference.''
   ``My guess is plant closing will become law but the parts about
layoffs will be very controversial and will lead to some litigation
later on,'' he said.``I think probably the vote is there in both
houses to override.''
   Lugar said the Republicans in the meeting ``were expressing
pretty good vote counts but saying the president ought to do his
thing.''
   The bill requires companies to give workers 60 days' notice of
plant closings and layoffs.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that Reagan
is likely to go ahead and veto the bill.
   But the spokesman also said no final decision had been made.
   ``It's always open until it's done,'' Fitzwater told reporters
after the arrived at the White House for Reagan's signature.
   The legislation passed both the House and Senate by veto-proof
margins, and some Republicans have said they're reluctant to vote
against it because of polls showing broad public support for the
proposal.
   Fitzwater disputed assertions that Republicans may be preparing
to deliver that sort of message to Reagan, saying, ``I would say
there are number of them who will recommend a veto.''
   Reagan has until Aug. 3 to make a decision. He could veto the
bill, sign it, or let it pass automatically into law without his
signature.
   The administration's stand on the issue has been repeatedly
assailed by Democrats, who say common decency requires that workers
be told when they are about to lose their jobs. Reagan says
business should have the ``flexibility'' to close plants and lay
off workers without the 60 days' notice.
   Vice President George Bush, certain to get the Republican
nomination for president in New Orleans next month, has stated
sentiments similar to Reagan's on the issue, although there have
been reports the Bush campaign would prefer to see the president
let the bill become law to ease the political heat on Bush.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
