<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     07-26 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0315</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined slightly in quiet trading
today, continuing Monday's mixed pattern.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.42 to 2,070.41
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 6 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 543 up, 657 down and
543 unchanged.
   Analysts said many investors were avoiding making big
commitments in advance of the Commerce Department's report due out
Wednesday on the gross national product for the second quarter of
the year.
   Private estimates generally call for inflation-adjusted GNP
growth to come in at about the same 3.6 percent annual rate
reported for the first quarter.
   Anything much higher than that might intensify worries about
inflation and higher interest rates, brokers said.
   Today the government said new factory orders for durable goods
jumped 8.8 percent in June. However, brokers said the figure wasn't
regarded as conclusive, because most of the increase came in
military goods, a category that is often subject to wide
month-by-month fluctuations.
   Phillips Petroleum rose { to 17 in active trading. The company
reported sharply higher earnings for the second quarter.
   Sears Roebuck, on the other hand, dropped \ to 35| as the
company posted slightly lower quarterly profits.
   Microsoft fell 3 to 57{ in over-the-counter trading. The company
reported higher quarterly profits, but the results evidently fell
short of many investors' expectations.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .05 to 149.69. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .25 at 304.43.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 56.72 million shares at
noontime, against 140.57 million at the same point Monday, when the
total was inflated by dividend-related trading in a few
high-yielding issues.
</TEXT>
