<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Computers     07-26 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Computers,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Control Data, Microsoft Report Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. and Microsoft Corp., two major computer
products companies, on Tuesday reported gains in quarterly net
income.
   Control Data, based in Bloomington, Minn., said its net income
for the second quarter totaled $9.2 million, or 22 cents a share,
compared with a loss of $5.5 million in the year-ago period.
   Revenue for the quarter ended June 30 totaled $951.7 million, up
21 percent from $785.9 million in 1987.
   Robert M. Price, chairman and chief executive officer, said
attributed the growth to revenue increases in the company's
business services and data storage products businesses.
   Revenue growth in the business services unit reflects the
acquisition of the SAMI-Burke marketing information business in
late 1987.
   Control Data provides computer products and services for
scientific, engineering and business applications worldwide.
   For the first six months of 1988, Control Data reported net
income of $16.9 million, or 40 cents a share, on revenues of $1.85
billion, compared with net earnings of $1.7 million, or 3 cents a
share, on revenues of $1.61 billion in 1987.
   In Redmond, Wash., Microsoft reported a 74 percent jump in
fourth quarter net income. Profits for the quarter ended June 30
totaled $30.01 million, or 54 cents a share, up from $17.26
million, or 31 cents a share for the same period in 1987.
   The personal computer software manufacturer said its
fourth-quarter revenue totaled $170.47 million, up 71 percent from
$99.76 million a year ago.
   ``These results represent strength across all channels of
distribution and in all product groups,'' said Jon Shirley,
Microsoft president and chief operating officer. ``Our
international operations were particularly strong, generating 47.8
percent of revenues for the year.''
   For the fiscal year, net income totaled $123.91 million, or
$2.22 a share, on revenues of $590.83 million, up from profits of
$71.88 million, or $1.30 a share, on revenues of $345.89 million
for fiscal 1987.
</TEXT>
