<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Transamerica     07-26 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Transamerica,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transamerica Reports Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transamerica Corp. on Tuesday reported
earnings from continuing operations rose 7 percent in the second
quarter, partly boosted by the acquisition of a commercial lending
operation.
   Profits from continuing operations totaled $87.6 million, or
$1.12 per share, up from $82.1 million, or $1.05 per share, in the
second quarter of 1987.
   Consolidated net income, however, fell to $89.45 million from
$105.96 million in the year-ago quarter. The financial services
concern posted a $1.87 million after-tax gain from investment
transactions in the second quarter. That's down from a similar gain
of $8.26 million and $15.6 million in gains from discontinued
operations posted in 1987.
   Revenue for the quarter totaled $1.996 billion, up from $1.977
billion for the same period in 1987.
   The insurance and financial services giant said expansion of its
commercial lending and leasing operations contributed to the
quarter and six-month earnings gains.
   ``Our insurance and finance operations both achieved outstanding
results, reflecting the fundamental strength and earning power of
our businesses,'' said James R. Harvey, chairman and chief
executive officer.
   Profits from continuing operations during the first half of 1988
were $163.1 million, or $2.08 per share, up 9 percent from 1987's
$149.9 million, or $1.91 per share.
   First half consolidated net income for 1988 totaled $166
million, including $3 million in other gains, while first-half 1987
consolidated net income of $217 million included $33 million of
other gains and $34 million in income from discontinued oprations,
said Richard J. Olsen, vice president of corporate relations.
   Total revenues for the first six months of 1988 were $3.975
billion, up from $3.810 billion for the same period last year, the
company said.
   The company expanded its commercial lending operation with the
acquisition in October 1987 of the Borg-Warner Acceptance Corp.,
now called Transamerica Commercial Finance Corp.
   In its life insurance operation, profits were increased by
reducing expenses and higher yields on invested assets, the company
said. Property and casualty insurance increases were attributed to
expansions in workers' compensation and re-insurance production.
</TEXT>
