<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-USX     07-26 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-USX,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Outperforming Oil At USX</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. said Tuesday its second-quarter
profits rose 29 percent as its steel division outperformed the
energy operations that had carried the company for most of the
decade.
   ``It's back to being a steel company again'' in terms of
generating profits, said steel industry analyst Charles Bradford of
Merrill Lynch & Co. USX reported it earned $213 million, or 74
cents per share, up from $165 million, or 56 cents per share, in
the second quarter of 1987.
   Sales for the quarter rose 7.5 percent to $4.3 billion from $4
billion.
   The company's USS division, the nation's largest steelmaker,
turned in operating profits of $223 million on sales of $1.6
billion, or nearly $70 per ton of steel shipped.
   The USX energy segment, comprising Marathon Oil Co. and Texas
Oil & Gas Corp., operated at a profit of $104 million on sales of
$2.4 billion.
   Marathon's operating profit was $120 million on sales of $2.2
billion, while Texas Oil & Gas lost $16 million on sales of $201
million.
   USX Chairman David Roderick said lower crude oil prices and
higher exploration costs dampened Marathon's performance.
   But, said analyst Bruce Lazier of Prescott Ball & Turben, ``The
energy division is still profitable despite $15 (a barrel) oil.''
   ``It's not a drag'' on earnings, he said.
   USX's diversified businesses showed profits of $69 million on
sales of $389 million, up from $5 million on sales of $235 million
in the year-ago period.
   USX acquired Marathon in 1982 and Texas Oil & Gas four years
later. ``During the period when steel was still down, the cash flow
from these operations helped support the whole debt structure,''
Lazier said.
   Now steel is coming on strong and energy is languishing.
``Roderick's strategy looks increasingly good,'' Lazier said.
   First half profits totaled $370 million, or $1.26 per share,
compared to $93 million, or 20 cents per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first six months of the year totaled $8.3
billion, up from $6.7 billion.
</TEXT>
