<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelPrices     07-26 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Prices,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Joins Bethlehem In Jan. Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Corp., the nation's second-largest
steelmaker, said Tuesday it is joining No. 3 Bethlehem in boosting
prices on flat-rolled products by $15 to $30 per ton effective Jan.
1.
   The moves appear to undercut USX Corp.'s efforts to raise its
prices on Oct. 1.
   Inland and Armco, the fourth- and fifth-largest steelmakers
respectively, said Tuesday they had not decided whether to follow
suit. Officials of No. 6 National Steel could not be reached
Tuesday for comment.
   USX announced its plans early this month. Bethlehem followed
last week with an announcement that it was delaying a price hike
until after the fourth quarter.
   ``Japan did not raise export prices to the U.S. for the fourth
quarter, and that might be what Bethlehem is worrying about,'' said
steel industry analyst Charles Bradford of Merrill Lynch & Co.
   ``Most of them would prefer to go along with USX,'' he said.
``Business is pretty good.''
   Bradford said he expected USX to back down on its Oct. 1 date.
   A USX spokesman declined comment Tuesday.
   The affected products include sheet steel used in automobiles,
appliances, office furniture and a variety of other consumer goods.
</TEXT>
