<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Oil     07-26 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Oil,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco, Chevron, Phillips Report Higher Profit; Amerada Hess Posts
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of the nation's major oil companies, Texaco Inc., Chevron
Corp. and Phillips Petroleum Co., on Tuesday said their profit for
the second quarter was boosted by strength in refining, marketing
and chemicals operations.
   Amerada Hess Corp., the 15th largest U.S. oil company, reported
a net loss of $23.5 million, compared with a year-earlier profit of
$89.4 million, or $1.06 a share.
   Texaco, the nation's third biggest oil company, said its
second-quarter net income quadrupled, lifted by refining, marketing
and chemicals as well as the sale of its West German subsidiary.
   The oil giant earned $527 million, or $2.17 a share, up from
$129 million, or 53 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 10.6 percent, to $9.4 billion from
$8.5 billion a year earlier.
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., emerged on April 7 from
bankruptcy protection under Chapter 11 of the federal code. The
company paid $3 billion to settle litigation with Pennzoil Co. and
initiated another $2.6 billion in payments to its other creditors.
   Texaco's earnings for the latest quarter include an after-tax
gain of $301 million, or $1.24 a share, from the sale of its West
German subsidiary, Deutsche Texaco A.G.
   The sale was part of the company's restructuring program under
the Chapter 11 proceedings. Texaco also signed a letter of intent
in June to form a joint venture with Saudi investors to refine and
market oil products in parts of the United States.
   In the first half of the year, net income tripled to $769
million, or $3.17 a share, from $247 million, or $1.02 a share, in
the same period in 1987. First-half revenue was up 6.5 percent, to
$18.1 billion from $17.0 billion.
   Fourth-ranked Chevron, based in San Francisco, said its
second-quarter profit jumped 45 percent _ to $520 million, or $1.52
a share, from $358 million, or $1.04 a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue was unchanged from a year earlier, at
$7.3 billion.
   Chevron Chairman George Keller said the company's profit margins
from sales of oil products were the highest in two years, while
chemical operations continued to benefit from strong demand in the
industrial market.
   Earnings in the first six months increased 63 percent _ to $1.2
billion, or $3.43 a share, from $719 million, or $2.10 a share.
Revenue for the period edged up 5 percent, to $14.8 billion from
$14.1 billion.
   Phillips, the nation's eighth biggest oil company, saw its
earnings in the quarter soar to $170 million, or 72 cents a share,
from $3 million a year earlier.
   The Bartlesville, Okla.-based company said that although its
gains were broad-based, refining and marketing were especially
strong.
   First-half profit was $300 million, or $1.27 a share, compared
with a loss of $29 million in January-June 1987. Revenue for the
six months rose to $5.78 billion from $5.18 billion.
   New York-based Amerada Hess said its second-quarter net loss of
$23.5 million included a loss from refining and marketing
operations of $6.5 million, compared with profit of $55.7 million a
year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue fell to $882.8 million from $1.1 billion
a year earlier.
   In the first half, Amerada Hess earned $42.2 million, or 51
cents a share, down from $270.8 million, or $3.21 a share. Revenue
for the period declined to $2.1 billion from $2.4 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
