<1ST_LINE>r f AM-C&NWTalks 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-C&NW Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bargaining Resumes in Rail Dispute; Bill Introduced To Block
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with talks adjourning for the
day and to include background on commuter service. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, bgng: `Although I ... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the United Transportation
Union and Chicago & North Western Railway on Tuesday failed to
resolve a labor dispute that could halt rail service for 40,000
Chicago-area commuters.
   Negotiations in the presence of federal mediators adjourned for
the day without an accord, but a government official said he would
not characterize the talks as unproductive.
   ``They're still talking,'' said Charles R. Barnes, executive
director of the National Mediation Board. ``All I can really say is
that mediation is in progress and, as far as we're concerned, it's
going to go right down to the deadline. ... We'll be available as
long as we can help.''
   While the two sides met behind closed doors at the board's
Washington offices, an Illinois congressman introduced legislation
to push them closer to an agreement and block a threatened Aug. 4
strike. C&NW provides the principal daily rail service for about
40,000 commuters in the Chicago area.
   ``Although I dislike intervention by the federal government, we
cannot stand idly by,'' said Rep. John Porter, R-Ill. ``Congress
may act if they fail to do so.''
   Porter's bill would require the company and union to accept as
binding the recommendations of a presidential emergency board
appointed to examine the dispute if the two sides fail to reach
agreement on their own by the strike deadline.
   At issue is a plan by Chicago & North Western, a subsidiary of
CNW Corp., to cut costs by eliminating the jobs of 1,156 of its
2,600 union brakemen.
   Company spokeswoman Leslie Cleveland said the nation's
eighth-largest rail carrier could save $51 million a year and
become more competitive if it reduced the size of its train crews
from an engineer, conductor and two brakemen to only an engineer
and conductor in most cases.
   The company contends that improved technology has made the jobs
obsolete. The union insists safety would be compromised without the
brakemen and said the cuts would violate its contract.
   The outcome of the dispute could set a precedent for crew sizes
throughout the rail industry, which is entering national bargaining
with its unions this year.
   A threatened UTU strike was averted in April when President
Reagan, acting under provisions of the Railway Labor Act, appointed
an emergency board to investigate the dispute. As part of his
order, the union was prohibited from striking before 12:01 a.m. on
Aug. 4.
   In a 29-page report to the president on July 1, the emergency
board proposed doing away with 689 brakemen's jobs, cutting one
brakeman per train in most cases and both brakemen when approved by
an arbitrator on a train-by-train basis.
   ``Without such relief, (C&NW) will be forced to take more
drastic economic action which could jeopardize the livelihood of
all its employees,'' the board said.
   United Transportation Union Chairman Fred Hardin said the report
was not acceptable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
