<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-TexasAmerican     07-26 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Texas American,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merger-Bound Company Reports Disastrous Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled Texas American Bancshares said Tuesday it
lost $135.3 million in its second quarter, due mainly to reserves
set aside to cover potentially bad loans.
   The loss, which the company said might substantially diminish or
possibly eliminate stockholders' equity, compared with a loss of
$6.5 million for the second quarter in 1987 and a loss of $17.8
million for the first quarter of 1988.
   ``The decline in second-quarter earnings is attributed to a high
provision for loan losses, as the reserve for loan losses was
substantially enhanced during the quarter, and to an increased
negative impact form a higher level of non-performing assets,''
said Joseph M. Grant, chairman of Texas American.
   Officials said the company had $598 million in non-performing
assets after the second quarter, an increase of $62 million from
the first quarter.
   The banking company, which has $5 billion in assets, said
stockholders' equity, which had stood at $163.5 million following
the first quarter, has been reduced to $28.2 million.
   Texas American also said it lost $153 million during the first
six months of 1988, compared with a loss of $6.1 million in
first-half 1987.
   On July 20, Texas American announced a plan to merge with
National Bancshares Corporation of Texas. Under the proposal,
Minnesota investor and businessman Carl R. Pohlad and his companies
would provide up to $200 million of capital in exchange for up to
85 percent of the new company.
   The plan also would call for the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corporation to provide $475 million in exchange for a subordinated
non-interest bearing note and 10 percent of the new company's
equity.
   Under the merger, existing shareholders of Texas American and
National Bancshares initially would receive 5 percent equity
interest in the new company. The merger is subject to approval by
shareholders of both companies and by various regulatory agencies.
   Deposits at Texas American averaged $4.5 billion for the second
quarter, a four percent decline from the first quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
