<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Johnson&Johnson     07-26 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Johnson&Johnson,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Qtr. Profit Up 20.4 Percent At Health Care Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnson and Johnson said Tuesday its
second-quarter earnings increased 20.4 percent from a year earlier,
paced by higher sales in its commercial, pharmaceutical and
professional businesses.
   The health care products manufacturer reported second-quarter
profit of $271 million, or $1.57 per share, compared with earnings
of $225 million, or $1.30 per share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Sales for the quarter rose 13.9 percent, to $2.29 billion from
$2.01 billion a year earlier.
   The higher earnings were led by sales gains in the New Brunswick
company's pharmaceutical division. The division reported
second-quarter sales of $611 million, a 20.8 increase compared with
1987 sales of $506 million.
   For the first six months of the year, Johnson & Johnson earned
$550 million, or $3.19 per share, up from $460 million, or $2.66
per share, during the same period in 1987.
   Six-month sales rose 15.3 percent, to $4.6 billion from $3.99
billion.
   The lower value of the dollar against major foreign currencies,
compared with the same period last year, added $140 million to the
company's six-month sales, the company stated.
</TEXT>
