<DOCNO> AP880726-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 2320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Edison-SDG&E     07-26 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Edison-SDG&E,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SoCal Edison Proposes $2 Billion Merger With San Diego Gas &
Electric</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMEAD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Diego Gas & Electric Co., which last
month said it intends to merge with an Arizona utility, has
received a rival $2 billion merger offer from the parent of giant
Southern California Edison Co., officials said Tuesday.
   The friendly stock-swap offer from SCEcorp values SDG&E at about
$2 billion based on Tuesday's closing stock price.
   SDG&E said in a news release it was studying the offer but
refused further comment. SCEcorp, recently formed as a holding
company for Edison, said it would pursue the merger _ which it
conditioned on SDG&E dropping its proposed merger with Tucson
(Ariz.) Electric Power Co. _ only if it were accepted by SDG&E
management.
   Analysts and SCEcorp termed the potential deal a boon to both
consumers and SDG&E stockholders.
   They predicted San Diego County consumers, whose electricity
bills are among the nation's highest, would get a piece of Edison's
large generating capacity. The 4.8 million customers of a combined
company, they said, would benefit because the enhanced purchasing
power of a huge, merged utility would win better prices for power
bought from utility companies elsewhere in the West.
   ``It makes total sense,'' said Edward Tirello, a securities
analyst who follows both companies for Shearson Lehman Bros. Inc.
in New York.
   He said SCEcorp's announcement said a goal of the merged
companies would be to reduce SDG&E's rates, which presently are 25
percent higher than Edison's.
   The proposal, made privately on Monday and announced by both
companies Tuesday, calls for SCEcorp to exchange 1.15 shares of its
common stock for each of the approximately 55.8 million SDG&E
shares outstanding. Preferred and other classes of stock would be
swapped at comparable rates.
   Management ranks would be thinned through attrition and
voluntary retirement, SCEcorp said.
   Any merger would require the approval of the state Public
Utilities Commission, federal regulators and the stockholders of
both companies. PUC deliberations would likely take a year.
   SDG&E's stock price rose $1.25 a share Tuesday to close at
$34.12{ in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. SCEcorp's
stock price was unchanged at $31.37{.
   On June 13, SDG&E announced a proposed merger with the Tucson
Electric Power Co. in Arizona that the companies valued at $5.7
billion.
   That merger would allow SDG&E, primarily a buyer of power rather
than a producer, to take advantage of Tucson Electric's excess
generating capacity and give Tucson a ready market for its power.
   SCEcorp said a merger with Edison would be more logical than
SDG&E's prposed merger with Tucson Electric because the companies'
coverage areas border on each other and their lines are
interconnected.
   Edison has ample power, both self-generated and purchased from
other utilities in the West, to provide for SDG&E, said spokesman
Robert Hull. The San Diego company's rates have been pushed up by
rising power prices and by the need to build high-cost transmission
systems to serve booming developments in the county.
   Edison serves 3.8 million customers across most of Southern
California. SDG&E, with 1 million customers, provides electricity
and natural gas in San Diego County and electricity in a slice of
Orange County.
   Howard Allen, SCEcorp chairman and chief executive officer,
stressed in a letter proposing the merger that it was a friendly
proposal.
   ``We have no intention of attempting to acquire your company
other than in a transaction approved by your board of directors,''
Allen said in a letter to SDG&E released by SCEcorp.
   Shearson Lehman's Tirello, author of a book predicting that such
mergers will form huge regional power companies, said a combination
would save the companies more than $200 million a year.
   ``The ratepayer does real well in San Diego simply because
Southern Cal Edison has said, `We want to bring you down to our
level as quick as we can,''' Tirello said. ``The Southern Cal
Edison ratepayer gets the advantage of increased buying power.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
