<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-state survey released by state securities
regulators indicates that fraud and abuse in the fast-growing
financial planning industry is on the rise, particularly in
multimillion-dollar investments.
   The North American Securities Administrators Association said
Monday that 22,100 investors lost $397 million in 79 cases pursued
by state securities officials between mid-1986 and mid-1988.
   That compares with $91 million lost in 31 cases between mid-1983
and mid-1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has
outlined modest changes in Pentagon contracting procedures designed
to curb the types of abuses uncovered in the ongoing defense
procurement investigation.
   The new practices place strict limits on what the Pentagon calls
``Best and Final Offers'' that each company can make on specifc
contracts, Carlucci said Monday.
   Contractors previously were able to amend their final offers in
consultation with the Pentagon to change prices or technical
specifications to meet Defense Department needs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fleet-Norstar Financial Group has agreed to
acquire Indian Head Banks Inc., a leading bank holding company in
New Hampshire, in an exchange of stock valued at $240 million.
   Indian Head Banks, with assets of about $1.8 billion, has 46
branches throughout New Hampshire and earned $16.6 million in 1987,
the company said Monday.
   Peter D. Kiernan, chairman and chief executive of Fleet-Norstar,
said the proposed acquisition would be a major step in expanding
Fleet-Norstar's New England banking operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have expanded their probe
of unintended acceleration in Mercedes-Benz automobiles to include
309,000 vehicles made from 1984 through 1988, the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration says.
   The agency said Monday it had received allegations of 301
instances of sudden acceleration in the cars, all of which are
equipped with gasoline engines and automatic transmissions.
   NHTSA said 217 of the reported sudden-accleration cases resulted
in accidents, in which 92 people were injured and one person killed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of fast-food giant McDonald's
Corp. have testified that Quality Inns International Inc. was
infringing upon its trademarks by using the name McSleep Inn for a
new chain of economy hotels.
   McDonald's began presenting its case Monday in the trial which
began July 18 before U.S. District Judge Paul Niemeyer.
   McDonald's took exception last September to the use of the
``Mc'' prefix after Quality Inns announced the new chain of hotels,
which will offer a night's lodging for $20 to $29.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue chip issues staged a mild rally Monday, but the rest of the
stock market continued struggling following last week's sharp drop.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.84 points to
2,071.83.
   The dollar rose sharply and gold prices skidded to five-month
lows as the markets picked up signals that inflation was easing.
   Bond prices finished mostly higher.
   Soybean futures prices settled at a two-month low while grain
futures also finished sharply lower. Oil prices slipped.
