<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-26 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip As Doubts Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed pessimism about OPEC's ability to
control its oil production has stalled the recent advance of oil
futures prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude, the nation's benchmark
grade, settled Monday at $16.05 per barrel, off 33 cents from
Friday's close. The near-term crude contract gained $1.41 per
barrel last week.
   Refined products also lost ground. The near-term contract for
wholesale gasoline fell .85 cent per gallon to settle at 51.22
cents, and heating oil dropped .78 cent per gallon to finish at
44.17 cents.
   Traders said activity was light as market attitudes turned
bearish about the cartel's chances for limiting overproduction and
firming prices.
   The market's strong move last week stemmed from bullish
interpretations of a proposed cease-fire between Persian Gulf
combatants Iran and Iraq and reports that members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would meet soon to
discuss prices.
   Both were interpreted as signs that fractious elements in the
gulf would be able to overcome their differences and prop up the
sagging oil market.
   The respected Middle East Economic Survey reported Monday that
OPEC's pricing committee would meet Aug. 3 in Switzerland, but the
news failed to inspire traders to follow through on the market's
previous gains. Instead, traders said, the market appeared to
recoil with its characteristic doubts about whether OPEC ever could
get together on the price issue.
   ``After a runup based on speculation, there's a natural amount
of profit taking,'' said Richard Redoglio of Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
