<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PillsburyCEO Bjt   07-26 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury CEO, Bjt,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Can Smith Turn Pillsbury Around?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s new top executive has been
criticized as lacking vital restaurant experience to turn around
the company's flagging Burger King chain, but Philip L. Smith says
he's just waiting to test his management ability.
   The troubled food giant on Monday plucked Smith from rival
General Foods Corp., where he served as chairman. The 54-year-old
Smith also served as vice chairman of Philip Morris Cos. Inc.,
which acquired General Foods in 1985. He begins his new job Aug. 1.
   Unlike General Foods, which has rested on the success of its
Oscar Mayer meats and Jell-O gelatin, Pillsbury has few high-growth
products, analysts said.
   ``Smith has been a big cheese in a company with a lot of easy
brands,'' said Stephen Carnes, a managing director at Piper Jaffray
& Hopwood in Minneapolis.
   But at Pillsbury, Smith ``will have to get down to trench
warfare, and he was never in that mode before,'' Carnes said.
Minneapolis-based Pillsbury, the nation's fourth-largest food
conglomerate, produces Green Giant vegetables, Haagen-Dazs premium
ice creams and Van de Kamp's frozen fish.
   Of greater concern to some is Smith's lack of experience in the
restaurant business. Pillsbury's restaurant unit, which also
includes Steak & Ale and Bennigan's, accounts for nearly half of
the company's total revenue.
   In the fiscal year ended May 31, restaurant sales slipped 5
percent as Burger King continued losing market share to rival
McDonald's Corp. despite a $200 million advertising campaign.
   ``Pillsbury's weakness has been more related to restaurants, and
if they got a guru in restaurants, they may have been better off,''
said Edward Froelich, an analyst at Pershing & Co.
   Echoing those concerns, Pillsbury stock fell $1.75 a share to
$35.12{ Monday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   But Smith is confident he can transfer his management skills to
a new industry.
   In a telephone interview, he said: ``I feel I have a very good
understanding of the operating fundamentals in the restaurant
business. I'm going to have an opportunity first hand to test
whether my judgments about what's important are right or not.''
   Smith follows in the footsteps of the hard-charging William H.
Spoor, who returned from retirement to run Pillsbury on an acting
basis nearly five months ago when former chairman John Stafford
resigned under pressure.
   Analysts have criticized Pillsbury, saying it lacked clear and
vital leadership in recent years.
   Its after-tax profit plummeted 62 percent in fiscal 1988 to
$69.3 million on sales of $6.2 billion, largely because of a
restructuring charge associated with the sale of its Godfather's
Pizza chain and a number of other restaurant operations and
consolidations.
   General Foods' performance under Smith is not immune to
criticism, either, some analysts say.
   Smith, a 22-year veteran of General Foods, counters that between
1984 and 1987, General Foods' growth rate went from ``relatively
flat to the point where we're growing better than 3 percent a
year.''
   As for management style, Smith said he typically tries to
``determine what the basic direction is we should be going and then
in a very aggressive and determined kind of way provide clear
direction to the organization and insist on commitment and
dedication.''
   Despite speculation on Wall Street, analysts are divided as to
how attractive a takeover candidate Pillsbury may be. Carnes, for
instance, said Pillsbury had ``too many wrecks in the ditch right
now.''
   Some experts have estimated the Burger King chain could fetch as
much as $1.5 billion if it were spun off as a separate company, but
Carnes said the chain would bring only about $900 million because
it was at least two years away from a turnaround.
   Smith said he would be surprised if selling Burger King ``made
any sense.''
   ``It has been very successful in the past, and I have to believe
there is room for a strong No. 2'' in the fast-food hamburger
business, he said.
   Philip Morris stated that Smith's position would not be filled.
The heads of the subisidary's domestic foods, coffee and Oscar
Mayer units would report directly to Hamish Maxwell, Philip Morris
chairman.
</TEXT>
