<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   07-26 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Car And Truck Sales Rise 5 Percent In Mid-July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto sales probably will continue at mid-July's
uneventful rate or slower through August and until the end of the
car model year, according to one industry analyst.
   Combined U.S. sales of domestically built cars and light trucks
rose 5 percent on a daily basis July 11-20 from the comparable
period of 1987, to 349,263 from 295,755, automakers reported Monday.
   There were nine selling days in this year's period and eight
last year.
   Sales moved at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 7.8 million,
trailing rates that frequently topped 8 million in the first half
of the year, but closer to the 7.7 million rate of mid-July 1987.
   Last August, dealers used buyer incentives to clear excess cars
from their crowded lots. After a hot-selling first half of 1988,
auto inventories are low, analyst Chris Cedergren said Monday.
   ``This year they won't need the fire sale approach,'' said
Cedergren, of J.D. Power & Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported increases in daily
car sales from July 11-20, offsetting a slight decline in General
Motors Corp. car sales.
   GM sold 106,791 cars in the nine-day period, up from 96,746 in
eight days of the comparable period last year. Daily sales were
down 1.9 percent.
   Ford sold 69,039 cars, up from 55,686 a year earlier, a 10.2
percent increase in daily sales. Chrysler sold 29,956 cars, up from
24,037, a 10.8 percent daily increase.
   GM sold 53,434 light trucks, up 7.7 percent on a daily sales
basis, and Chrysler sold 29,172, up 9.8 percent. Ford sold 45,426
light trucks, with the daily sales rate down 0.8 percent.
   ``It is an indication that finally sales are beginning to slow
down to more of a normal pace. It's a slight slowdown in the
marketplace, but still a pretty healthy rate,'' Cedergren said.
   Erratic sales last year exaggerate fluctuations among
manufacturers from 10-day period to period, he said. ``It all
depends who had incentive programs going last year and who has them
this year.''
   Overall, he said GM, with 49 percent of the market in
domestically made cars, has halted an erosion in its market share.
   Ford, with 31.7 percent, and Chrysler, with 13.7 percent, have
shown slight gains, partly at the expense of imports facing price
disadvantages because of changing exchange rates, Cedergren said.
   Sales of imported cars and trucks are reported at the end of
each month.
   Honda Motor Co. sold 6,344 of its U.S.-made cars in the mid-July
period, up from 5,469, a 3.1 percent daily sales gain. Nissan had a
0.6 percent gain, selling 3,376 U.S.-made cars, up from 2,984 a
year earlier.
   Toyota sold 1,745 domestically produced autos, up from 874 in a
period when its plant wasn't fully operational a year earlier.
   Mazda sold 690 U.S.-made cars. It did not begin domestic
manufacturing until September 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
